## Introduction: The Financial Bear — A Field Guide

### The Bear as Threat
- 84 million US equity shareholders alone; millions more globally whose financial futures can be "destroyed or seriously damaged" by bear markets
- Bear markets are **harder to recognize** than literal bears — and making noise won't scare them away
- The book was written when the March 2000 – late 2002 decline raised the unanswered question: new bull market, or **bounce in a longer bear**?
- Napier's answer (written ~2005): **we remain in a bear market**

### Why You Can't Just Wait It Out
- **Prof. Jeremy Siegel**: hold 17 years and you'll never lose money in real terms since 1802
- But average NYSE holding period (first half 2005) = **12 months**; 1900–2002 average = 18 months
- 20th century: real annual return on US equities was **negative in 35 of 100 years**; in 8 of those, negative return exceeded **20%**
- Implication: average investor encounters a bear every ~3 years; a particularly mean one every ~13 years
- Even with a 10-year horizon: **9 years of the past century** produced negative 10-year total real returns — "big bears tend to linger"
- Napier's judgment (2005): post-October 2002 rise is a **"false dawn"** in a longer bear market

### The Bull Case for Bears
- Alternative title considered: *How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Bear*
- Bear markets = lower prices; buying cheap in a bear, given long-term real returns, is "even more profitable" than avoiding them
- The book focuses on **four historically lucrative bottoms**: when equities were pushed well below fair value and rebound was imminent

> "You can observe a lot just by watching."
> — Yogi Berra (cited by Napier on observing bear market signals)

### Signals to Watch at the Bottom
- Low valuations, improved earnings, improving liquidity, **falling bond yields**, changes in market perception
- The guide identifies factors that have historically been **good markers** vs. those that were misleading
- Finance advantage over physics: "you don't need to provide the right answers, just better answers than most everyone else"

### The Problem with Efficient Markets
- **Henry Ford**: "history is more or less bunk" — but Ford meant *tradition* (extrapolation), which is dangerous
- **Harry M. Markowitz** (1952): *'Portfolio Selection'* in *Journal of Finance* → academic assault on the value of history
- Assumed market efficiency → **efficient market hypothesis** emerged; by 1970s, Wall Street endorsed the view that prices reflect all information
- 1974 crash forced practitioners to embrace academic risk-management → "new Wall Street" built on mathematical modelling
- New Wall Street failures: 1987 portfolio insurance debacle, Orange County and Gibson Greetings derivative losses, **LTCM** implosion 1998, dot-com bust 1995–2002
- Conclusion: new Wall Street "no more successful in protecting clients' interests than the failed 'improvised strategies' of 1974"

### Behavioural Economics as Vindication
- **Daniel Kahneman** and **Vernon I. Smith** won 2002 Nobel in economics for integrating psychology into economic decision-making under uncertainty
- Kahneman's first article on the concept appeared in **1974** — just as Wall Street was embracing efficiency
- Nobel Committee had previously honored efficiency acolytes: **Markowitz, Merton Miller, William Sharpe** (1990); **Myron Scholes, Robert Merton** (1997)
- Awarding Kahneman recognized that human judgement, even in aggregate, does not produce efficiency
- Financial history = empirical study of human decision-making under uncertainty; "a guide to understanding the future"

### Methodology: The Wall Street Journal Archive
- Napier analyzed **~70,000 WSJ articles** written in the two months either side of the **four great bear market bottoms**
- Press coverage of stock market dates to the railway boom ~1850 — reliable financial press since then
- Goal: accurate picture of bear-market bottom based on **contemporary opinion** (not hindsight)
- What emerges: remarkable **similarity across all four bottoms** → a replicable set of signals

### Selecting the Four Bottoms

#### The "Hindsight Value" Method
- **Andrew Smithers and Stephen Wright** (*Valuing Wall Street*, 2000): defined **"hindsight value"** — average of 40 discrete subsequent return periods (1- to 40-year horizons)
- Best three years to buy US equities by this measure: **1920, 1932, 1948** (year-end); adjusted for intra-year: **August 1921, July 1932, June 1949**
- Fourth period, **1982**, added by Napier with "good reasons" — top four confirmed 23 years later

#### The q Ratio as Valuation Tool
- **q ratio**: stock-market valuation of a company relative to **replacement value of its assets**
- "Fair value" in this book = q ratio at its geometric mean
- The four periods studied are the **only occasions** when equities traded at more than a **70% discount to replacement value**
- **Cyclically adjusted PE** (Robert Shiller / Yale) also useful; Smithers/Wright found **q ratio** to be the more accurate predictor of superior future returns

### Book Structure
- Each period covered under:
  1. *"The road to [year]"* — backstory, forces driving prices to extreme discount
  2. *"Structure of the markets"* — important structural differences in each era (e.g., major financial institutions not listed on NYSE in 1921)
  3. *"At the bottom with the bear"* — signals marking the end of the bear market
- Extended attention to **1929–32**: unique in financial history; often mistakenly treated as the *typical* bear market
- Literary epigraphs throughout from writers living amid the turbulence of each era (Fitzgerald, Farrell, Vidal, Updike)

### Literary Characters as Market Proxies
- **Nick Carraway** (Fitzgerald): quit Wall Street in 1922, heading west just as the greatest US bull market began
- **Studs Lonigan** (Farrell): invested nest egg in 1931 at worst possible moment; dead before July 1932 bottom
- **Robert Holton** (Vidal): stayed on Wall Street in late 1940s — benefited from one of the longest bull markets in US history
- **Harry 'Rabbit' Angstrom** (Updike): bought gold/krugerrands almost at gold's all-time high
- The four bear-market years also mark four societal transitions: 1921 = birth of consumer society; 1932 = birth of big government; 1949 = birth of military-industrial complex; 1982 = rebirth of free markets

> "Shoot the bastard."
> — David Hempleman-Adams (polar explorer), when asked what to do when confronted by a bear; Napier notes guns offer no protection from the financial bear

<!-- pp. 41-60 -->

## Part I: August 1921 — Introduction

- By August 1921, the DJIA had returned to its level of **22 years prior**; blue chip railroad shares were back to 1881 prices
- Equities were trading at a **70% discount to replacement value** of their assets
- By September 1929, equities were close to a **100% premium** to replacement value; DJIA had risen almost fivefold
- Central question: What changed in 1921, and how could investors have anticipated the bottom?

> *"'Can't repeat the past?' he cried incredulously. 'Why of course you can!'"*
> — F. Scott Fitzgerald, *The Great Gatsby* (epigraph)

---

## The Road to August 1921: The Course of the Dow, 1896–1921

### Market Context: The Two Indexes

- In 1921, no single representative market index existed — investors tracked two distinct sectors:
  - **Dow Jones & Co. 20 Industrial Stock Average**
  - **Dow Jones & Co. 20 Railroad Stock Average**
- 1896: industrials = 48% of NYSE volume; railroads = 52%
- NYSE membership prices had fallen 41% over the prior decade — reflecting depressed market activity post-1893-95 panic

### DJIA Background
- **DJIA** first published May 1896; originally 12 component companies; price-weighted (not market cap)
- **Charles Dow** created original index in 1884, dominated by railroad shares
- Expanded to 20 stocks in October 1916; to current 30 in October 1928
- Book uses DJIA as "the market" throughout; S&P Composite used only for valuation/earnings data where quality is superior

### Merger Mania & Railroad Bull Market (1896–1902)
- **JP Morgan** amalgamated bankrupt railroads after the 1893-95 panic, reviving the sector
- Business mergers surged: 69 in 1897 → **1,200+ in 1899**
- Merger-driven bull market in railroads (excess capacity removed) far outpaced industrials 1896–1902
- Industrials' share of NYSE turnover didn't return to the 1896 level until **1911**

### Trust-Busting Shift (1901–1914)
- **William McKinley** assassination (1901) → **Theodore Roosevelt** ascendancy
- Roosevelt's trust-busting hit mature railroads harder than growing industrials
- By 1911, industrials exceeded railroad activity for the first time
- Activity roughly equal between the two sectors until WWI created dramatic divergence

### WWI's Structural Transformation of Markets
- By war's end, **industrials = 80%+ of NYSE volume**; most railroads had been nationalised
- Market reaction to **Archduke Franz Ferdinand** assassination (28 June 1914) was initially calm
- On 25 July 1914, Austria-Hungary and Germany refused the six-power conference → war appeared inevitable
- Investors feared gold outflow (US was a debtor nation), tightening domestic liquidity
- NYSE closed 31 July 1914 (DJIA at 71.42; railroad avg at 89.41) — forced by European exchange closures
- Market reopened 12 December 1914 with restrictions; industrials had fallen **32%** from July level; railroads rose slightly to 90.21
- Instead of feared capital outflow, **funds poured INTO the US** as warring nations bought war materials

### The 1916 Profit Boom — A Stunning Fact
- Industrial profits boomed as "**war brides**" — companies with huge European war orders — surged
- 1916 corporate earnings were so exceptional that **nominal profits did not exceed the 1916 level until 1949**
- In **real terms**, 1916 earnings weren't exceeded until December 1955
- As late as January 1992, S&P Composite real earnings were still barely above (4.7%) the 1916 level
- Railroads: nationalized at **noon on 28 December 1917** — converted equity into de facto bonds (fixed dividend based on pre-nationalization average earnings)
- With railroad returns constrained, investor focus shifted entirely to industrial stocks
- By the 1919 bull market peak, railroad turnover = only **13.8%** of total trading volume

### The 1917 Bear Market
- 1917 downturn driven by: US entering the war, early peace prospects, government price controls, railroads denied ICC rate increases, rising costs, excess profits tax, increased government debt issuance
- Markets traded sideways through 1918 (war of attrition)
- Industrials bull market resumed 1919, hitting all-time high **November 1919**

---

## Living with the Fed — A Whole New Ball Game (I)

### The Fed as Unknown Variable (1921 Context)
- **Federal Reserve System** established 1914 — brand new institution, unfamiliar to investors
- Analogous for modern investor to imagining the Fed being abolished tomorrow
- Structure: **Federal Reserve Board** + 12 **Federal Reserve Banks**
  - Reserve Banks could set their own discount rates (subject to Board review)
  - Open market operations: NO Board oversight → high autonomy for individual Reserve Banks
  - **NY Fed** became de facto driver of monetary policy given its location

### Why the Fed Was Created
- **1895 crisis**: Only a loan from **JP Morgan** and **Rothschilds** prevented exhaustion of US gold reserves and end of gold standard
- **1907 panic**: JP Morgan again brokered a rescue of key financial institutions
- Both crises triggered by public shift from bank deposits to cash, causing liquidity collapses
- **President Andrew Jackson** had vetoed renewal of the Second Bank of the US in 1832 — leaving a 80-year gap without a central bank
- Wilson's Democrats created the Fed despite significant political opposition
- Mandate: *"To provide...an elastic currency, to afford means of rediscounting commercial paper, to establish more effective supervision of banking"*

> *"The most detailed knowledge of the actual trade of the country...would not enable any man or set of men to adjust, and keep always adjusted, the right proportion of circulating medium in a country to the wants of trade."*
> — Bullion Committee report to British House of Commons, 1810 (the pre-Fed orthodoxy)

### Gold Standard Mechanics (Sidebar)
- **Gold standard**: bank notes redeemable for gold at fixed price; currencies fixed relative to each other
- BOP surplus → more buyers of currency → more money created → higher prices → eroded competitiveness → BOP moves to deficit (self-correcting mechanism)
- Post-WWI variant: **gold exchange standard** — some authorities held other currencies (themselves gold-redeemable) as reserves

### The Elastic Currency & Real Bills Doctrine
- Fed created money via: receipt of gold, **rediscounting** eligible commercial bank paper, discounting foreign trade acceptances, open market purchases of government securities
- Ability to create money via rediscounting = **real bills criterion**
- Apparent conflict: gold standard dictates money stock needed to balance payments; real bills doctrine doesn't limit quantity of money
- **Milton Friedman** and **Anna Jacobson Schwarz** argued contradiction was "more apparent than real" — gold standard governs long-term money stock; real bills governs currency/deposit split

### The Fed's Actual Behavior: Elastic Currency Abused
- From Fed creation (Nov 1914) to June 1920, "elastic" money was **stretched and the money stock more than doubled**
- Pre-US war entry (to April 1917): Fed played minor role — money growth driven by **gold inflows** from belligerent nations purchasing US goods
  - US international investment position: deficit of **$3.7 billion in 1914** → surplus of similar size by **1919**
  - Fed had no assets to sterilize the gold inflow — could only stretch, not tighten
- US entry into war (April 1917): gold flow ceased; Fed money-creation became primary mechanism
  - Fed money = 21% of high-powered money in April 1917 → **59% by November 1918**
  - Member banks lent to customers for government bond purchases, then **rediscounted** those loans at Reserve Banks — war finance through the elastic currency
  - This was NOT the purpose the system was designed for (panic prevention), but it worked: US remained on gold standard unlike during Civil War

### The Postwar Bubble Setup (1919)
- After Armistice, expected economic contraction began **August 1918** but ran its course by **March 1919**
- Fed kept interest rates low through 1919 (well below market rates) to fund government floating debt and prop up government bond prices (key bank collateral)
- Stretched elastic currency as much in the postwar period as during the war itself
- Result: **speculative bull market** in industrial equities and commodities raged through 1919
- Investors playing by old rules (wartime inflation → postwar deflation under gold standard) **missed the 1919 bull market**
- Fed credit: $0 in Nov 1914 → **~$3 billion by end of 1919** (~4% of GDP)
- Many investors wrongly concluded Fed had permanently circumvented the gold standard's deflationary mechanism

### The Statutory Limit — The Pin that Burst the Bubble
- Legislation required Fed to hold: **40% gold reserves against notes**, **35% legal tender reserves against net deposits**
- Fed's own internal minimum: **40% total reserves against net deposits + note liability**
- Reserve ratio fell from **48.1% in December 1918** to **42.7% in January 1920** — approaching the limit
- Call money rates: **15% by June 1919**, rising to **30% by November** — money market already warning
- Fed acted November/December 1919: raised discount rate to **4.75%**, then **6.0% by January/February 1920**
- This forced tightening — driven by the reserve ratio approaching its statutory floor — was the proximate trigger for the 1919-21 bear market

### Price Level Uncertainty: The Core Investor Problem
- Under gold standard, bear markets were normally associated with: loss of competitiveness, deteriorating external accounts, tightening liquidity, economic contraction, **declining price level**
- Wholesale prices rose **147%** from June 1914 to May 1920 — largest since the Civil War
- By how much would prices need to fall to restore US competitiveness?
  - French franc, mark: down **60%+** vs dollar from start of 1919 to start of 1921
  - Sterling: down **almost 30%** vs dollar — all with high domestic inflation too
  - Made assessing the required US price adjustment extremely difficult
- Figure 6 data (Friedman & Schwartz): Wholesale price rises by period:
  - US neutrality (Jun 1914–Mar 1917): **+65%**
  - War (Mar 1917–Nov 1918): **+23%**
  - Peace (Nov 1919–May 1920): **+22%**

### GDP Reality Check
- GDP data (Nathan Balke & Robert Gordon, NBER): 1914–1919 nominal GDP +123%; real GDP +25%
- Real growth of **1916 alone** accounts for **70% of all real growth** in the five-year period 1915–1919
- Key investor questions postwar:
  - Was the 1916 war-production boom a permanent surge in US share of world trade, or one-time?
  - If one-time, didn't peacetime augur a **major contraction in profitability**?
  - Should stocks be valued on wartime profitability or pre-war profitability?
- Gold inflow data (US Treasury): Gold stock grew from $1,526m (1914) to $2,873m (1918), then fell as gold left postwar

<!-- pp. 61-80 -->

## The Inflationary Alternative: Germany vs. the Gold Standard Nations

### Postwar Policy Divergence

- US investors in 1921 had to consider not just domestic deflation
  but the alternative path taken by Germany, Russia, Poland,
  Hungary, and Austria — nations free from the **gold standard**
- These countries printed money to stimulate growth and avoid
  deflation; the policy worked initially but destroyed capital
- **Gold-to-note coverage ratios** (Fig. 8) tell the story:
  Germany fell from 54% (1914) to just 1.5% (1921);
  Austria to 0.01%; contrast with US rising from 18% to 93%

### Germany's Inflationary Boom — Then Catastrophe

- In 1921 Germany had 29% wholesale price inflation vs.
  24% deflation in France, 26% in UK, 11% decline in US
- German economy avoided recession entirely; stock market boomed:
  **Frankfurter Zeitung** average +40% March–August 1921
- **Berlin Stock Exchange** suspended trading in Sept 1921 —
  speculative volumes exceeded members' capacity to handle

> "Early in July paper marks began to show such a tendency toward
> depreciation that the investing classes in Germany took alarm and
> there was a mad rush to invest their paper in industrial and other
> securities before currency dropped further."
> — *Wall Street Journal*, 9 September 1921

- German government estimated ~$1 billion in German bank notes
  held by foreign investors; mark had fallen from US8¢ to US1¢
- Anonymous German banker at Brussels Conference, warned Germany
  was headed for the abyss, replied:

> 'We do not care about the advice of the British. They are only
> thinking of themselves. Perhaps we are headed for the abyss, but
> then we will drag France down with us, and that means the
> bankruptcy of all Europe.'
> — *Wall Street Journal*, 3 October 1921

- **German Wholesale Price Index**: 152 (1918) → 1,338 (1921) →
  23,927 (1922) → **11,634,000,000,000** (1923)
- Peak monthly inflation: Germany 3 million%; Russia 213%;
  Poland 275%; Austria 134%; Hungary 98%
- Key lesson: what appeared a positive policy vs. deflation in 1921
  led to **almost complete loss of capital** for equity investors

### Implications for US Investors

- US investors couldn't simply assume gold-standard deflation was
  the only outcome — Germany's path was a live alternative
- If Germany, Russia, Poland, Austria continued inflationary path,
  their real exchange rates would fall, stealing US market share,
  making US economic adjustment larger than expected
- Without gold standard anchor, **calculating the price bottom
  was considerably more complicated**

---

## Structure of the Market in 1921

### The Stock Market in 1921

- **NYSE** had 382 companies with quoted stocks, 586 total issues
  (185 preferred) — vs. 2,500+ today; still broad sectoral range
- Common stocks considered **speculative** — institutional investors
  focused primarily on the bond market
- New stock issuance in 1921: railroads <1%; balance split equally
  between public utilities and industrials

### Key Sectors

- **Railroads**: NYSE since 1830 (Mohawk & Hudson); plagued by
  excessive competition despite numerous 19th-century bankruptcies;
  key names: Atchison Topeka & Santa Fe, Baltimore & Ohio,
  Canadian Pacific, Union Pacific, NY Central
- **Steel**: dominated by **US Steel** (assembled by JP Morgan via
  Carnegie Steel); working capital almost double the other 12
  listed companies combined; capacity utilisation fell to **20%** by 1921
- **Automobiles**: Ford produced ~half of US autos but didn't list
  until 1956; **General Motors**, Studebaker, Pierce Arrow,
  Willys-Overland, Republic Motors available on market
- **Oils**: dominated by former **Standard Oil** trust fragments —
  13 listed companies including Standard Oil of CA, NJ, Ohio;
  independent sector focused on Mexico (Associated Oil, Houston
  Oil, Mexican Petroleum, Sinclair Oil)
- **Rubber**: Goodyear vulcanisation + auto boom drove sector;
  listed: Goodrich BF, US Rubber
- **Mining**: copper price collapsed from wartime highs back to
  1911 levels; 12¢/lb in 1921 vs. 15.5¢ pre-war avg; only 8 of
  leading US copper mines still producing; listed: Anaconda,
  Homestake, Dome
- **Sugar**: refined sugar crashed from 26¢/lb (1920) to 5.5¢ (1921);
  **National City Bank** became one of Cuba's largest sugar
  producers via seizure of collateral on bad loans; Cuba output
  = one-third of that nation's economy
- **Tobacco**: post-breakup of **American Tobacco** trust;
  cigarette boom shifting consumers from loose tobacco;
  key names: Lorillard, Liggett & Myers
- **Retail**: Sears-Roebuck, Woolworth's, Montgomery Ward,
  May Department Stores

### The Curb Market

- Until 28 June 1921 the **curb market** operated literally on
  the sidewalk at Broad Street — home to companies that would
  become global successes: British American Tobacco, Gillette,
  Philip Morris, **RCA** (Radio Corporation of America)
- Historical curiosities: Wright Aeronautical Co (Orville Wright),
  Savage Arms Company, National Acme Co

### Railroad Performance in the Bear Market

- Nationalized railroads missed the postwar commodity/equity boom
  (dividends pegged at historic levels by government fiat)
- But in the 1920-21 bear market, **railroad index decline was
  only half that of the DJIA** — guaranteed dividends provided
  downside cushion (Fig. 11)
- Broad **S&P Composite** and preferred shares also outperformed
  the narrow 20-stock DJIA during the downturn

---

## The Bond Market in 1921

### A Long Bear Market Since 1899

- The 1919-21 equity bear was intensified by a **long bear market
  in bonds that had begun in 1899**
- Federal debt was artificially scarce (1900-16): debt-to-GDP
  averaged just 4.2%; legislation required banks to hold govt bonds
  as security for banknotes → 80% of $965m govt debt was pledged
- Result: **corporate bond market** was the prime investment medium
  — nearly 20x larger than the entire US govt bond market pre-war
- **Average yield of prime corporate bonds** (Fig. 12) rose
  steadily from ~3.2% (1900) to ~5.2% (1921)
- Jan 1917–May 1920: corporate bond prices fell 23.6% — more
  than half the total 1899-1920 decline crammed into 3 years
  (worst bond bear since Civil War)

### WWI Transforms the Bond Market

- US entry into WWI flipped Federal debt from illiquid/overpriced
  to the most liquid, widely-held instrument in the country
- Federal debt rose from **2.7% of GDP (1916) to 32.9% (1921)**
  — the largest debt load in US history, edging out the 31.0%
  Civil War peak of 1866
- Federal debt: $24.3 billion by 1920, surpassing the $18.0 billion
  corporate bond market in size
- **Liberty Bond** issues (1917-18): ~18 million subscribers out of
  a US population of just over 100 million
- Liberty Bonds = 71% of Federal debt outstanding in 1921;
  Victory Loans = 16%; first Liberty Bond yielded 3.5%,
  fourth yielded 4.25%
- In the 1920-21 bond bear market, **~80% of original Liberty Bond
  holders sold out**

### Bond Market Structure in 1921

- Average daily NYSE bond turnover: ~$10 million vs. $36 million
  for stocks; Federal debt consistently >50% and sometimes
  two-thirds of bond trading volume
- Miscellaneous (non-Federal) NYSE bonds: 144 rail issues, 63
  industrials, 41 government & city bonds (Fig. 14)
- Total US corporate bonds outstanding Dec 1920: 6,000+ issues,
  10x the number of NYSE-listed stocks (Fig. 15)
  - Railroads: 1,700 issues / $9.6bn
  - Public Utilities: 3,795 issues / $6.1bn
  - Industrials: 868 issues / $2.4bn
- **Foreign sovereign bonds** listed in NY: Argentina, Belgium,
  Brazil, Canada, Chile, Cuba, Denmark, France, Japan, Mexico,
  Norway, Sweden, UK, Uruguay, etc. — sign of US rivaling UK as
  global financial center
- UK was largest single foreign bond issuer on NYSE: $450m face
  value; had to liquidate US investments AND still borrow
- **Mexico** was the junk sovereign: price in low 30s, in default
  since 1914
- **Imperial Russian Government bonds** trading at ~20 on the curb
  market — unlikely to be redeemed absent restoration of monarchy

---

## At the Bottom with the Bear — Summer 1921

### Undervaluation: Price Fall vs. Earnings Stagnation

- Bear market bottoms are not just about price declines —
  a key element is that stock prices **fail to keep pace with
  economic and earnings growth for a prolonged period before**
  the bear market even begins
- This "pre-bear undervaluation" is a feature of all US bear
  market bottoms except 1929-32
- **DJIA on 24 August 1921: 63.9** — a level first reached on
  27 January 1899; essentially no price progress in two decades
- Yet the US economy transformed massively 1899-1920 (Fig. 17):
  nominal GDP +383%, real GDP +88%, real GDP per capita +33%,
  steel production +320%, railroad track +57%, auto output from
  $4m to $1.6bn, telephones 1m → 13.3m, exports +563%

### The Cowles Index and Earnings Stagnation

- **Alfred Cowles** (1938): a private investor so frustrated by
  expert incompetence that he spent years building a broader
  stock index; his index became the **S&P Composite Index**
- Cowles' broad index confirms the DJIA story: August 1921 market
  at a similar level to June 1881 — 40 years of zero price progress
- **Listed sector earnings grew only 130% from 1881** vs. nominal
  GDP growth of 732% and real GDP growth of 435%
- S&P earnings per share peaks and troughs:
  - 1880 peak: 123; 1894 trough: 40
  - 1916 peak: 383; 1921 trough: 73
- Valuation ambiguity: using depressed 1921 earnings → PE = 24.5x;
  using peak 1916 earnings → PE = 4.6x; using normalized
  1922-26 average → January 1921 PE was **7x**
- Core finding: **corporate earnings growth had massively lagged
  GDP growth** — listed companies failed to translate the economy's
  extraordinary expansion into shareholder returns
- This earnings failure is a key reason stocks were deeply
  undervalued at the 1921 bottom even before the price decline

<!-- pp. 81-100 -->

## Valuation at the 1921 Bottom

### PE Compression and Cheap Equities

- **Market PE** had declined to 7x by January 1921 using 1922-26 average as normalised earnings
- Cyclically-adjusted PE peaked ~25x circa 1901, then fell steadily to ~5x by 1921 (Figure 20)
- Despite depressed 1921 earnings showing PE of 25.2x on current earnings, stocks were objectively cheap on any normalised basis
- Most dramatic evidence: **cumulative retained earnings per share** of listed industrials averaged $48 from 1915-1920 — the same as the average price of an industrial share in 1921
- Many companies selling below **working capital**; shares of copper mines below cost to equip the mines

> "…the capitalisation of scores of concerns today is selling below working capital. In the case of many companies the shares are selling for less than the value of the plants… The shares of a large number of industrial corporations are selling at one-third their respective intrinsic values." — Anonymous banker, WSJ, 19 September 1921

- Investors chose to ignore this earnings power; rise in government debt from $1.1 billion (1915) to $24 billion crowded out equity investment and distracted capital

### Forty Years of Stagnation

- **S&P Composite unchanged from 1881 to 1921** — zero capital return over 40 years
- Reinvested dividends did exceed prime commercial paper returns, but only marginally
- Stock investors obtained only marginally higher total return than holders of highest-quality fixed-interest securities
- Cause: listed-sector earnings growth lagged the economy AND valuations (PE) almost halved over the period

### Q Ratio at the Bottom

- **Q ratio** (market price / replacement value of assets) peaked at 1.12x in December 1905 — also the market peak
- At year-end 1921: q = 0.35x
- Given significant rally from August to December 1921, the August bottom implied q ≈ **0.28x** — equities trading at >70% discount to replacement value of assets
- Equities had become cheap by August 1921, but the process had been developing for ~40 years, at least since the 1907 bear market

---

## Good News and the Bear

> *"It was the hour of a profound human change, and excitement was generating in the air."*
> — F. Scott Fitzgerald, *The Great Gatsby*

### The "Wait for Bad News" Fallacy Debunked

- Common advice: buy stocks when all news is bad, use the press as indicator of maximum pessimism
- **This advice was wrong for 1921**: the WSJ in summer 1921 was full of bullish forecasts from businessmen, Fed officials, and politicians — all accurately predicting the end of the bear
- An investor waiting for absence of good news would have missed the entire **Roaring Twenties** bull market
- The DJIA bottomed **24 August 1921**; the **NBER** dates the economic trough as July 1921 — improvement in economy coincided with improvement in equities

### WSJ Chronology of Bullish Signals (June–October 1921)

- **25 June**: Steel makers taking a more cheerful view; consumers will eventually buy steel
- **27 June**: Fed Reserve Bulletin declares domestic business has begun to show a turn for the better
- **27 June**: DR Crissinger (Comptroller of the Currency) predicts 5% rates on commercial paper soon
- **27 June**: Harry F. Sinclair (Sinclair Consolidated Oil) — "We have hit the bottom"
- **14 July**: Secretary Hoover declares business has turned the corner of depression
- **15 July**: Commission houses note market discounts 6 months ahead; if business picks up by Nov/Dec, Wall Street will discount it very soon
- **18 July**: Ford, Studebaker, Dodge running nearly full; noticeable improvement in motor sales
- **1 August**: US Steel quarterly earnings $10M better than expected; Bethlehem Steel dividends fully earned
- **1 August** (Judge Gary, chairman of US Steel): 'The biggest business this country has ever witnessed' is coming
- **1 August**: Federal Reserve Board review notes retail demand as good or better than prior year; excellent food crop returns most hopeful feature
- **2 August**: National Bank of Republic of Chicago — downward swing of prices nearing end; commodities reaching level where forward commitments may be safely undertaken
- **5 August**: Many brokerage houses advising purchase of stocks; tendency upward for remainder of year
- **9 August**: **Benjamin Strong** (Governor, Federal Reserve Bank of New York) — "We have entered the cycles of recovery. One of the best symptoms of recovery is the easier rates for money."
- **24 August: DJIA bottoms**
- **1 September**: Rural bankers express astonishment at pessimism prevailing in Wall Street
- **22 September**: Secretary of Labor Davis — "the greatest era of prosperity the United States has ever known near at hand"
- **23 September**: WPG Harding (Governor, Federal Reserve Board) — if lessons of past two years remembered, next prosperity will be longer and subsequent reaction far less severe
- **2 October**: Harvard University Committee on Economics Research — trough of business depression clearly passed; copper, tin, lead, rubber, cotton have recovered
- **21 October**: Vice President Coolidge — "a definite turning of the tide in the business and industrial activities of the country"

### Key Insight: Bears Bottom with Good News

- **Extreme undervaluation periods are precisely when investors should NOT wait for an absence of good news**
- In 1921, economic recovery and equity market recovery coincided — they were not sequential
- The bottom was memorable for investors' failure to *react* to good news, not for an absence of it
- 1921 represented one of only three such extreme undervaluation episodes in the 20th century

---

## Price Stability & the Bear

> *"A phrase began to beat in my ears with a sort of heady excitement: 'There are only the pursued, the pursuing, the busy, and the tired.'"*
> — F. Scott Fitzgerald, *The Great Gatsby*

### Price Stabilisation as the Key Signal

- The most accurate forecasters of the 1921 bear market bottom were those who focused on **the change in the trend of prices**
- Under the **gold standard**, the contraction mechanism worked as follows:
  1. Deflation reduced domestic prices → improved competitiveness
  2. Improved competitiveness → improvement in external accounts
  3. Gold flowed back into the US → easing of liquidity
  4. Liquidity easing → economic recovery
- **Price stabilisation** was the practical signal that this mechanism had completed its work
- Without knowing the "correct" price level, investors could use stabilisation as evidence the adjustment was over

### The Scale of 1921 Deflation

- 1921 was **very probably the sharpest price decline in US history**
- **Nine major economies** suffered their worst annual deflation of the 20th Century simultaneously in 1921: Australia, Canada, France, Netherlands, South Africa, Sweden, Switzerland, UK, and US
- Unskilled labour fell from 60¢/hour at peak to 25¢/hour by summer 1921
- Price declines from 1920 peak to 1921 lows (Figure 24):
  - Farm products: -87.7% (still 18% above 1913)
  - Metals and metal products: -78.9% (still 20% above 1913)
  - Finished steel: -78.4% (still 37% above 1913)
  - Food: -72.2% (still 52% above 1913)
  - All commodities: -69.8% (still 52% above 1913)
- Most prices did NOT have to deflate all the way to 1913 levels — a concern investors had in 1920

### Demand Response Confirmed the Bottom

- The decisive signal was not just price stability but **demand responding to lower prices**
- Automobile industry (increasingly important) saw demand improving from early summer in response to price cuts
- **Phonograph companies** facing "buyers' strike" cut prices by a third → considerable stimulation of high-priced model sales

> "The moral seems to be that the public has the power and the will to buy when it can get a bargain."

- Coal operators refusing to accept current spot prices for September delivery — believed prices might rise (supply-side confirmation)
- Iron prices advancing first in Chicago, then spreading nationally — producers had been selling below cost, stocks run down to impossibility of filling orders
- As commodity prices firmed one by one, investor confidence spread that the list would grow

### Collateral Damage of Deflation

- Even investors who had *anticipated* postwar deflation couldn't fully protect themselves
- One broker expecting deflation bought $15,000 of diamonds in 1918 → by 1921 pawnshops would only lend 10% of purchase price; forced to sell for $6,000
- "Even the girls' best friend had failed as a store of value in a deflationary period"

---

## Liquidity and the Bear

> *"I bought a dozen volumes on banking and credit and investment securities… promising to unfold the shining secrets that only Midas and Morgan and Maecenas knew."*
> — F. Scott Fitzgerald, *The Great Gatsby*

### Gold Accumulation and Monetary Potential

- WWI produced major wealth shift: by 1921 the US held **one-third of the world's monetary gold supply**
- This gold, along with Federal Reserve money, was the dominant component of **high-powered money**
- Many pundits believed forecasting the turn in the money/credit cycle was the key to predicting economic and equity recovery
- WSJ summer 1921 coverage frequently cited easier money as a bullish signal alongside price stability

### Credit Lags and the Difficulty of Reading Liquidity

- **Critical asymmetry**: price indices peaked and fell sharply, but bank credit lagged significantly
- Prices in textiles began declining as early as Feb/March 1920; general price level didn't fall until 3 months later
- **Credit volume peaked in October 1920** — 5 months after general price peak
- By summer 1921: Department of Labor index 46% below maximum, commodity index 58% below maximum, but national bank loans only **14% below maximum**
- Commercial-bank loans had grown 18% year-on-year in second half of 1919; still +8% YoY in first half of 1920
- The rapid rise in the discount rate — from **4% in November 1919 to 7% in June 1920** (a level not surpassed until 1973) — took time to affect banks
- **Key question of 1921**: did the gap between price deflation and credit contraction mean further credit/price deflation to come, or was the relationship between credit and price level not as direct as assumed?

### Federal Reserve Reserve Ratio as Key Indicator

- The **Federal Reserve reserve ratio** was identified as the most important monetary indicator
- Fed law required: 40% gold reserve against Federal Reserve notes in circulation; 35% cash against net deposits
- Monitoring the reserve ratio was how investors assessed the Fed's capacity and willingness to ease money
- The study of the **Fed balance sheet** — particularly the reserve ratio — was the practical tool for assessing the credit cycle

> "The Reserve ratio itself is the most important indicator… The Federal Reserve law requires Federal Reserve banks to carry a gold reserve of 40% against Federal Reserve notes in actual circulation and 35% cash against net [deposits]."

<!-- pp. 101-120 -->

## Chapter 2 (continued): 1921 Bear Market Bottom — Monetary Signals & Market Psychology

### The Reserve Ratio as a Misleading Signal

- The **reserve ratio** was widely cited as "the most important indicator" by the WSJ
- When the combined ratio fell to ~40%, banks contracted loans → lower prices → gold inflows → ratio improved
- The first rate cut came in May 1921 when the reserve ratio had risen to **56.4%** (highest since Aug 1918)
- That discount rate cut came **three months before the equity market bottomed** — DJIA fell another 20% in the interim
- Key problem: the Fed was NOT steering policy by its own balance sheet mechanics; it was making **subjective judgments** about appropriate price-level deflation — waiting specifically for wage rates to fall before easing
- Investors who read the Fed's balance sheet for monetary easing signals were **misdirected**
- The elastic currency (invented to prevent financial collapse) had been used 1917-19 to finance the government and was now being used to manage the economy — making it inherently unpredictable as a signal

### Market Interest Rates Also Misleading

- Market rates had declined significantly from 1920 to 1921 **without halting the bear market**
- June 1920: call-money rate ranged 10–14%, some rates as high as 30%
- August 1921: call money at 5%, time money at 6% — yet the stock market continued to fall
- By 28 July, call rates were at lows not seen since November 1919 — stocks still declining
- **Key insight:** investors who focused on **price stability** (not interest rates or Fed balance sheet) were better able to gauge the turning point

### Broad Money (M2) Also Unreliable

- Nominal M2 showed no improvement until mid-1922 — well after the equity bottom
- Inflation-adjusted M2 showed improvement in April–May 1921 — but this signaled a buy before the final 20%+ decline in the DJIA
- Credit growth: commercial bank lending continued expanding long after economic contraction began; total loans actually fell 5.5% from June 1921 to June 1922 — while the economy expanded 7% real and the DJIA rose 36%
- **Conclusion:** watching credit growth numbers was useless for finding the 1921 bottom

### Why the Banking System Survived 1920-21 (Unlike 1929-33)

- The key structural difference: US commercial banks entered 1919-21 deflation in a **highly liquid position**
- **Chase National Bank** (4th largest US bank), balance sheet 30 June 1920:
  - Cash/Fed Reserve: 24% of assets
  - Bills discounted: 24%
  - Time loans: 20%
  - Demand loans: 12%
  - US Bonds: 5%
- Public faith in the banking system held in 1920-21 → deposits increased; in 1929-33 that faith collapsed
- Long experience with deflationary periods under the **gold standard** had trained banks to maintain liquid balance sheets

---

### The Bulls and the Bear: Day-by-Day Chronicle, June–October 1921

> *There is no confusion like the confusion of a simple mind, and as we drove away Tom was feeling the hot whips of panic.*
> — F. Scott Fitzgerald, *The Great Gatsby* (epigraph to this section)

Napier reconstructs investor sentiment through WSJ commentary from 25 June to 24 October 1921 to show what it actually felt like to navigate the bottom in real time.

#### Late June — Early Bullish Stirrings, Bears Still Dominant

- **25 June**: Consensus market "acting as though it wants to go up." Easy money shifting sentiment from bear to bull
- **28 June**: Analysts say it's unreasonable to judge stocks on 1921 earnings — **"It is the balance sheet that is even more important in times like these"**
- **29 June**: Bears bolder — "urgent liquidation is over... market gives every indication." But bears refuse to regard any development as constructive; pessimism slowly giving way to optimism

#### July — Exhaustion, Apathy, and Technical Signals

- **6–7 July**: Market holds up on violent break in **Mexican Petroleum** — failure to go down proved market was "so oversold that the short interest was serving as a cushion." Largest single-day recovery of the year recorded on 7 July as shorts covered
- **13 July (Hornblower & Weeks)**: "Stocks more recently do not appear to be in plentiful supply for lending purposes… some constructive developments might easily be reflected in higher quotations"
- **13 July**: Broker holdings of **US Steel** had been 58% at Dec 1916, fallen to 23% by end June 1921 — signaling distribution to public/long-term investors
- **15 July**: Floor traders not even coming into the office — complete apathy
- **18 July**: "Dullest market in three years… absolutely no public participation… acknowledged that the big money has already been made on the short side"
- **20 July**: Industrial preferred stocks yielding 7–10% while money available at 6% — clear value
- **22 July**: Lowering of rediscount rate did not stimulate any interest. Big short interest in steel
- **28 July (Hornblower & Weeks)**: "The obvious seldom happens in a professional market at the time when expected"

#### August — Approaching the Bottom

- **1 August**: American Telephone $90M offering very successful. Brokerages bare of customers
- **2 August**: **United Fruit** insiders buying on all dips despite bear raids
- **3 August**: Broker loans lowest in ~8 years — contracted from $1.25B to $500K. Daily call market volume collapsed from $45M (1919 peak) to $10M
- **5 August**: Only 900,000 shares of Steel held by Wall Street vs. 2,500,000 "a few years ago" — massive distribution complete
- **9 August**: "There is no body of small investors who provide market support in the darkest hour"
- **10 August (anonymous broker)**: "I have clients who are straining at the leash to buy stocks, and I am holding them by main force"
- **20 August**: "This is a period of investment accumulation. Majority of buyers say they are picking up stocks for a pull of a year or two realizing they are cheap"
- **23 August**: "Liquidation in a number of stocks seems to be over… particularly true of the copper issues"
- **24 August**: **DJIA bottoms**
- **25 August (William Peter Hamilton, Dow Theory)**: "Far from encouraging to the bull, but they do not yet jointly indicate a definite resumption of the main bear movement"
- **25 August**: **International Paper** selling at $39.50 months after annual report showed $53/share available for common — "a stock market development without precedent." **American International** sold to 25⅜ vs. liquidating value of $50
- **27 August**: Urgent short covering by bears — vigorous rally in virtually all stocks
- **28 August**: "Bears Trapped" — list of stocks commanding premiums in loan crowd longest since bear market began two years prior. Bear rumors about Mexican Petroleum dividend deferral revealed as false; large financial interests combined to force shorts to cover

#### September — Confirmation and New Buying

- **29 August**: Bear attack fails. "Many companies have more cash than at any time in their history"
- **2 September**: "With the short interest eliminated there is now no one to buy stocks"
- **3 September**: Attitude shift — instead of stressing bearish factors, traders now "tending to look on the brighter side"
- **7 September (**Jesse Livermore**)**: Extended quote arguing the deflationary liquidation cycle was complete — inventories drawn down, output cut, shortage now emerging; once public realizes low prices and prosperity ahead "there will be a scramble by everyone to purchase… advancing prices always bring prosperity throughout the country"
  - Livermore's actual thesis: **low inventory levels** would prevent further price declines and spur buying
- **10 September**: "A bear panic existed before the end of the day. The last of the Waldorf crowd, which had been persistently bearish, was driven in"
- **12 September**: "Thousands of shares of better class industrial and railroad stocks absorbed by large interests… bear crowd has been given one of the worst beatings in the history of Wall Street"
- **14 September (William Boyce Thompson**, mining entrepreneur, former Fed director): "The capitalizations of many concerns are today selling below net current assets over current liabilities. The shares of many corporations are selling at one-third of their respective book values. Security prices like these are too attractive to exist for any great length of time"
- **14 September**: Outside a handful of stocks, little interest — recent rise had not encouraged public participation
- **16 September**: "Great price movements always overrun themselves and this is true of bull and bear markets alike. When tested industrial properties show a book value far in excess of their common stock at the market price… the superior safety of tax-exempt municipal bonds has blinded the investor to equities"
- **22–23 September**: **Jesse Livermore** blamed for halting advance (fell out with partner **George J. Whelan**, tobacco magnate, over which stock should lead the rally). Public refused to come in; rally driven by large banks and financiers convinced the bottom was in
- **26 September (Hornblower & Weeks)**: "The greatest necessity in the early stages of a bull market is patience… the market of today keeps would-be purchasers in constant doubt and they will not buy stocks when they are dull and unattractive, but only when they are active and made to look very attractive for selling purposes"
- **4 October (William Peter Hamilton, WSJ editor)**: "The stock market reflects absolutely all everybody knows about the business of the country. When the market is taken by surprise there is panic and history records how seldom it is taken by surprise"
- **24 October**: Bearish operators "badly punished in the upward drive" — hasty short covering gave further impetus to the advance

---

### Key Analytical Conclusions: What Actually Worked

#### Sentiment Extremes as Contrarian Signals
- The emergence of **buying interest on every "drive" by bears** was evidence their day was ending
- Just before the bottom (19 August), common stocks selling out of line with preferreds — shorts being forced to cover commons, creating misalignment
- **Peak bear sentiment = buy signal**: "Bear tips are now quite the thing, and anyone who even intimates that a stock may go up is looked on with suspicion. Such a condition usually marks the end of a bear market"

> 'I listen to a hundred confidences a day and recently the exaggerations I have heard from men in all walks of life are appalling… Bad news may travel fast but fake news has the wings of Mercury… out of a possible 100 reports of disaster and tribulation I listen to weekly, perhaps one has an iota of truth in it.'
> — Anonymous banker, late August 1921

- **Edward L. Doheny** of Mexican Petroleum had newsletter writer **WC Moore** indicted for criminal libel over a bear-case investment newsletter

#### Short Interest as a Technical Signal
- When supply of stocks for lending was decreasing and cost of borrowing stocks rising → **shorts running out of ammunition**
- The very bottom occurred when the number of stocks lent at a premium **peaked** — peak shorting activity = impending wane of bear pressure

#### Ownership Concentration: US Steel / AT&T as Bellwethers
- In significant bull markets, stock concentration shifts **to Wall Street** (professionals)
- **US Steel** (largest listed company since 1901) broker holdings: 58% at 1916 peak → 23% by June 1921
- Peak holder count in **US Steel** and **AT&T** coincided with nadir of public participation — once public was maximally conservative (holding defensive stocks), any shift would increase stock market commitment
- In 1919-21, **AT&T** became co-equal bellwether with US Steel

#### Volume at the Bottom: Contrarian vs. Modern View
- 1921 bottom was attended by **low volume**, not a high-volume capitulation
- Modern adage: bear markets end with capitulation on heavy volume — **this did not happen in 1921**
- Low volume at the bottom reflected **disinterest** in stocks → bullish signal for future
- Rising volume after the first DJIA rebound suggested the price rise was sustainable

#### Key Players at the Bottom
- **Jesse Livermore**: Banned from NY/Boston bucket shops by 1900 for being too successful; made >$3M in one day shorting during the 1907 crash. Switched from bear to bull **almost exactly at the 1921 bottom**. His bull thesis: depleted inventories would halt price declines and spark buying
- **William Peter Hamilton**: WSJ editor; using **Dow Theory** (reading both DJIA and Dow Jones Railroad index together) accurately called the 1921 bottom

#### The Earnings Trap
- **Bulls of 1921 focused on value and technical factors — not earnings**
- Market bottomed in August 1921; reported earnings had a **further 37% to fall** before bottoming in December 1921
- **Earnings recovery significantly lagged the stock market recovery**
- Waiting for earnings to confirm the bottom would have meant missing the entire move

<!-- pp. 121-140 -->

## Dow Theory (continued from prior section)

- **Dow Theory** first expounded by **Charles H. Dow** in his 'Review and Outlook'
  editorial in the WSJ, beginning April 1899
- Dow never formalized it; first codified by **S.A. Nelson** in *The ABC of Stock
  Speculation* (1903)
- **William Peter Hamilton** joined WSJ in 1899, worked with Dow until Dow's death
  at 51 in 1902; wrote extensively on theory's market implications; published
  *The Stock Market Barometer* (1922)
- Three simultaneous movements: **primary** (lasts at least a year), **secondary**
  (sharp rallies in bear / sharp reactions in bull), and daily fluctuation
- Key practical rule: the two averages (industrials + rails) must **corroborate
  each other** — no primary movement where they disagree

> 'One of the best tested of them is that the two averages corroborate each other,
> and that there is never a primary movement, rarely a secondary movement, where
> they do not agree.' — **William Peter Hamilton**, *The Stock Market Barometer*

---

## Bonds and the Bear — 1921

### Bond Market Timeline

- Bear market in bonds had been underway since **1899**, escalating with postwar
  inflation
- **Dow Jones index of 40 corporation bonds** hit its lowest reading: **57.29 in
  May 1920**, then briefly recovered and re-bottomed at 57.75 in June 1921
- June 1921 bottom was 0.8% above May 1920 low — but this was the true launch of
  a **25-year bull market in bonds** that ran until 1946
- **Liberty Bond** market behaved differently: bottomed decisively in May 1920 and
  did not retest those lows; prices rallied 13 months May 1920–June 1921, then
  made equal gains again in just 5 months June–October 1921

### Sequencing of Bond Market Recovery

- **Government bonds led** the recovery; **corporate bonds followed** ~3 weeks later
- **Liberty Bond prices** bottomed first week of June 1921
- **Corporate bond index** bottomed final week of June 1921
- **DJIA** did not bottom until **24 August 1921** — bonds clearly led stocks
- Within corporates, **industrial bonds** were last to bottom; industrial corporations
  had cut or omitted dividends in summer 1921, while railroad/utility dividend
  outlooks were more stable

### Why Deflation Mattered for Corporate Bonds

- Deflation devastated corporate bond issuers: fixed costs (including bond interest)
  remained while sales contracted
- Corporate bonds were uniquely sensitive to evidence that deflation was ending
- **Key variable for bond bottom: trend in deflation** — more so than for equities
- Recovery was led by **high-yielding paper and second-grade rails / foreign
  government issues** — biggest gains in the riskiest credits

### Railroad Bonds: A Special Case

- Railroad bond/equity outlook entangled with **politics**: would the government pay
  compensation for underinvestment during nationalisation?
- **Interstate Commerce Commission** had approved 40% rise in freight rates and 20%
  rise in passenger rates as late as 1920 — gave railroads pricing certainty
  unavailable to market-dependent sectors; explains their faster turnaround
- High-grade rail bonds yielded ~5.5% at the August 1921 recovery point;
  lower-grade rails averaged ~8.6% yield (Erie conv 4s: 9.8%, St L & San Fran Inc
  6s: 10.3%)

### Investor Sentiment at the Bond Bottom

- Contradicting typical bear market psychology: no "crescendo of pessimism" at the
  bond bottom — instead, a clamour of good news and buying advice was being ignored
- WSJ (27 June): commercial banks becoming major buyers of government bonds as
  demand for credit "for expansion purposes has almost ceased"
- Call money ~5%; WSJ noted corporate bonds available at 8% yields — obvious
  carry trade being underutilized due to fear of continued deflation
- Banking houses advising clients to exchange short-maturity holdings for
  **long-term bonds** (WSJ, 23 July)
- Price stabilization reduced deflation risk, encouraging investors to borrow
  short at ~5% and buy higher-yielding bonds

### 1921 Bear Market Bottom Checklist (Napier's Summary)

> *US equities traded below fair value from 1917 to 1926. How was an investor to
> know that 1921 was the opportune moment to invest? There was a combination of
> signals in the summer of 1921: improving demand at lower prices for selected
> goods, particularly autos; commodity price stabilisation; improving economic news
> being ignored by the market; rising volumes on a strong stock market; falling
> volumes on a weak stock market; a rising short interest; a final fall in equity
> prices on low volumes; reductions in Fed controlled interest rates; a rally in
> the government bond market; a rally in the corporate bond market; positive signals
> from the Dow Theory. This is the checklist of features one needs to focus on if
> one seeks the bottom of the bear market.*

---

## Part II. July 1932

> 'It wasn't anywheres near as frightful as this one.' — **James T. Farrell**,
> *Judgement Day*

- DJIA: 63.9 on 24 August 1921 → **381.2 on 3 September 1929** (almost +500%)
- Then plunged **89%** to bottom at **41.22 on 8 July 1932**
- Napier's contrarian warning: **1929–32 may be more the exception than the rule**
  among bear markets — over-studying it may have misled generations of investors

---

## The Road to July 1932

### The 1920s Bull Market — Slower Start Than Remembered

- DJIA bottomed August 1921 at 63.9; still below 100 as late as **July 1924**
- Still below November 1919 high as late as **April 1925**
- **1921–24** = return to pre-recession profit and valuation ("normalcy") — profitable
  but not speculative; market rose 87% from 1921 low with avg. dividend yield of
  6.4% by April 1925
- NYSE seat prices flat 1921–24 (~$77k–$101k range); surged to $625k by 1929
- NYSE volume: 260M shares in 1922 → 1.12 billion in 1929 — speculative explosion
  only truly began in 1925

### Political Catalyst: Coolidge and the Republicans

- **Calvin Coolidge** victory in November 1924 election seen as catalyst for bull
  market acceleration
- Republicans were known **reluctant enforcers of antitrust** — e.g., dropped
  antitrust action against Aluminium Company of America
- **Andrew Mellon** (Treasury Secretary, one of America's richest men) delivered
  tax cuts and cut government spending
- Coolidge inaugural address (4 March 1925): "The collection of any taxes, which
  are not absolutely required… is only a species of legalised larceny."
- WSJ 50th anniversary (27 June 1932) singled out the post-1924 election period
  as uniquely sensational — two-million share days became common

### Two Structural Drivers of the 1920s Bull Market

**1. Technological displacement: Electrification**

- Electricity first offered to US consumers **4 September 1882**; slow adoption —
  only 8% of dwellings wired by 1907
- By 1921: **37.8%** of homes connected; by 1929: **67.9%**
- Factory machinery powered by electricity: **32% (1919) → 49% (1929)**
- Commercial electrical equipment sales in 1929 were **146% higher** than 1921
- US produced more electric power in 1929 than **rest of world combined**
- Three bull market stimulants from electrification: surge in **productivity**,
  dampening of **inflation**, leap in **demand** for new products
- Real GDP per man-hour rose **19%** from 1921–1929; each unit of capital 23% more
  productive in 1929 vs. 1921
- **Cowles Commission** data: S&P Composite Index earnings per share rose **455%**
  from 1921–1929 (even from recovery year 1923, still +64% by 1929)
- **Deflationary surprise**: most US prices in 1929 were *below* 1921 levels —
  all commodities 97.6→95.3; fuel/lighting 96.8→83.0; textiles 94.5→90.4
- Automobile-driven shift: 5 million fewer horses on US farms in 1929 vs. 1921,
  freeing 1/3 of cropland from fodder production to food
- Household appliance sales +189% in dollar terms 1921–1929; radio sales nearly
  **30-fold**

**2. Consumer credit expansion (instalment credit)**

- Instalment credit existed since at least 1807 (furniture retailers); popularised
  from 1850s by **Singer Sewing Machine Company**
- Still socially stigmatized pre-WWI; **Anna Schwarz** and **Milton Friedman**
  (*Monetary History of the United States 1867–1960*) note it was "hardly known"
  in 1914
- Key psychological shift: **General Motors Acceptance Corporation** opened 1919 —
  made instalment credit respectable for the middle class buying automobiles
- Household car purchases on instalment: **4.9% (1919) → 15.2% (1929)**
- **Wilbur Plummer** (1927): 40% of poorer families, 25% of middle-class families,
  5% of wealthy families using instalment plans
- By 1927: 15% of all consumer durables ($6 billion) bought on instalment; 85%+
  of furniture, 80% of phonographs, 75% of washing machines sold this way
- **National City Bank** (largest US bank) entered personal-credit business in 1928
  — further mainstream endorsement
- Key insight: instalment credit expansion happened **within overall monetary
  moderation** — a new channel appeared where none previously existed; bull markets
  in consumption can be fuelled by such new credit channels even without broad
  credit excess

### Living with the Fed — A Whole New Ball Game (II)

- The Fed, emboldened by its 1914–21 role in economic management, continued
  intervening rather than letting the gold standard operate freely
- 1920s: large gold inflows to US naturally dictated easy monetary policy, but
  Fed believed it had to **curb speculation** associated with easier money
- Tight policy would also reduce current account deficit, thus preventing gold
  from flowing to trading partners — important for **reconstructing the international
  gold standard**
- These **dual objectives** (curb speculation + ensure gold flows to partners)
  would complicate policy responses in 1927–29 as speculation escalated
- US was sitting on a "monetary powder keg" since WWI as gold flowed in; Fed
  was hesitant to permit large credit structures built on what it viewed as
  temporarily concentrated gold stock

<!-- pp. 141-160 -->

## The Gold Standard, Fed Policy, and the Course of the 1929-32 Bear

### Gold Concentration and the Interwar Gold Standard

- In 1921, only the US and five small countries (Cuba, Nicaragua, Panama,
  Philippines, Salvador) remained on the **gold standard**
- By 1925, the US held **43.2% of world gold reserves**; 48 countries had
  returned to gold by 1929
- **France** deliberately undervalued its currency (a political choice),
  accumulating gold; **Britain** returned at a rate that clearly overvalued
  sterling — the net impact was no dramatic drain of US reserves
- From 1923–1929, the Fed **sterilised gold inflows** to dampen monetary
  growth, total money stock, credit, and the economy
- If the Fed had not sterilised, the US would have had a boom-bust much
  earlier in the decade — though possibly not as large
- **Hugh Bancroft** (WSJ president): reparations and war-debt settlements
  "drained $500 million a year from the rest of the world… when more than
  70% of the world's monetary gold was concentrated in the US and France,
  there wasn't enough gold left in the rest of the world to sustain
  confidence"

### Fed Credit Growth Was Not Excessive in the 1920s

- Total bank loans grew 43.5% from 1921–1929; total bank assets +45.7%
- Nominal GDP grew 42% over the same period — credit growth broadly in line
- **J.K. Galbraith** argued the Fed should have tightened further, but this
  would have destabilised the international gold standard reconstruction
- Money stock at the peak (August 1929) was actually **lower than 16 months
  earlier** — the Fed had been tightening since 1928
- Conclusion: the 1920s were not characterised by excessively loose monetary
  policy in aggregate

### The Speculative Lending Problem

- By 1925, Fed members worried credit was being channelled to "speculative"
  rather than "productive" uses — especially Wall Street broker loans
- Fed Board split: majority favoured **"direct pressure"** (deny
  rediscounting privileges to banks making speculative loans); minority
  favoured raising the discount rate
- The source of speculative loans was **not the banking system** — it was
  non-banks, corporations, and foreign capital flowing into the call market
- NYSE-listed stocks and bonds rose from $27 billion (end 1924) to
  $89 billion (October 1929); broker loans from NY banks barely increased
- By October 1929, "Others" (non-bank) broker loans were $6.64 billion
  vs. NY banks' $1.1 billion — direct pressure on member banks was
  therefore largely irrelevant
- February 1928: **Federal Reserve Bank of New York** raised rates for the
  first time, acknowledging direct pressure had failed

### The Rate Hike That Killed the Economy

- NY Fed discount rate rose from **3.5% (Feb 1928) to 6.0% (Aug 1929)**
- Call-money rates rose from 4.24% (Jan 1928) to 9.23% (July 1929)
- March 1929: brief panic as call rates hit **20%** — then fell back, market
  resumed its climb
- The rate hikes were too small to stop speculation in an environment of
  assumed capital gains, but large enough to slow the economy by
  July 1929 — curbing speculation by curbing the economy itself
- By September–October 1929, Fed tightening was curbing speculation
  primarily because it was curbing **overall economic activity**
- "Fed-watching had been born" — investors in 1928–29 knew the Fed's
  stated goal was to end the speculative frenzy

---

## The Course of the Dow 1929–32

> *"It's goddamn tough when a poor man saves a little money and thinks that
> he's got something put aside for his old age, and then the bank goes bust."*
> — James T. Farrell, *Judgement Day*

### The End of the Bull Market

- Industrial/factory production indices peaked **June 1929**; NBER reference
  peak: **August 1929**
- Global slowdown already underway: Australia/Netherlands slowed 1927,
  Germany/Brazil slumped 1928, Argentina/Canada/Poland H1 1929
- The US ran a **current account surplus** throughout the 1920s — the country
  holding 43% of world gold reserves not running a deficit restricted
  global growth; Wall Street acted as a magnet sucking in capital that
  would otherwise have eased conditions elsewhere
- US private capital outflows fell **42%** in 1929 from the 1927–28 average,
  starving the rest of the world of liquidity
- Countries maintaining gold parity with no current account improvement
  had no choice but **deflation** — the September–October 1929 crash may
  partly reflect belated recognition of this global deflationary dynamic

### Triggers of the Crash

- **DJIA peaked 3 September 1929**; fell 32% by 28 October
- **26 September 1929**: Bank of England raised discount rate from 5.5% to
  6.5% — defending against capital drain to the "orgy of speculation
  3,000 miles away" (Chancellor **Philip Snowden**) — this changed the
  US/UK interest rate differential and began to unsettle US investors
- **30 September**: Collapse of **Clarence Hatry**'s UK business empire —
  he had been forging scrip to raise finance for steel consolidation;
  banks pulled credit, stocks went into free fall
- **11 October**: Massachusetts Dept. of Public Utilities refused Boston
  Edison a 4:1 stock split, stating "no one… on the basis of its
  earnings, would find it to his advantage to buy it"
- **Time magazine** covers: 28 October featured **Ivar Kreuger** (Swedish
  financier who committed suicide in 1932 when his empire collapsed);
  4 November featured **Samuel Insull** (Chicago utilities magnate, later
  fought extradition from Greece on embezzlement charges)
- The magnitude of the initial crash was not exceptional: 1907 bear was -44%,
  1919–21 was -47%; Sept–Nov 1929 was -48%

### The Misleading Recovery and What Followed

- By 17 April 1930, market had recovered **52% of the decline** and was
  just 23% below its Sept 1929 high — magnitude not abnormal, rebound
  faster than normal
- Investors who bought on 17 April 1930 saw the DJIA lose **86%** of its
  value before the bottom in July 1932
- The October 1929 crash itself is not what makes 1929–32 unique —
  **events after April 1930** are what distinguish it from all prior
  bear markets

### The Banking System as the Key Differentiator

- The single key difference between 1929–32 and all prior 20th-century
  bear markets: the **collapse of the banking system**
- 1907 panic involved bank failures but led to the Fed's creation; 1916–17
  and 1919–21 — the new Fed system successfully contained bank collapses
- **Figure 41 — DJIA phases of the 1929–32 bear:**
  - The Crash (Sept–Nov 1929): -48% (cumulative -48%)
  - 1st Rally (Nov 1929–Apr 1930): +48% (cumulative -23%)
  - Summer Decline (Apr–Sept 1930): -17% (cumulative -36%)
  - **First Banking Crisis** (Sept–Dec 1930): -36% (cumulative -59%)
  - 2nd Rally (Dec 1930–Feb 1931): +23% (cumulative -49%)
  - **Second Banking Crisis** (Feb–Oct 1931): -56% (cumulative -77%)
  - Potential Stability (Oct 1931–Mar 1932): +3% (cumulative -76%)
  - **The Gold Drain** (Mar–Jul 1932): -54% (cumulative -89%)

### Public Participation and Investment Trusts

- Pre-WWI: ~500,000 Americans owned securities; by 1929: **up to 20 million**
- Uneducated retail participation meant the downside when enthusiasm waned
  was larger than in periods of less public interest
- 1920: at most 40 investment trusts in the US, negligible importance
- 1927–1930: **700 investment trusts** created; 1929 alone: 265 new trusts
  with $3 billion subscribed; peak market cap of the sector: **$8 billion**
- Dubious practices were common: buying illiquid stock, purchasing from
  connected directors, price manipulation, excessive gearing, extreme
  concentration
- **Hugh Bullock** (1932): American investment management was embryonic
  compared to Britain — "we are somewhat new to the business"

> *"Investment management in Great Britain is a profession. There are
> approximately 200,000 seasoned, marketable securities in the world. It takes
> specialists to find the best. We in America are somewhat new to the
> business."* — Hugh Bullock, 1932

### The First Banking Crisis (Oct–Dec 1930)

- From mid-1929 to Oct 1930, the economy contracted only modestly: GNP -1.8%,
  CPI -0.9% in the 12 months from June 1929
- Bank failures in 1920s were high (mostly agricultural banks), but Q4 1930
  was on a new scale: Nov–Dec 1930 alone saw **$550 million** in deposits
  tied up in 608 bank suspensions
- Key failure: **Bank of the United States** — largest US bank failure in
  history to that point, 400,000 depositors concentrated in New York City
- Before Oct 1930, the **deposit-currency ratio** was at an all-time high —
  Americans had unprecedented faith in banks at precisely the moment the
  crisis arrived
- When deposits began to flee, the fractional reserve system meant banks had
  to reduce deposits by **$14 for every $1** they needed to return as cash
- DJIA declined 36% from mid-September to mid-December 1930, crashing
  through the November 1929 low

### The Monetary Transmission Mechanism Breaks Down

- Banks reacted to deposit flight by scrambling for liquid assets — shifting
  from corporate bonds into government securities
- Corporate bond prices (which had been rising after the Oct 1929 crash)
  began to decline in Oct 1930, starting a price decline that ran until
  summer 1932
- The **deposit-currency ratio** collapsed from 11.5 (Oct 1930) to 4.4
  (March 1933) — levels not seen since the 19th century
- Total bank deposits: $59.8 billion (June 1930) → $58.1 billion
  (Dec 1930) → $56.1 billion (June 1931) → **$49.5 billion** (Dec 1931)
  — back to 1924 levels

### The Second Banking Crisis and European Contagion (1931)

- **May 1931**: Austria's largest private bank, **Creditanstalt**, failed
- Austria imposed exchange controls, freezing foreign balances; contagion
  spread to Hungary then **Germany** (Creditanstalt had controlling
  interest in Hungary's biggest bank)
- More than half of German bank deposits were owned by non-Germans —
  their loss of confidence had severe international consequences
- Full-scale banking crisis in Germany by July 1931; exchange controls
  followed; US bank deposits frozen in Austria, Hungary, and Germany
- Domestic bank suspensions: Aug 1931–Jan 1932 — 1,860 banks with
  $1,449 million in deposits — equalling the **entire 1921–29 period**
  in just six months
- Second banking crisis accounted for **32% of the total DJIA decline**
  from September 1929 to July 1932

### The Gold Drain and the Fed's Failure

> *"… no longer any fear on the part of the banks or the business community
> that some sudden and temporary business crisis may develop and precipitate
> a financial panic… The Federal Reserve System is the antidote for money
> contraction and credit shortage."*
> — **Andrew Mellon**, Secretary of the Treasury, Saturday Evening Post,
> 14 April 1928

- The Fed offered no such antidote — it reduced the discount rate but made
  no attempt to expand credit to member banks as the public fled the system
- Fed credit outstanding in summer 1931 was near the 1924 low (~$1 billion)
  despite vast scope to expand the "elastic currency"
- Not until **late summer 1931** did the Fed begin material open-market
  purchases — by which time deposit-currency ratio had fallen below 9.0
- **September 1931**: UK devalued sterling — eight countries immediately
  followed, four more in October; gold began draining from the US
- US gold stocks had risen **15%** from Sept 1929 to Aug 1931 (safe-haven
  inflows); then declined **15%** Aug–Oct 1931, erasing all the gains
- Fed responded as gold standard required: raised discount rate from 1.5%
  to **3.5% in October 1931** — this forced banks to dump even government
  bonds, which for the first time in the recession saw their prices decline
- In six months (Aug 1931–Jan 1932): 1,860 bank suspensions with
  $1.449 billion deposits — same as the entire 1921–29 period

### The Final Blow: 1932 Gold Drain and Policy Panic

- October 1931: **National Credit Corporation** launched to lend to banks
  against assets the Fed wouldn't accept
- February 1932: **Reconstruction Finance Corporation** created to lend to
  banks and railroads; **Glass-Steagall Act** passed allowing government
  bonds as collateral for Fed notes (removing a technical barrier to
  liquidity creation)
- March 1932 DJIA marginally above October 1931 levels — investors who
  bought then lost **54%** before the July 1932 bottom
- Final blow: US gold reserves fell a further 12% Mar–Jul 1932
- **George Harrison** (governor, Federal Reserve Bank of New York) admitted
  the open-market operation was prompted by fear of Congressional
  interference: "the only way to forestall some sort of radical financial
  legislation by Congress, is to go further and faster with our own program"
- The Fed's belated conversion to **reflationary policy** convinced foreign
  investors the US might abandon the gold standard — they liquidated dollar
  deposits, accelerating the gold drain
- **Barry Eichengreen**: devaluations elsewhere threatened to erode
  America's current account surplus; the greater the political pressure
  on the Fed to reflate, the greater the risk of dollar devaluation
- The DJIA — assailed by the 1929 crash, first banking crisis (Oct 1930),
  second banking crisis (1931), and gold drain (1932) — bottomed in
  July 1932 at a level **89% below** its September 1929 peak

<!-- pp. 161-180 -->

## Structure of the Market in 1932

> *'It's this way, Joe. Now, what gave us good times? The automobile industry. Why?
> Because it was something new to develop. Now, what do we need now to bring back
> better times? Something else that's new, to develop.'*
> — James T. Farrell, *Judgement Day*

### The Stock Market in 1932

- **Market size grew enormously** between bear bottoms: 1,278 NYSE-listed stocks at
  end of 1932 vs. just 691 at end of 1921 — nearly double
- Turnover rate fell from 59% (1921) to 32% (1932), yet absolute volume rose:
  **425 million shares traded in 1932 vs. 173 million in 1921** — listed shares
  increased 349% over the period
- At the June 1932 low, average weekly volume was just 3,047,183 shares; average
  stock price on 1 July was $11.89 → weekly NYSE turnover value ~$36.2 million
- **Preferred shares still mattered**: 445 preferred stocks listed alongside 808
  common stocks on 1 July 1932; preferred accounted for 19% of combined market value
- Typical active day: ~500 of the 1,253 listed issues actually traded

**Countering the "dead market" myth:**
- Total NYSE market cap in 1932 was only 40% below its end-1924 level — the DJIA's
  89% fall masked relative resilience of the broader market
- The 32% turnover rate of 1932 would not be surpassed again until after 1979
- The 89% DJIA decline occurred against only a 5% decline in number of listed
  securities — most companies survived

### Sector Composition: 1929 vs. 1932

**September 1929 market cap by sector (top 5):**
- Railroads & Equipment: $12,778m (14.25%)
- Petroleum: $7,601m (8.48%)
- Chemicals: $7,112m (7.93%)
- Autos & Accessories: $6,162m (6.87%)
- Communications (incl. **AT&T**): $5,315m (5.93%)
- Total market: $89,670m across 1,280 issues

**Surprising facts about 1929 composition:**
- **Railroads were still #1** despite industrials outperforming them by 86%
  from the 1921 low to the 1929 peak
- The 1920s boom is associated with autos and radios, but the **real bull
  market leaders were chemicals (+369%) and electrical equipment (+349%)**
- Financial sector (largely investment trusts) was less than **2.5% of total
  market cap** in September 1929
- **US Steel** had been the largest US listed company as recently as 1920;
  by 1929 the entire steel sector was just the 10th largest

**July 1932 market cap by sector (top 5):**
- Petroleum: $1,698m (10.86%)
- Communications: $1,686m (10.78%)
- Railroad & Equipment: $1,364m (8.72%) — fallen from #1 to #3
- Gas & Electric Operating Companies: $1,492m (9.54%)
- Chemicals: $1,212m (7.75%)
- Total market: $15,635m across 1,244 issues

**Key structural shifts 1929→1932:**
- **Railroads lost their crown** permanently during the Depression — from >50%
  of NYSE turnover two decades earlier to just 8.7% of market cap by July 1932
- By 1932, **utilities, oil and communications** together = 37% of total market cap
- **Concentration increased**: top 10 sectors = 77% of cap in 1932 vs. 71% in 1929
- Autos suffered far more than defensive sectors (food, tobacco, communications, utilities)

### Sector Performance: The Bull Market (June 1926–September 1929)

**Top performers (total return with dividends):**
- Chemicals: +369%
- Electrical Equipment: +349%
- Utilities: +326%
- Financials: +275%
- DJIA: +149%

**Why chemicals led:** Investors excited about **petrochemical industry** prospects.
**Du Pont** added waterproof coating to cellophane in 1927; synthetic methanol and
nitrates entering commercial production. Neoprene, Perspex, polythene, nylon
anticipated. Prospect of growth in synthetic raw materials drove valuations.

**Why utilities performed:** Electrification of American households and businesses
accelerated through the decade. However, much was built on **dubious financial
engineering** — utility holding company CEOs **William Foshay** (Minneapolis) and
**Samuel Insull** (Middle West Utilities) ended up on criminal charges after the bust.

**Why financials surged:** Investment trust mania — trusts trading at significant
**premiums to NAV** and applying leverage to boost returns.

**Laggards during the 1920s bull market:**
- Commodity sectors (led the 1917-19 bull) — inflation in abeyance, commodity prices
  actually declined
- Oil: +48% (worst major sector) — those who held through 1919-21 bear were not rewarded

### Sector Performance: The Bear Market (September 1929–June 1932)

**Best performers (least bad):**
- Tobacco: -38% (volumes up, raw material prices collapsed, selling prices held)
- Telecoms: -70%
- Clothes: -75%

**Worst performers:**
- Wholesale: -94%
- Games: -93%
- Steel: -92%
- Electrical Equipment: -91%
- Financials: -91%
- Transport: -90%
- DJIA: -89%
- Autos: -88%
- Beer: -86%
- Chemical: -85%
- Utilities: -82%

**Key insight:** Even **seemingly defensive sectors** — utilities and food — offered
little protection. Utilities fell 82%; food fell 72%. Food was relatively new as a
packaged consumer product in the 1920s, so demand was still cyclical. By 1932,
**85% of bread consumed in America was baked at home**.

- The declines must be viewed against a **33% decline in the wholesale price index**
  (a real offset) and the fact that most companies maintained some dividend payments
- **Cowles Foundation data**: dividends fell 48% from 1929 to 1932

**Tobacco was the only true safe haven 1929-32**: rising volumes, collapsing raw
material input costs, stable selling prices — a near-perfect defensive combination.

---

## The Bond Market in 1932

> *'What does Father Moylan say? He tells what the bankers are doing. Loaning American
> money to Europe. If they had kept American money in America where it belongs, there
> wouldn't be any depression.'*
> — James T. Farrell, *Judgement Day*

### Bond Market Structure

**NYSE-listed bond market, 1 June 1932:**
- 1,587 bond issues, $52,193m par value; market value $36,856m
- Composition by market value:
  - US government: 40.5% ($14,929m) — just 11 issues
  - Foreign government: 30.5% ($11,242m)
  - Railroads: 13.4% ($4,953m)
  - Utilities: 7.7% ($2,811m)
  - Industrial: 4.9% ($1,812m)

- Average daily bond trading volume ~$10m, of which ~40% in US government securities
- The total value of NYSE-listed bonds declined only **21%** from September 1929
  to June 1932 (vs. stock market decline of ~83% by market cap)
- Investment managers remained heavily allocated to bonds — **Fidelity Fund** reported
  65% bonds, 28.6% stocks, 6.4% cash as of 30 June 1932

### Bond Yield Shifts (Sep 1929 → Jun 1932)

| Sector     | Sep 1929 | Jun 1932 |
|------------|----------|----------|
| Government | 3.70%    | 3.76%    |
| Industrial | 4.10%    | 6.80%    |
| Railroad   | 5.38%    | 9.14%    |
| Utility    | 5.16%    | 7.21%    |

**Pattern of corporate bond prices:**
- Sep 1929 → Sep 1930: rally — industrial yields fell 33 bps as recession
  appeared normal
- Sep 1930 onward: first banking crisis → industrial bond prices fell dramatically,
  below Sep 1929 levels by December 1930
- Railroad and utility bonds followed the same pattern
- **Key implication:** the 11-month rally in company bond prices after the 1929 crash
  suggests the stock market crash itself may not have caused the Depression — the
  real break came with the banking crisis one year later

**Government bonds:** Largely flat over the full period. Bull market in govts lasted
Sep 1929 to June 1931 (second banking crisis, yield reached 3.13%). Devaluation panic
of late 1931 reversed even that gain. Net result: government bond prices unchanged
over the entire equity bear market.

**BAA corporate bonds** (Figure 51): Yield rose from ~6% in 1929 to nearly 12%
at the 1932 peak — a dramatic credit spread widening reflecting deflation-driven
corporate balance sheet deterioration.

### Foreign Government Bonds

- **Surprising fact:** Foreign government bonds outstripped domestic corporate bonds
  in market value on the NYSE — the US became the world's primary capital exporter
  in the 1920s as Britain recovered from WWI
- Jan 1926: 116 foreign government issues on NYSE ($3,024m); by Sep 1929: 202 issues
  ($16,012m) — one-third of all bond value listed on NYSE
- Investor could buy bonds of Bavaria, Bolivia, Brazil, Budapest, Costa Rica, Cuba,
  Haiti, Nuremberg, Oslo, Panama, Rotterdam, Warsaw, Vienna, Yokohama

**1929 prices vs. 1932 lows (selected):**
- Bolivia: 84½ → 2 (near total default)
- Brazil: 88⅛ → 14
- Columbia: 77⅞ → 13½
- German external 7s: 105¼ → 41¼
- Australian external 5s: 94⅜ → 46½
- France external 7s: 109 → 109 (held perfectly — undervalued currency in 1928)
- UK 5½s: 102 → 90 (resilient despite leaving gold)
- Canada 5s: 101⅛ → 87 (resilient despite devaluation)

**Mechanism of sovereign credit collapse:** Countries that devalued against gold
lost ability to service USD-denominated debt. Internal deflation demanded to stay
on gold became politically intolerable as unemployment rose and banking systems
failed. By 1932, the US remained on gold while a long list — including Germany,
UK, Japan, Australia, most of Latin America — had devalued.

**Best-performing sovereign**: **France** — joined gold standard in 1928 with an
*undervalued* currency, maintained gold until 1936, bonds unchanged.

**Lesson**: Leaving gold ≠ sovereign credit collapse. UK and Canada left gold by
1932 but pursued sound monetary policy; their bonds traded above Italy's, which
stayed on gold until 1936 but lacked credibility.

---

## At the Bottom with the Bear — Summer 1932

> *'The investment trenches were deep and muddy in the summer of 1932.'*

### What Made 1932 Different from Other Bear Bottoms

**The key distinction:** The speed and violence of the overvaluation-to-undervaluation
transition. In 1921, stocks became cheap through a **slow process** — prices drifted
sideways while the economy and earnings grew. In 1932, the market crashed from
extreme overvaluation to extreme undervaluation in under three years.

- DJIA peak before 1919-21 bear: 119.6 (barely above 100.5 in 1909)
- DJIA peak September 1929: **381.2** — up ~500% from the 1921 low
- The Dow peaked 220% above the previous bull market high of November 1919

**Implication:** 1929-32 cannot be characterized as "just the final down leg
exacerbating an undervaluation." The bull market had created genuine, sustained
overvaluation. 1932 is the **exception** among the four bear bottoms in this book —
the other three feature slow, grinding devaluation; 1932 features a sudden crash.

### The Economic Transformation 1920→1929 (Figure 53)

Key statistics showing genuine economic gains that justified some equity re-rating:
- **Real GDP**: $607bn → $865bn (+43%)
- **Nominal GDP**: $87bn → $104bn (+20%; balance = deflation, mainly 1921 commodity crash)
- Motor vehicle registrations: 9.2m → 26.7m
- Electricity production: 56,559m → 116,747m kWh
- Crude oil production: 443m → 1,007m barrels (+127%)
- Telephones: 13.3m → 20.1m
- Life insurance in force: $40.5bn → $102bn

**Notable counterfactuals suggesting overvaluation:**
- None of the economic indicators in Figure 53 grew as fast as the stock market
- Federal government expenditure actually fell: $6,403m → $3,298m
- Public debt fell: $24,299m → $16,931m
- Union membership fell: 5.0m → 3.6m

**Core question raised:** What explains the sudden transformation of the relationship
between broad economic growth and equity prices in the 1920s — if the economy
genuinely grew but the stock market grew far faster?

<!-- pp. 181-200 -->

## The 1929 Bull Market: Earnings vs. Valuation

### Earnings Growth in the 1920s
- Best earnings data from the **Cowles Foundation** (compiled by **Robert J. Shiller**, *Market Volatility*)
- Start date matters enormously: 1921 was a profit collapse year; 1916 was a war-profit peak
- Cyclically adjusted (10-year rolling average) earnings rose only **11% from 1921 to 1929**
- More useful: profits of listed companies roughly **doubled** from the 1922-23 recovery to 1929 peak
- Economy expanded **43%** over 1920-29; earnings doubled — reported earnings outpaced GDP
- Contrast to 1871-1921: economic growth outpaced earnings; the 1920s reversed this relationship
- Stock market rose **220% above its previous highest level** and ~5x above the August 1921 low
- The "new era" narrative: shareholders would finally participate in economic growth → justified higher valuations

### Valuations at the 1929 Peak
- **Cyclically adjusted PE** (S&P Composite): rose from **7.4x in August 1921** to peak at **31.6x in September 1929**
- Long-run average (Jan 1881–Sep 1929): **15.3x**; previous peak was **26.5x in June 1901**
- **q ratio** similarly at extreme: year-end 1929 data still **20% above previous high** (1905) and **80% above the 1900-29 average**
- Key contrast: on eve of the **1919-21 bear market**, cyclically adjusted PE was just **10.6x** — 33% *below* the 1881-1919 average

> "On the eve of the 1929-32 bear market, equities were very expensive, a marked contrast to the situation in 1919."

### The q Ratio Explained
> "The idea behind **the q ratio** is basically very simple. It compares two different estimates of the value of US companies. The first is what Wall Street says the companies are worth and the second is their fundamental value... fundamental value is what it would cost today to replace all the assets of all quoted companies... net worth... The ratio between the two is q."
> — *Andrew Smithers & Stephen Wright, Valuing Wall Street*

### Structural Point: Bear Markets Rarely Make Expensive Markets Cheap Quickly
- Popular memory treats 1929-32 as the template: rapid price decline → undervaluation
- **Napier's key counter-argument**: the 1921 experience (slow, decade-long valuation decline) is more typical
- "**Bear markets, where three-year price declines make overvalued equities cheap, are the exception and not the rule.**"
- The 1949 and 1982 bottoms also required extended compression — not crash-and-done

---

## The 1929-32 Bear: Valuations and the July 1932 Bottom

### The Earnings Collapse
- DJIA fell **89%** peak to trough; S&P earnings fell **68%** from Sep 1929 to Jul 1932
- Real S&P earnings in July 1932 were below those reported in **October 1873**; nominal earnings back to **December 1880** levels
- GDP (nominal) returned to ~1917 level; real GDP to ~1922 level (contractions of 43% and 26% respectively)
- Earnings collapsed *faster* than economic activity — not a simple proportional relationship

### Valuation at the July 1932 Bottom
- Despite earnings at 1880 levels, market capitalized them at only **10.2x** — a **26% discount** to the 1871-1932 average monthly PE
- **Cyclically adjusted PE**: almost **70% below** its 1881-1932 average
- **q ratio**: had probably fallen below **0.3x** — equities trading at more than a 70% discount to replacement value of assets
- Same as August 1921: extreme cheapness by every normalized measure

### The Roosevelt Uncertainty Problem
- By May 1932, **Franklin D. Roosevelt** (even before his Democratic nomination) stated capital must accept smaller returns relative to labor
- Some investors feared a structural, permanent reduction in corporate profitability under a Roosevelt administration
- This made "normalized earnings" genuinely unknowable — the 68% decline could represent a new regime, not just a cycle
- "This confusion as to the level of underlying earnings accounts for the dramatic differences in valuation parameters around the bear market bottom of July 1932."

### The Dramatic PE Surge in 1933
- Within 12 months of the July 1932 bottom, market valued earnings at **26.3x** — the most dramatic 12-month PE change on record
- Driven by: the rise in index prices + a further **13% decline** in already-depressed earnings
- Misleading read: the high PE did NOT mean stocks were expensive — it reflected 1880-level earnings being applied to a recovering market
- On any normalized earnings basis, equities were **deeply undervalued** throughout the recovery

### Price-to-Book at the Bottom
- *Wall Street Journal* (19 May 1932) published price-to-book and price-to-working-capital for 21 DJIA stocks
- Simple average: **0.66x price-to-book** vs. 0.82x at the 1921 low
- 18 May was not the bottom — DJIA fell a further **22%** before July 8 low; final P/B ratio reached ~**0.52x**
- Investors who anchored to 1921's 0.82x as floor suffered an additional 27% decline
- Selected data points (% of book value, 1932 low):
  - Bethlehem Steel: **9%** | US Steel: **13%** | American Smelting: **15%**
  - Mack Trucks: **19%** | Westinghouse: **25%** | International Harvester: **26%**
  - General Electric: **100%** (at book) | General Motors: **60%**

> "During the roaring days of the bull market, lack of full information about a company gave its securities a certain 'mystery' value. The long depression has done a great deal to eliminate 'mystery' value from consideration of the worth of a security." [31]

- By summer 1929, investors paid a **premium for mystery**; by summer 1932, they demanded a **50% discount on hard assets**

---

## Good News and the Bear (Summer 1932)

### Sentiment Context
- By July 1932: 34 months of economic decline, two banking crises, 89% market decline, wholesale prices -40%, industrial production halved
- Average recession peak-to-trough since 1854: **20 months**; 1929-32 was already **35 months** and counting
- NBER bottom of recession: **March 1933** — the equity market bottomed **9 months before** the economy
- A third banking crisis followed Roosevelt's November 1932 election; economy dipped to new lows, but the **DJIA never revisited its July 8, 1932 low**
- **Arthur Burns** and **Wesley Mitchell** described summer 1932 and March 1933 as a "double bottom" for the economy

### Key Finding: Good News Existed Even at the Darkest Hour
- Popular myth: no good news at a bear market bottom
- Napier demonstrates ample positive news in the *Wall Street Journal* May–September 1932:

**Selective timeline of positive WSJ reports:**
- **9 May**: Auto sales up 36% March-to-April in seven states
- **16 May**: Building permits up 19.7% over March (vs. normal seasonal -3.3%)
- **21 May**: Employment up in 8 of 16 major industrial groups
- **25 May**: Inventories at low ebb — any demand uptick would find bare shelves
- **11 June**: Chevrolet sales curve rising
- **21 June**: Fisher's wholesale price index records first gains in months across cotton, sugar, corn, wheat, cattle, hogs, tin, gasoline
- **6 July**: Charles Edison (son of Thomas Edison, head of Edison Industries) expresses belief that "bottom of business depression has been reached"
- **8 July**: **DJIA bottoms**
- **9 July**: World commodity markets respond to Lausanne reparations agreement — sharp price mark-ups in hogs and sugar
- **11 July**: Bank suspensions drop to 24 from 41 the prior week
- **22 July**: Barnet, Fuerst & Co.: "Economic crises in the past century have all ended with a firming of commodity and bond prices. Both of these indications are visible today."
- **6 August**: Roy D. Chapin (new Secretary of Commerce): "depression has run its course"
- **8 August**: *London Economist* expresses belief the US has passed crisis; credit expansion policy beneficial
- **19 August**: *Dun's Review*: "Steady improvement in business sentiment in all lines… The outlook is brighter than at any time in the last six months."
- **3 September**: *London Economist* (ed. Sir Walter Layton): possibility of "substantial economic recovery… as result of existing natural forces backed by the stimulus of controlled inflation now being applied"

> "As in 1921, the investor's ability to **ignore good news**, rather than the predominance of bad news, characterised the end of the bear market in 1932."

### Pattern Similarities Between 1921 and 1932 Bottoms
- In both: **motor industry** in the vanguard of recovery; **New England** showed early improvement
- In both: pickup in demand, against falling prices, appeared first in **higher-quality, higher-priced goods**
- **Most striking similarity**: a positive chain of events began once evidence of **price stability returned to commodity markets**
- Commodity/wholesale price stabilization was the most reliable leading indicator that the equity bear market was ending

---

## Price Stability and the Bear

- Signs of **price stability** coincided with the bear market bottom in both 1921 and 1932
- Pattern: stability in selected commodity prices → broadened to more commodities → reached the wholesale price index
- In 1932 (as in 1921), the US was one of the few nations still on the **gold standard**
- Whatever complications other currencies' free-float created, commodity price stability still defined when the economic cycle was nearing bottom
- "At the first sign of an upturn in commodity and wholesale price indices in the long bear market from September 1929, the equity market stabilised and moved higher."

<!-- pp. 201-220 -->

## Commodity & Wholesale Prices: 1932 vs. 1921

### Why 1932 Differed from 1921
- The wholesale price improvement in summer 1932 was **not sustained** — unlike 1921
- Economic growth stalled around November 1932; by March 1933, activity was back below July 1932 levels
- Wholesale prices fell through their July 1932 lows: Bureau of Labor wholesale price index was 6.6% below June 1932 by February 1933
- Equity prices at 1933 lows remained **20% above** July 1932 levels — stocks led commodities
- Sustained commodity price advance finally began February 1933, coinciding with the most dramatic phase of the 1932–1937 bull market

### Key Lesson: Watch for Stabilization, Don't Forecast the Level
- **Increasing stability in commodity/wholesale prices is an important indicator that the stock market bottom is near**
- In 1921: sign of sustainability was producers unwilling to sell forward + very low inventory levels
- Same signals appeared in summer 1932 (*WSJ* reported "Anti-Deflation Forces Spread"):
  - Fed purchases of government securities
  - Excessively low return on capital in New York
  - Probable cut in NY rediscount rate
  - Bank of England cooperation; rate cut from 6% to 2.5%
  - British Treasury accumulated £13.5M in gold since March
  - Idle capital piling up in Paris and Switzerland
  - Suspension of gold standard and currency depreciation in many countries
  - Continued gold flow from India

### Impossibility of Forecasting the Price Bottom
- In 1921, many predicted prices must return to pre-war levels — they didn't have to; markets bottomed earlier
- In 1932, the wholesale price index sank through the 1921 cyclical low, through 1913 pre-war level, through 1907 levels — falling to 1907
- Commodity-level carnage: **Procter & Gamble** cut Ivory soap to its 1879 launch price; sugar at 1895 levels; copper, lead, zinc at 50-year lows; cotton market bottomed near 1848 levels
- Conclusion: watching for price stabilization signs was far easier and more useful than forecasting a "correct" price level

### Notable Quotes at the Bottom
> "In the 93 years of my life, depressions have come and gone. Prosperity has always returned, and will again."
> — **John D. Rockefeller**, announcement released 8 July 1932 (the day the DJIA bottomed)

- Rockefeller (fortune >$200B in today's terms, larger than Gates and Buffett combined) was also bullish on 30 October 1929:

> "Believing that fundamental conditions of the country are sound and that there is nothing in the business situation to warrant the destruction of values that has taken place… my son and I have for some days been purchasing sound common stocks."
> — **John D. Rockefeller**, 30 October 1929

---

## Liquidity and the Bear

*Epigraph: James T. Farrell, Judgement Day — on the impossibility of safely holding money anywhere*

### Why Liquidity Was So Hard to Read
- The **Federal Reserve System** (created 1914) made liquidity forecasting far more complex than under the gold standard
- In 1918–20, the elastic currency expanded well beyond predictions to finance WWI; contraction continued long after the 1921 bottom
- Those waiting for Fed credit outstanding to stabilize as a buy signal were **still waiting in mid-1924** — three years after the bottom
- This explains the near-absence of positive liquidity commentary in the *WSJ* in summer 1932

### The Internal Fed Battle (1929–1932)
- Long-standing conflict: **Federal Reserve Bank of New York** vs. **Federal Reserve Board**
- NY Fed plunged into the market in October 1929 buying **$160M of government securities** despite only $25M explicit Board authorization — Board strongly disapproved
- Board's view: open-market purchases delay necessary liquidation and promote speculation
- NY Fed lobbied for elastic currency expansion from November 1929 through sterling's devaluation in September 1931
- **Governor Benjamin Strong** (NY Fed's persuasive voice) died in 1928 — denting New York's influence
- Board held the upper hand; Fed credit outstanding showed no increase until late summer 1931

### The April 1932 Open-Market Program
- From August to October 1931, total bills/securities held by Fed rose from $930M to **$2,062M** — but equity market didn't respond (sterling devalued simultaneously)
- Program halted when gold drained from US following sterling's departure from gold standard
- January 1932: NY Fed again pushed the Board for open-market purchases
- **April 1932**: Board authorized major securities purchases — widely attributed to **Congressional pressure** (fear of legislative action), not genuine policy conversion
- Fed credit expansion essentially ceased when **Congress adjourned on 16 July**

**Figure 59 — Federal Reserve Bills & Securities Discounted (peaks/troughs):**
| Period | Amount |
|---|---|
| Peak October 1920 | $3,358M |
| Trough July 1924 | $827M |
| Peak December 1928 | $1,766M |
| Trough July 1931 | $906M |
| Peak October 1931 | $2,062M |
| Trough March 1932 | $1,635M |
| Highest March 1932–March 1933 | $2,407M |

### Why the Liquidity Injection Didn't Work
- Fed's open-market purchases merely **offset gold outflows** — no net injection
- Chicago bank failures caused further public cash withdrawals; currency in circulation rose $32M June 8–July 6
- A 2¢ check tax also incentivized cash-holding over deposits
- Banks recognized the program as politically driven and were cautious deploying funds
- **Guaranty Trust Company** (June 1): banks would make loans when domestic consumption picked up — "A resumption of normal purchasing by the public will be quickly followed by an expansion of bank loans. The latter must follow, but cannot precede, such action."
- *WSJ* (June 16): even pawnbrokers flush with liquidity — public unwilling to borrow at any price
- By June 1932, increase in member bank reserves was **only half** the amount lost since the second banking crisis began
- Commercial bank loans continued declining until **April 1933** — the transmission mechanism failed entirely

### The Indirect Effect Hypothesis
- Something did happen: commodity prices began rising and the economy began recovering — but **not via credit creation**
- Possible indirect channel: Fed action reduced public fear → improved deposit-currency ratio → stabilized commodity prices
- Amount of currency held by public peaked July 1932; deposit-currency ratio improved marginally thereafter
- Key lesson: **betting on Fed easing as the equity buy signal was extremely dangerous**
  - Buying in August 1931 (first open-market program) → exposed to further 69% decline in DJIA
  - Buying in April 1932 (second program) → lost one-third by July 1932

### The Limits of Monetary Analysis at the Bottom
- Broad money and credit growth gave no useful signal: total US commercial bank loans didn't bottom until **1935**
- Broad money growth (nominal or real) didn't show improvement until Q1 1933
- South Carolina mill workers were accepting **cloth as payment** — the very use of money was in question
- In Paris, American gold double-eagles traded at a **25% premium** on the curb; gold slivers cut from bullion
- Conclusion: "In such extreme situations, crunching monetary statistics in the search for evidence of financial stability is probably not the best use of one's time."

---

## The Bulls and the Bear — WSJ Market Chronicle, May–August 1932

*Epigraph: James T. Farrell, Judgement Day*

### Key Thesis
- Both in 1921 and 1932, investors who watched for **returning price stability** as the market turning point were proven correct
- Liquidity analysis was fraught with problems in both bottoms
- In the investment trenches, tactical signals often matter more than strategic monetary analysis

**Figure 60** — DJIA, 8 May to 8 October 1932: bottomed ~8 July, rallied from ~41 to ~80 by September, then pulled back to ~60 by October

### WSJ Day-by-Day Market Notes (Selected)

**May 1932 — Still Falling**
- **9 May**: Absence of upside momentum due to unusually small short interest and lack of inducement for important buying; sharpest upswing in months on Hoover budget-balance plea
- **12 May**: Volume rising on advances, volume declining on declines — early constructive sign
- **13 May**: Inflation policy by government would trigger stock price rise
- **26 May**: Sharp volume increase signals market may be "approaching a climax"
- **28 May**: GE cuts quarterly dividend 60%; AT&T hits new low; market interest "practically non-existent"

**June 1932 — Approaching Bottom**
- **2 June**: DJIA down ~60% since March 8; "the very depth of the decline seems to indicate that the market is somewhere near a turn"; Senate passes tax bill
- **6 June**: Each recovery so far had been "swiftly followed by a reaction" — market fears another false dawn
- **16 June**: Volume increases on advances, subsides on declines — classic constructive pattern; leading stocks performing best, evidence of "concerted buying"
- **17 June**: Bond market leading; "without an advance in bonds, permanent improvement in stocks can hardly be anticipated"
- **21 June**: Daily volume hits **400,000 shares** — lowest since June 1924; vs. 16,410,000 on Black Tuesday (October 29, 1929); General Motors alone traded 971,300 shares on that single day
- **25 June**: More than 50% of stocks trading **under $10/share**; 226 of 422 issues sold at $10 or less; not one common stock sold at $100 or better
- **28 June**: DJIA breaks May low — under Dow Theory, confirms bear market continuation; "long deflation is not over"
- **29 June**: New lows: US Steel, Coca-Cola, General Motors, National Biscuit, Sears-Roebuck, Union Pacific, AT&T

**July 1932 — The Bottom and Early Rally**
- **2 July**: WSJ recommends quality stocks with "fair modicum of earning power": AT&T, Consolidated Gas, Pacific Gas & Electric, Chesapeake & Ohio, American Tobacco, P&G, William Wrigley Jr., Borden, Corn Products
- **3 July**: Rail average holding above June low — Dow Theory signal still ambiguous; "clear signs of resistance to selling pressure in the rails"
- **8 July**: **[DJIA bottoms]**
- **12 July**: 67 stocks were trading **50%+ above their 1932 lows** the day the market bottomed — advance guard was already building
- **14 July**: Anglo-French accord on European financial matters; foreign buying of American stocks returning
- **15 July**: Congressional adjournment expected to be a catalyst; market holding in face of unfavourable news
- **20 July**: Interims showing poor earnings — but "securities of most companies reporting have long since discounted this fact"
- **22 July**: DJIA up 13% from lows; Aluminium Co. 80% above its 1932 low
- **25 July**: Bond advance starting to feed through to stocks via margin collateral — "any sharp rise in bonds gives such accounts greater buying power"
- **26 July**: Volume dries up on dips, surges on advances — **direct reversal** of the prior bear pattern (March–June: volume rose on declines, dried up on recoveries)
- **30 July**: "Trend line from September 1929 finally broken — conclusive technical evidence that the major bear movement has definitely been succeeded not by a minor recovery but by a bull swing"

**August 1932 — Confirmation**
- Bear short-covering (forward dollar shorts from "flight from dollar" spring 1932) accelerating the rally
- **5 August**: New highs in most active market since October 1931
- **9 August**: European capitals buying American stocks at highest pace since 1929 crash
- **12 August**: Security loans declined $112M in July to lowest level on record — total security loans down $8.518B from peak of $13.205B on September 30, 1929
- **13 August**: Market ignoring poor business figures; focusing on indices pointing to an upturn — a **change in market psychology**
- **16 August**: London led the summer rally (broker circular on July 26 showed American blue chips yielding 10.4% on average); NYSE seat price: $150,000, up 25% from prior sale (low for year: $68,000)

### Key Behavioral Signals at the Bottom

**Signal 1 — Market stops responding negatively to bad news**
- "One key change… was that the market in general, and specific securities in particular, stopped posting negative price reactions when bad news was announced"
- A subtle shift from a market that had reacted to every bad headline

**Signal 2 — Selective advance before the average bottoms**
- 67 issues were trading 50%+ above their 1932 lows on the day the average bottomed (8 July)
- Common trait: these stocks benefited from higher commodity prices, especially sugar
- This suggests **buying power was building** beneath the surface before the index turned

**Signal 3 — AT&T weakness as capitulation signal**
- AT&T was the most widely-held stock; major one-day declines made headlines
- Its "air pockets" possibly indicated small investors **finally throwing in the towel** (last bulls becoming bears)

**Signal 4 — "Safe" sector collapse**
- Food stocks fell 23.2% in May; tobacco fell 21.3% — vs. average monthly bear-market declines of 3.4% and 1.3%
- Caveat: food sector fell 27.9% and tobacco 21.3% in September 1930 — those who bought on that "capitulation" lost half their money by July 1932
- This signal is only useful **in conjunction with other indicators**

**Signal 5 — Volume pattern reversal (most reliable)**
- From March to June 1932: volume rose on declines, dried up on recoveries
- From June 1932 onward: volume rose on advances, dried up on dips — **same constructive pattern noted at the 1921 bottom**
- Interpreted as: fewer sellers willing to liquidate, arrival of "big constructive interests" buying on strength

<!-- pp. 221-240 -->

## 1932 Bottom — Continued Analysis

### Short Sellers and Capitulation

- In 1932, unlike 1921, short positions **continued to increase** from
  the market bottom (8 July) through 27 July — DJIA rose 29% in that
  span, meaning shorts endured severe pain before capitulating
- Bears not covering quickly was actually a **positive sign** for
  sustainability — fewer forced short-covering rallies, more room for
  genuine buying to drive prices higher
- Popular belief: bear markets end with a **capitulation event** —
  sharp final decline on high volume as last bulls sell out
- **Reality in both 1921 and 1932:** final decline occurred on *low*
  volume; high volume only developed *after* the initial rise began
- Pattern: **volume rises after the bottom, not at the bottom** —
  more reliable indicator than the "high-volume capitulation" myth

### Earnings Recovery — Irrelevant at the Bottom

- Investors awaiting earnings recovery **missed the July 1932 bottom**
  entirely — Cowles Foundation data shows S&P earnings bottomed
  December 1932, not visible to investors until Q2 1933
- 1933 earnings were only 7% above 1932 levels; 1934 earnings grew
  just 11%; not until 1935 (earnings +55%) was cyclical recovery clear
- **DJIA bottomed 8 July 1932 at 41.22** — investors waiting for
  earnings clarity were buying in early summer 1933 at ~2x the bottom
- Second leg of bull market (March 1935 – Feb 1937) nearly doubled
  again — earnings-focused investors caught this leg but missed the
  first (and more explosive) move
- Listed companies (S&P data) never reported aggregate losses through
  the Depression — but *all* US corporations (Harold Borger data) were
  deeply in the red: aggregate corporate profits went from +$1,696M
  (3Q 1929) to -$677M (3Q 1932)

### Shareholder Count as a Signal

- In both 1921 and 1932, rising **shareholder counts** were tracked as
  a bullish indicator — counterintuitively, bear markets saw shares
  move into *more* hands (public accumulation)
- R.G. Dun & Co.: among 346 monitored companies, stockholder count
  rose 42% from May 1930 to May 1932
- **US Steel shareholder diffusion** was used for market timing for
  decades — when price fell below the shareholder count on a scaled
  chart, that was a buy signal (worked in 1903, 1914, 1920, 1923)
- In 1929–32, US Steel shareholder count almost doubled — investors
  fleeing speculative issues to safety of the country's largest firm
- Signal misfired in early 1931 (premature buy), bringing the method
  into disrepute — but direction remained informative
- At the *actual* bottom: stocks moved *back* from the public to
  professionals, stock brokers, and rich capitalists — concentration
  of shares into bigger hands marked the bull market's return, not
  a surge of public enthusiasm

### The Fiscal Red Herring

- The *WSJ* obsessively attributed the March–July 1932 plunge to
  **fiscal deterioration** — DJIA halved in four months, exceeding
  the October 1929 crash and both banking crises in severity
- Contemporary view: unbalanced budget caused the final crash; balanced
  budget was prerequisite for equity/bond recovery
- **This was wrong.** Budget deficit was only 0.60% of GDP in 1931
  (small by historical standards — in 1837, the worst US contraction,
  deficit peaked at 0.68%); deficit then ballooned to 4.6% (1932),
  4.61% (1933), 5.50% (1934) — while one of history's greatest bull
  markets was underway
- Roosevelt, endorsed by Democrats in July 1932, was also loudly
  demanding a balanced budget — if this drove equity recovery, it was
  misguided policy coinciding with a bottom, not its cause
- **Calling for a balanced budget as a precondition for equity
  recovery was the most erroneous investment judgement of 1932**

> 'Have we a government? That is surely a "mouthful". Was there ever
> before such a shameless and cheap bunch of politicians in Washington?'
> — Letter to the *Wall Street Journal*, 17 May 1932

### What Actually Caused the Final Plunge (March–July 1932)

- The real culprit was a **drain on US gold reserves**, not fiscal
  concerns — monetary gold stock contracted 12% (Jan–July 1932) to
  $3.65 billion
- Two compounding factors caused gold outflow:
  1. **Trade deterioration** — partner countries had devalued; US
     trade surplus had already halved 1930–31; UK imported only 396
     US autos in first four months of 1932 vs. 5,188 in all of 1928
  2. **Fed's April 1932 open market purchase program** — interpreted
     by foreign investors as a precursor to abandoning the gold standard,
     triggering capital flight
- Gold outflow stopped when Fed ended its purchase program *and*
  Congress adjourned — both happened simultaneously with the bottom
- The *WSJ* (called "the Republican bible" by Truman) blamed worsening
  political odds of a Democratic president for the gold drain — a
  partisan misread of structural currency dynamics

### The Lausanne Agreement — The Actual Catalyst

- One event unique to 1932 helped relieve the gold drain and bottom
  the market: the **Lausanne Conference** on German war reparations
- Germany had been in perpetual reparation crisis since Versailles:
  defaulted 1921 → Ruhr occupation by France/Belgium → hyperinflation
  → **Dawes Plan** (1924) rescheduled debt → **Young Plan** (1929)
  reduced burden → Hoover moratorium (summer 1931) on war debts
- At Lausanne, parties surprised markets by agreeing to abolish
  Germany's reparation obligations in return for bonds — a de facto
  **90% reduction** in Germany's financial burden
  - Secret side agreement: US would cancel Allied war debts (Congress
    later refused to honor this)
- **Market impact:** news seen as breaking the international financial
  logjam; commodity markets rallied sharply on expectation of increased
  demand from debtor nations; German bonds jumped 10 points in days
- Swiss franc weakened after Lausanne — "unemployed capital" that had
  fled to gold-backed Switzerland was seen moving back into productive
  use globally — read as positive for financial markets

### German Politics and Market Sentiment

- **Adolf Hitler** defeated by Paul von Hindenburg in April 1932
  presidential election — markets welcomed this; *WSJ* consistently
  called him a "shoddy leader"
- Nazi party failed to increase its vote in 31 July Reichstag
  elections — Wall Street interpreted this as improving odds of
  "order" in Germany, positive for US-held German government bonds

> 'The opinion is growing that the Hitler movement has reached its
> peak in Germany and that the Nazi party will continue to be a
> troublesome element to those seeking orderly government, Herr Hitler
> will not be able to secure control of the government.'
> — *Wall Street Journal*, 1932

### Dow Theory — Second Successful Bear Bottom Call

- **Dow Theory scored again in 1932**, as in 1921 — both railroad
  and industrial averages moved to fractional new lows; *WSJ* Dow
  experts noted this could signal a double bottom rather than a
  confirmed breakdown
- **Robert Rhea** (successor to William Peter Hamilton as leading
  Dow theorist, independent commentator) called the bottom of the
  great bear market on 21 July 1932 — two-for-two for Dow Theory
- Fractional penetration of prior lows: per Dow Theory, requires
  *more* than fractional penetration to qualify as a definitive
  bearish signal — a fractional new low can be a double bottom

---

## Bonds and the Bear (1932)

> 'I remember the panics of 1907, and 1893, and they were bad. But
> not as bad as now. I don't know how many millions of men there's
> on the streets.'
> — James T. Farrell, *Judgement Day*

### The Paradox: Government Bonds Fell in Deflation

- In a deflationary depression, **US government bond prices declined**
  — deeply counterintuitive; most investors would expect deflation
  plus rising credit risk to push investors into safe-haven Treasuries
- Long-term government bond yield: 3.70% (Sept 1929) → 3.15% by
  June 1931 (normal safe-haven behavior) → then spiked to 4.26% by
  January 1932 — over a period when wholesale prices fell 31%
- Sterling's departure from the gold standard (Sept 1931) was the
  trigger: foreign central banks liquidated US dollar assets, gold
  stock declined; domestic depositors simultaneously hoarded cash
  over deposits → banks forced to liquidate government bonds
- NY Fed raised rediscount rate from 1.5% to 3.5% on 16 October 1931
  to defend gold standard exchange rate — further pressure on bonds
- **Government bond stabilisation** came in early 1932 — likely due
  to establishment of the **Reconstruction Finance Corporation (RFC)**
  in January 1932 (borrowing power $1.5B, expanded to $3.3B by July
  Emergency Relief and Construction Act) — lent to banks, reducing
  need to liquidate bonds; also Fed bond-buying from April 1932

### The Corporate Bond Collapse

- Corporate bond investors initially expected a normal recession after
  October 1929 crash — **Baa-rated bond yields actually declined**
  from Sept 1929 (6.12%) through most of 1930, reaching 5.65% by
  Sept 1930
- First banking crisis (3Q 1930) ended the complacency — by Nov 1930
  Baa yields had exceeded Sept 1929 levels; by Dec 1930 exceeded 6.7%
- **Second banking crisis and internationalisation (1931)** triggered
  the real crash in corporate debt: Baa yields jumped from 6.72%
  (April 1931) to 10.42% (December 1931)
- Corporate bond bottom: **June 1932** — Baa yield peaked at 11.52%,
  one-third higher than the highest yield ever previously recorded
  (data available from 1919)
- AAA corporate bonds: peak yield 5.41% in June 1932 (highest since
  December 1921); Dow Jones 40-bond average fell to new all-time low
- Corporate bond market bottomed ~5 weeks **before** the equity
  market bottom in July 1932

### What Turned the Corporate Bond Market

- **RFC provision of credit** to distressed banks and railroads
  alleviated forced selling pressure — key institutional mechanism
- **American Securities Investment Corporation** — pool formed by
  major US commercial banks to buy bonds collectively, spreading risk;
  market surged on announcement; actual buying occurred above the lows
- Commercial banks, starved of lending opportunities, became large
  bond buyers; corporations bought their own bonds at <50 cents on
  the dollar
- **Lausanne Agreement** directly boosted corporate bonds — German
  bonds jumped 10 points; WSJ reported growing evidence commodities
  were stabilising (Fisher's wholesale price index posted 3 consecutive
  weeks of gains in mid-July; by August "advance sustained for more
  than two months")
- Garner Plan (proposed $1B bond issuance for public works) worried
  bond investors about supply dilution — never became law; **fears
  proved misplaced**, deficits ballooned without producing bond
  sell-off; bond bull market 1932–1949

### Key Sequencing at the 1932 Bottom

- **Government bonds bottomed:** January 1932
- **Corporate bonds bottomed:** early June 1932
- **Equity market bottomed:** 8 July 1932
- **Commodity prices stabilising:** visible by late May 1932
- Commodity stabilisation led corporate bonds by ~2 weeks and equities
  by ~6 weeks — deflationary process ending was the foundational signal
- The June 1931 to January 1932 setback in government bonds (yields
  3.13% → 4.11%) disrupted investor perception of "fair value" across
  all financial assets — rising risk-free rates during deflation and
  falling earnings was a maximally hostile valuation environment

<!-- pp. 241-260 -->

## Section: Closing Arguments on the 1932 Bottom (cont.)

### Bond Market Stabilization — One-Off Factors

- **American Securities Investment Corp (ASI)** formed as government-bond buying
  by the Fed failed to create credit growth; pooled commercial banker funds to
  buy bonds, spreading purchaser risk — mere *announcement* triggered a
  substantial bond rally without the ASI initially buying a single bond
- **RFC** (Reconstruction Finance Corporation) also stabilized government bond
  prices, improved bank liquidity, and improved credit quality in key sectors
  (notably railways)
- **British war loan conversion**: Britain's £2 billion 5% war loan converted to
  a 3.5% perpetual loan; WSJ reported "frantic scenes of excitement" on London
  Stock Exchange — 4% consols rose 8 points to £110 — just days before the
  US equity bottom; likely redirected capital to US securities
- Key bottom-line: as in 1921, the decisive stabilizing force was the
  **stabilization of commodity and wholesale prices**, not policy gimmicks alone

### Roosevelt and the Bear

> *'But getting back to politics, boys, this spring is only going to be a preview
> of the presidential election in 1932. Then we'll have Democrats all the way
> from the White House to the street cleaners on every block.'*
> — James T. Farrell, *Judgement Day*

- The Democratic convention began 27 June 1932; Roosevelt was front-runner but
  outcome uncertain until 1 July
- **Counterintuitive**: WSJ reported that Roosevelt as likely President was
  *depressing*, not supporting, equity prices — markets preferred a compromise
  "business-friendly" candidate
- When Roosevelt won the nomination and gave his acceptance speech on 2 July,
  it became increasingly clear he would be the next president
- **John Nance Garner** (VP running mate) said Democrats needed only to "sit
  still and keep quiet" to win
- Roosevelt campaign sent **contradictory signals**:
  - Radical: called for "bold experimentation" and redistribution of national
    income; capital must accept smaller returns (Oglethorpe commencement, 23 May)
  - Conservative: promised to cut government spending 25% and balance the budget
    (Pittsburgh speech, 19 October) — criticized Hoover for spending too much
- **Paradox**: Roosevelt attacked deficit spending while Hoover defended it —
  speeches "seemed to have gotten mixed up"
- **Guaranty Trust Co.** told clients on eve of Democratic Convention that the
  presidential election was "largely imaginary" in its economic influence —
  contemporary expert view was that Roosevelt's election would reduce or have
  no material impact on financial markets

### Roosevelt's Election: NOT the Cause of the Bull Market

- Napier's conclusion: **Roosevelt's nomination was coincidental with, not
  causal of, the July 1932 equity bottom**
- The first setback for the bull market began *with* Roosevelt's November
  election and lasted until his March inauguration — markets feared his gold
  standard commitment
- Despite Roosevelt's radical New Deal policies, one of the greatest equity
  bull markets in US history followed

> *There had never been a bear market like the bear market of 1929-32. The market
> declined 89%, far surpassing the worst previous market declines of 45% in the
> panics of 1857 and 1907. As in 1921, equity prices did not stop declining
> until they reached a 70% discount to replacement value.*

- Key difference from 1921: Fed discount rate cut came at the **beginning** of
  the bear market, not the end
- The 1932 economic and price recovery was not sustainable — but the DJIA held
  above its July 1932 lows; investors who bought then made spectacular returns
  over five years

---

## Part III: June 1949

> *When we isolate the four most profitable times to invest in stocks, June 1949
> comes second on our list after July 1932, but well ahead of 1942.*

- June 1949 ranks #2 for long-term returns (40-year horizon benefits from
  1982-89 bull market)
- April 1942 was also a rare bear bottom (q ratio below 0.3x) but subsequent
  returns from 1949 significantly exceeded those from 1942 — **1949 was better**
- The 1940s represented Depression-era sentiment dragging equities to deep
  discounts throughout the entire decade

### The Road to June 1949

- World utterly transformed from 1932: WWII killed 55 million, US military grew
  from 250,000 to 12+ million; 300,000 Americans did not return
- By 1949: 10 million Americans had re-entered civilian life; government now
  accounted for a much larger share of economic activity; public was a heavy
  holder of government bonds
- **Equity market a backwater**: daily NYSE turnover often below $500,000;
  speculative enthusiasm focused on property, not stocks
- On 13 June 1949 — the day DJIA hit its postwar low — a NY Times headline
  was about a heat wave ("1,500,000 Cool off at City's Beaches")

### The Course of the Dow — 1932-37

- July 1932 to March 1937: one of the **greatest equity bull markets in US
  history** — DJIA rose from 41.22 to 194.15, a **370% gain** with GDP
  deflator rising only 11%
- Dividend yield at the July 1932 bottom: **10%**; dividends grew 60% to 1937
- Underpinning: increasing **financial system solvency** from 1933 onward;
  net national product grew **12% per annum** (real) from trough 1933 to peak
  1937 — "Such economic growth rates have not been recorded before or since"
- S&P Composite earnings rose **176%** from 1932 to 1937 — nearly 3x faster
  than nominal GDP
- Despite this, 1937 earnings still below 1929, 1928, 1926, 1925, 1917, 1916
  levels; dividends 49% below 1929 peak; market itself 49% below August 1929
- Powerful combination: **surging earnings + surging dividends + falling
  interest rates** (excess capacity kept inflation low despite rapid growth)

### Volume Collapse — Evidence of Investor Disengagement

- From 1929 record trading day to 1942 low: NYSE volume fell **99%**
- 1942 dollar volume of equity trades was below 1901 levels; 70% below 1932
- **Turnover ratio**: 119% of listed shares traded in 1929 → 30% in 1937 →
  9% in 1942 → only 13% by 1949
- Bear market disinterest in 1949 was *higher* than even the worst Depression
  years of 1921 and 1932 (where turnover was 59% and 32% respectively)
- NYSE market cap in 1949 **exceeded** the 1929 level — almost no one wanted
  to participate

### NYSE Seat Prices — The Insiders' Verdict

- 1929: NYSE seat worth $495,000
- 1932: dropped ~90%, to $68,000 low
- 1942: dropped further to $17,000 — a 75% decline from 1932 even as DJIA
  doubled; a remarkable gauge of insider disillusionment
- Recovered 1942–1946, then slid again to 1949 bottom ($35,000 low)
- Long-run apathy toward equities persisted **long after** the worst Depression
  was over

### The 1949 Valuation Paradox

- By June 1949, DJIA was at its February 1926 level — 57% below the 1929
  all-time high, nearly 20 years of zero capital progress
- Within 1932–1949: **two bull markets** (1932-37, 1942-46) and **two bear
  markets** (1937-42, 1946-49)
- Why focus on 1949 rather than 1942 if index doesn't go lower? Napier's
  criterion: **subsequent long-term returns** and **q ratio** — both better
  from 1949; q ratio re-fell below 0.3x by June 1949

### The New Deal Bull Market — Radical Policy, Rising Stocks

- Recovery (Nov 1932 – March 1933 interregnum) completely reversed: third
  banking crisis; Nevada bank holiday Oct 1932; by 3 March 1933 **half of
  US states had suspended banking operations**
- NBER: economy reached its absolute low in March 1933 — marginally below
  June 1932
- Roosevelt's March 1933 Inaugural Address declared: "the money changers have
  fled their high seats in the temple of our civilization"
- New Deal legislation cascade: *Securities Act* 1933 → *Glass-Steagall* 1933
  → *Securities Exchange Act* 1934 → *Banking Act* 1935 → *Public Utility
  Holding Company Act* 1935 — **bull market continued through all of it**
- Roosevelt's gold moves:
  - Day 2 in office: "temporary" bar on gold exports
  - 19 April 1933: endorsed **Thomas Amendment** to Agricultural Adjustment
    Act — empowered president to issue unbacked currency
  - **Lewis Douglas** (Budget Director): "This is the end of Western
    Civilization"
  - Roosevelt criminalized gold hoarding and abrogated gold payment contracts
  - Dollar devalued: gold price went from $20.67/oz to $35/oz (Jan 1934)
  - Not until mid-January 1934 did FDR announce return to gold standard
- **Key paradox**: despite abandoning the gold standard, criminalizing gold
  hoarding, launching socialist-era regulation, and devaluing the dollar by
  70%, the bull market in equities **raged on**

### Pecora Hearings

- Hoover had asked Congress to investigate the exchange even as market bottomed
- **Senate Banking Committee "Pecora hearings"** (chief counsel **Ferdinand
  Pecora**) began April 1932, continued through May 1934
- Produced lurid headlines, ample evidence of Wall Street misdeeds; some
  convictions not secured until the 1940s
- Bull market continued throughout

### The "Socialism" Minority

- 1932-37: a vocal minority called the New Deal "socialism" and argued
  ideological "attack" on financial markets was underway — ample evidence for
  the concern
- In conjunction with banking/financial regulation, government created state
  agencies for services deemed unsuitable for the private sector
- Yet: **fundamentals overwhelmed the fears** — the earnings/dividend/rate
  trifecta drove prices regardless of political backdrop

<!-- pp. 261-280 -->

## New Deal State Expansion & The 1937-42 Bear

### Government Encroachment and Fiscal Deficits
- **Reconstruction Finance Corporation** (created by Hoover, massively expanded by Roosevelt)
  became the largest company in the world
- Federal Home Loan banks (1932), Home Owner's Loan Corp (1933),
  Tennessee Valley Authority (1933), Federal Farm Mortgage Corp (1934)
- National minimum wage introduced; social security taxes raised labour costs further
- Pre-Roosevelt, the largest peacetime fiscal deficit was 0.7% of GDP (1837 crash)
- Deficit hit 4.7% of GDP in 1932 and peaked at **5.5% of GDP in 1934**

> "There can be only one capital – Washington or Moscow. There can only be one atmosphere of government, the clear, fresh air of free America or the foul breath of Communistic Russia."
> — **Al Smith**, former Democratic presidential candidate, January 1936

- Despite socialist fears, the bull market raged on — the equity market judged earnings
  recovery and financial stabilisation more important than structural impairments

---

## The Course of the Dow – 1937-42

### The 1937 Recession Within the Depression
- By peak of recovery in 1937, **unemployment still at 14.3%** — half again the pre-1930 high
- Economy reversed before any meaningful employment recovery — shook faith
  in the business cycle
- Fed began raising **reserve requirements** in August 1936; also raised margin on
  security purchases from 25% to 50% (using new powers from the **Banking Act**)
- Wholesale prices rising + rising stock market → Fed wanted to retighten
- Fed blamed the subsequent contraction on fiscal tightening; federal deficit/GDP
  fell from 4.2% (1936) to 2.8% (1937)
- Other factors: sharp drop in corporate profitability from higher labour costs
- Result: industrial production fell one-third from 1937 peak to 1938 low;
  **S&P earnings declined almost 50%**
- Cyclical trough: June 1938 — just two months after first Fed reserve requirement reduction
- In 12 months from March 1937, **DJIA declined 49%**, back to mid-1933 levels
- Key psychological damage: this recession-within-depression produced more antipathy
  toward equities than the Depression itself

### Equities Fail to Recover with Earnings (1938-41)
- From 1938 low, S&P earnings doubled by December 1941 — but **DJIA unchanged**
- Investors had lost faith in the economy returning to pre-1929 normalcy
- In an era of waning confidence, equities could ignore even strong earnings recoveries

### War and the Market (1939-41)
- UK declared war on Germany: no panic on Wall Street — **DJIA rose 15%**
  in first 8 trading days of September 1939
- Investors recalled US neutrality in WWI: flight capital and "war bride" stocks
  benefited from European orders 1915-16
- Hitler's **blitzkrieg** (10 May 1940): Netherlands and Belgium surrendered,
  Dunkirk evacuation → **DJIA declined 23%** in 15 days
- Flight capital dried up; US war orders now likely only from UK, expected to
  pay in IOUs of dubious quality — the 1915-16 positives would not recur
- **Lend-Lease** programme announced December 1940, began March 1941 —
  US receiving credit/services instead of cash/gold; market disliked it
- Sep 1940 to 6 Dec 1941: **DJIA declined 14%** as lend-lease expanded
- Wholesale prices rose 23% (Aug 1939–Nov 1941) on raw material demand
- **Regulation W** (1 Sep 1941): Fed imposed consumer credit controls —
  min down-payments, max maturities
- 1 Nov 1941: Fed raised reserve requirement to maximum 25%
- **Pearl Harbor** (7 Dec 1941): market continued gradual decline — took
  five more months to fall another 20%, bottoming **28 April 1942**
- April 1942: **q ratio** showed equities at 70%+ discount to replacement value —
  a level only seen in 1921 and 1932

---

## The Course of the Dow – 1942-46

### Fed Pegs the Yield Curve
- April 1942: Fed stated it would fix **Treasury bill rate at 0.375%** for duration of war
- In practice created a **capped federal debt yield curve** — remained until March 1951
- De facto maximum yield on longest-term government bonds: **2.5%**
- Rationale: encourage War Bond purchases, reduce financing costs
- Commercial banks (unlike WWI) used expanded reserves to buy government
  securities directly; between 1941-45, Treasury made seven war-bond issues
  without surging yields

**Figure 74 — WWII Yield Support Schedule:**
| Security | Capped Yield |
|---|---|
| Treasury bills | 0.375% |
| 1-yr certificates | 0.875% |
| Short bonds | 2.0% |
| Longer bonds | 2.25% |
| 25-30 yr bonds | 2.50% |

> During this period, the Fed, in the words of its chairman **Marriner Eccles**,
> 'merely executed Treasury decisions.'

- From April 1942, monthly prime corporate bond yield fell from 2.63%,
  averaging 2.55% in 1942-46
- With bonds yielding ~2.5% and equities yielding **11%+ in 1942**, the relative
  case for equities was compelling
- Reported inflation 4% annually (Nov 1941–Aug 1945) — but **price controls**
  (introduced Jan 1942) and rationing suppressed the headline; real inflation
  (black market) was higher, making bonds even less attractive

### Wartime Headwinds for Equities
- Tax receipts as % of GNP: 7% in 1941 → **21% in 1945**; top income tax rate hit **90%**
  (vs. 66.3% in WWI)
- Corporate profit margins controlled by:
  - **War Production Board**
  - **War Labor Board**
  - **Office of Price Administration**
- Corporate tax: top rate rose from 19% (1940) to 40% (1942);
  **excess profits tax** reached flat rate of **95% by 1943**
- Result: S&P earnings and dividends basically unchanged in 1946 from 1942 levels
- The 1942-46 bull market was driven **entirely by valuation expansion**,
  not earnings growth — against a background of negative real bond yields

### War News vs. Market Behaviour
- DJIA bottomed 28 April 1942 — US nadir: Philippines fell (Bataan 9 April,
  Corregidor 6 May)
- By June 1942: Battle of Midway; August: Guadalcanal landing
- November 1942: El Alamein victory; Soviet counter-offensive encircled Hitler's
  Sixth Army at Stalingrad
- Despite all this positive news, **DJIA traded sideways July 1943 to end of 1944**
  while Allies liberated Paris, Brussels, Rome, etc.
- Bull market only resumed early 1945; accelerated only after **VJ Day**
- January 1946: margin requirements raised from 75% to 100%

> "Strongly fortified by elimination of excess profits taxes, net earnings of industrial
> companies as a group promise to be some 30% higher than in 1945… Dividends in total
> should increase fully proportionately with earnings."
> — **Harry D Comer**, Paine Webber Jackson & Curtis, *WSJ*, 2 January 1946

- Bull market peaked May 1946 — **DJIA still 44% below September 1929 all-time high**

---

## The Course of the Dow – 1946-49

### The Postwar Bear: Inflation vs. Deflation Debate
- Bulls expected: pent-up consumer demand boom + return of corporate tax rates to normal
- Bears remembered: post-WWI Armistice produced soaring inflation → sharpest
  annual deflation in US history + vicious bear market
- DJIA ranged 163-190 for two years after Aug-Sep 1946 crash (-17%),
  then broke down to low of **162 on 13 June 1949**
- In 1946-49 bear market, **S&P earnings increased nearly 200%** — yet equities fell
- Dividends grew only 31% as companies retained profits for capital investment
- Extraordinary: a 200% earnings boom could not overcome deflation fears

### Sewell Avery and the Historical Analogy Trap
- *James Grant*, **Money of the Mind**: **Sewell Avery** of Montgomery Ward studied a
  commodity price chart going back to the 19th century
  
> "Prices rose and fell recurrently. They rose in wartime inflations and fell in
> subsequent postwar deflations. The pattern had repeated itself as recently as
> 1919-1920… To Avery, a postwar depression was therefore a foregone conclusion.
> 'Who am I to argue with history?' he asked, and kept on asking."

- Avery loaded up on government bonds instead of investing in his business —
  the deflation never came; the bet proved disastrous
- By Jan 1949, even Truman admitted: "We cannot afford to float along ceaselessly
  on a postwar boom until it collapses"

### Why This Time Was Different
- **Employment Act of 1946** enshrined "maximum employment" as government mandate
- No attempt to reconstruct the gold standard — **Bretton Woods** (July 1944) was
  explicitly designed to make deflationary periods less likely
- Government sector now 15% of GDP vs. 3% in late 1920s —
  structural change that could institutionalise inflation
- Non-agricultural union membership: 33% of workforce by 1949 (up from 13% in 1932)
  — wage pressure built into the system
- Wholesale price index rose **32% in 1946** alone (second half) when price controls lifted
- Minority view: this was not a prelude to deflation but "the shape of things to come"

### The Inflation/Deflation Tug-of-War in Financial Markets
- **AAA corporate bond yield** hit all-time low of **2.46% in April 1946**,
  then rose steadily to 2.86% by December 1947
- July 1947: Fed lifted posted buying rate for T-bills (0.375%); T-bill yield
  gradually rose to 1.25% by end of 1948
- First official rate hike: January 1948, +25bps; August 1948, another +25bps → 1.5%
- Reserve requirements raised: February, June, September 1948
- Congress temporarily restored Fed's credit control powers (August 1948, 12 months)
- Economic peak: November 1948; DJIA fell to 162 on 13 June 1949

### Cold War Overlay
- **Winston Churchill**, Missouri, March 1946: "an iron curtain has descended across Europe"
- **Truman Doctrine** (March 1947): financial support to peoples resisting communist subjugation
- **Marshall Plan** → Soviet antagonism; Berlin Blockade May 1948 → Allied airlift
- **NATO** formed April 1949 — Soviets called it "openly aggressive"
- Soviet atomic bomb detonated **29 August 1949** — "hot war" fears
- But Soviet failure to act militarily over NATO eased fears; a "cold war" arms race
  (not a shooting war) was better for equities — echoes of US neutrality/rearmament boom 1915-16

> "For over three years fears of what is now occurring in the business world have dampened
> market sentiment, preventing normal price-earnings relationships. When this weight is
> lifted… There should be room for plenty of cheer in the realisation that:
> There isn't going to be a war…"
> — broker **Sam Smith**, Bache & Co., *WSJ*, 12 July 1949

- By July 1949: deflation finally arrived AND war fears receded simultaneously →
  stage set for a **bull market lasting almost 20 years**

---

## Structure of the Market in 1949

### The Stock Market in 1949
- Total NYSE market cap (end May 1949): **$64 billion** — one-third below Sept 1929,
  but four times the 1932 bottom
- NYSE accounted for ~90% of total US equity market cap
- 1,457 listed equity securities; 1,043 companies; average market cap **$58 million**
- Investment management industry decimated: only **150 investment management companies**
  registered with the SEC in June 1949; total AUM = **$2.7 billion** —
  less than 5% of the US equity market even if fully invested in equities
- Daily trading: ~900 of 1,500 listed issues traded; monthly volume just **$526 million**
  (vs. $1,946 million in January 1946 at the peak)
- Market was trading **half-days on Saturday** — liquidity extremely thin

<!-- pp. 281-300 -->

## 1949 Bear Bottom: Market Structure & Sector Performance

### NYSE Sector Composition: 1932 vs. 1949 (Figure 77)

- Trading volumes collapsed: average daily equity volume in July 1949 was $23.4M;
  the lowest daily volume was $541,360 — 97% below 1929 levels
- **Oil** rose from 10.9% to 16.0% of market cap (1st by 1949);
  **Chemicals** rose from 7.8% to 9.0% (2nd)
- **Utilities** fell from 15.5% to 6.7%; **Tobacco** from 5.5% to 2.3%;
  **Railroads** from 8.7% to 5.1%
- **Retail** and **Autos** grew significantly — both benefited from postwar consumer demand
- Sector shift driven partly by new equity issuance: shares outstanding rose 59%
  while number of listed companies rose only 27%

### Drivers of Sector Change

- **Petrochemicals**: German chemical industry largely destroyed; US companies filled the gap
- **Polyethylene** ("war-born plastic") finding new uses daily; production quadrupled
  to 50M pounds/year
- **Penicillin** exports alone exceeded total prewar US drug exports
- **Autos**: sector had been barred from producing cars during WWII; by 1949 retooling
  to satisfy long waiting lists
- **Oil**: uniquely smooth wartime-to-civilian transition — demand was even higher
  in 1946 than 1945, no product changes needed

### Sector Returns: June 1932 – June 1949 (Figure 78, Best/Worst)

- **Best performers (total return):**
  - Beer: +3,993% (repeal of Prohibition Dec 1933; investors who bought on likelihood
    of Democratic win still richly rewarded)
  - Games: +2,606%
  - Wholesale: +2,396%
  - Autos: +2,201%
  - Services: +2,199%
- **Worst performers:**
  - Utilities: +280%
  - Tobacco: +398%
  - Coal: +489%
  - Communications: +527%

> "The last shall be first and the first last." — Matthew's Gospel (Napier's summary
> of sector rotation from 1929-32 leaders to 1932-49 laggards)

- Sectors that **outperformed** the 1929-32 bear (utilities, tobacco, telecoms)
  **underperformed** in 1932-49 — classic defensive-to-cyclical rotation

### 1946-49 Bear: Mild but Different

- Bear market May 1946 to June 1949: DJIA -24% only (volume down 70%)
- Cheapness came from **earnings boom**, not price collapse
- In this mild bear, **utilities again showed defensive qualities** (only -9.7%
  vs. transport -33.4%, electrical equipment -27.5%)
- **Oil** was the sole large-sector gainer (+5.8%) in 1946-49

---

## The Bond Market in 1949

### Bond Market Scale and Composition

- NYSE-listed bonds: $128B market value in 1949 vs. $32B in 1932
- Government bond price index +16%, corporate high-grade index +43% over same period
- But number of NYSE bond issues fell from 1,600 (1932) to 912 (1949) —
  lowest since 1905; 75 of 912 were US Treasury and World Bank issues
  traded entirely OTC
- **Corporate bond market was shrinking**: from 1932-1945 (ex. 1936, 1938),
  corporate bond retirements exceeded new issues every year
  — net retirements of $42.8B; by 1949 corporate bonds outstanding probably <$30B
- **Government bonds dominated**: federal debt grew from $19.5B (1932) to
  $168.6B (1949 face value), plus $56.3B savings bonds, $82.2B notes/bills
  — federal debt market alone ~3x the equity market

### Bond Trading Volumes: Structural Decline

- Peak NYSE bond trading: 1922, avg $15M/day
- By 1929 equities dominated; bond volumes fell to $11.4M/day
- NYSE bond trading bottomed in 1949: $3M/day average; less than $1B traded
  for entire year — under 1% of $128B outstanding market value
- Government bonds migrated almost entirely OTC:

> "For every $1,000 Government bond sale recorded on the Exchange there were
> $1,000,000 par value unrecorded transactions made by a very few banking houses
> which were known as Government bond dealers." — C.F. Childs,
> *Concerning US Government Securities*

- **Liberty Bonds** post-WWI briefly made govt bonds popular with retail (76%
  of NYSE bond trading in 1919 was govts); as bonds moved to institutions,
  off-market transactions resumed dominance

### Foreign Bond Market: Rise and Collapse

- Pre-WWI: only 2 foreign bonds on NYSE (Argentina, Japan)
- US became world's key creditor after WWI; 1920s saw foreign sovereign bond mania
  with all hallmarks of Britain's 19th Century foreign debt manias
- Peak Sept 1929: 202 foreign bond issues on NYSE, 1/3 of bond trading volume
- By June 1949 DJIA bottom: only 46 foreign issues listed; 20 sovereign issuers remaining
- Countries trading below half par value: Chile, Colombia, Costa Rica, Greece,
  Italy, Mexico, Peru, Serbia, Yugoslavia
- $1,030M of European dollar bonds paying no interest by end 1948;
  64% accounted for by Germany
- After Pearl Harbor, **SEC banned trading** in $1,250M face value of Axis-power
  dollar bonds (Germany, Italy, Austria, Romania, Hungary, Bulgaria, Japan);
  most markets not reopened by 1949

> **Benjamin Graham** dismissed foreign bonds as having 'a bad investment history
> since 1914'… "Yet every few years, market conditions are sufficiently favourable
> to permit the sale of some new foreign issues at a price about par. This
> phenomenon tells us a good deal about the working of the average investor's mind."
> — *The Intelligent Investor*

---

## At the Bottom with the Bear — Summer 1949

### Character of the 1949 Bottom

- 1949 was more like **1921 than 1932**: no catastrophic price collapse,
  but prolonged valuation erosion
- DJIA peaked May 1946 (16-year high); declined only 24% to June 1949 bottom
- **Key similarity to pre-1921**: equities spent a long time seeking lower valuations
  before a final material price decline

### Valuation Compression: The Real Story

- **CAPE (cyclically adjusted PE)** fell from ~13.7x (1871-1932 average) to:
  - 9.4x current earnings at June 1932 bottom (but prospective PE higher as
    earnings hadn't bottomed yet; Dec 1932 earnings implied 11.6x)
  - **5.8x earnings by June 1949** — even lower than 1932
  - On forward-adjusted basis: 6.4x in June 1949

> **Investors who bought at the 1932 bottom expecting valuations to mean-revert
> saw them fall a further 40% by 1949. Earnings growth was poor, but ever-lower
> valuations were the key driver of poor returns — particularly post-1937.**

- **Q ratio**: declined from 0.43x (end 1932) to 0.36x (end 1949)
- By 1949, equities were exceedingly cheap — stage set for the longest bull market
  of the 20th century

### Why Valuations Kept Compressing

- Economy expanded materially (real GDP per capita +62%, 1926-49) while
  equities went nowhere — DJIA in 1949 was back at 1926 levels
- Real GDP below 1926 levels until 1935; all growth concentrated 1935-1949
- Government's share of economy: expenditure rose from 3% to 15% of GDP
- Labour's share improved sharply: CPI +73% (1935-49) but manufacturing
  hourly earnings +155%
- **"Normalised" earnings (10-year average) in 1949 were only 33% higher
  than normalised 1932 earnings** — deeply disappointing vs. nominal GDP growth
- Nearly 2/3 of all profit growth in 1932-49 occurred in just 1945-49
  (driven by repeal of **excess profits tax**); investors doubted its sustainability

### Investor Psychology at the Bottom

- Two prior false dawns: June 1938 and October 1945 — recessions ended,
  economy turned up, but equities did NOT sustain rallies
- Investors in 1949 had to believe "this time it was different"
- Fear of postwar depression/deflation (like 1921) or permanent government
  expansion stifling corporate profits suppressed valuations

### Good News and the Bear (WSJ Headlines, Spring/Summer 1949)

- Counterintuitively, **there was ample good news at the bottom** — consistent
  with 1921 and 1932 findings that bear markets do NOT end on absence of optimism

- **21 Apr**: Q1 earnings better than expected
- **22 Apr**: International Harvester farm equipment sales +30% YoY
- **22 Apr**: Sam Smith (Bache & Co.) — readjustments will set stage for
  "vigorous business revival"
- **25 Apr**: Evans Wollen Jr. (American Bankers Assoc.) cited pent-up demand,
  Marshall Plan spending, Atlantic Pact military aid as positives
- **28 Apr**: U.S. Steel, Du Pont, General Motors Q1 reports show improvements
- **2 May**: 197 firms Q1 earnings $732M — 21% above 1948 (WSJ survey)
- **12 May**: Treasury Secretary Snyder — postwar adjustments "practically completed"
- **9 June**: Business loans falling 20 consecutive weeks; but real estate loans
  at record high $4,092M
- **16 June**: Most businessmen expected downturn to last ~1 year;
  Gillette president estimated 4-6 months more

- **DJIA bottomed June 1949; NBER recession end date: October 1949**
  — equity market led the economic recovery by 4 months

<!-- pp. 301-320 -->

## 1949 Bear Market Bottom: Economic Signals (continued)

### Rolling Recession & Sectoral Divergence (June–July 1949)

- **16 June**: Term **"rolling recession"** coined by White House economic adviser — industrials
  hit in series rather than all at once; cotton, textiles, airlines, frozen foods, radio sets,
  distillers, luxury goods already down; autos, drug makers, electric power still strong
- Government analysts estimate ~1 year per industry to complete decline from postwar peak
- **16 June**: Federal Reserve consumer survey paradox — consumers had more money than ever,
  felt optimistic, intended to buy durables — yet appliance sales slumping; lower prices
  were stimulating sales (dealers who cut prices aggressively got results)
- **22 June** — Walter Maynard, **Shearson, Hammill & Co.**: upturn in business and stocks
  likely in July; investors should adopt more aggressive posture
- **2 July**: Unemployment jumped to 7-year high of 3,778,000 — but increase entirely in
  under-25 age group; non-farm adult employment actually rose (construction, outdoor work)
- **6 July** — **Daniel F. Rice & Co.**: recession to bottom in fall, gradual pickup in spring
  of next year
- **8 July** — **Lucien Hooper, W.E. Hutton & Co.**: 'Field reports indicate that the usual
  conditions which precede a major depression are lacking.'
- **8 July**: Industrial electricity sales below year-ago for first time since August 1946 —
  but residential (+14.2%) and commercial (+7.2%) electricity still rising YoY
- **12 July** — **Sam Smith Bache & Co.**: fear of war, tax increases, and labor bills had
  suppressed P/E ratios for 3+ years; 'stocks are low and yields are high'

### Early August Turning Point

- **1 August**: NAPA purchasing survey — business declining but at slower rate; order bookings
  show 30% reporting increases vs 28% decreases (first such signal since October 1948)
  Commodity prices rising: copper, lead, zinc, alcohol, corn, ceramics, rosin
- **4 August**: Steel mills report definite pickup in demand
- **6 August**: **Federal Reserve Board** announces cuts to reserve requirements of member
  banks — freeing $1,800 million for investment or lending
- **10 August** — **Bache & Co.**: 'The beginning of a new spirit can be sensed in Wall Street.
  This could easily be the foundation for the next major expansion in American business
  activity.'

### Key Synthesis: Bear Bottom Signals Across 1921, 1932, 1949

> "As in 1921 and 1932, the market's failure to respond to good news was more indicative
> of the end of the bear market than any proliferation of bad news."

- Common factors at ALL THREE bear market bottoms (1921, 1932, 1949):
  - Economic recovery began in **New England** first (consumer goods industries)
  - **Auto industry expanded** while general economy still contracting
  - Rising demand at lower prices → early signal deflation was ending

---

## Auto Industry as Bear Bottom Indicator

- Wartime production halt (Feb 1942) created massive pent-up demand; only 749 new cars sold
  1943–44; 1945 registrations still below 1939
- Used car premiums peaked post-war: 1946 Chevy (list $1,200) sold used for $1,500 in 1947;
  by 1949 back to ~$1,100 — declining premium signalled return to market normalcy
- US auto sales: 2.1 million (1946) → **5.1 million (1949)** vs. 3.8 million pre-war (1941)
- **William F. Hufstader**, GM VP: average car age rose from 5.33 years (1941) to 8.73 years
  (1948); 13 million cars 10+ years old vs. 5 million pre-war → secular demand story
- Investors feared peak sales once wartime pent-up demand was satisfied — concern proved
  unfounded
- Pattern: **products with low diffusion rates** (still rising from low ownership base) are
  first to benefit at bear market bottoms; spending then spreads to other products
- Las Vegas anecdote (May 1949): Flamingo bar revenue 10% above year-ago even as national
  liquor sales down 40% — structural growth cities/industries outperform in downturns

---

## Price Stability and the Bear

### The Core Thesis

- In 1949 as in 1921 and 1932, **return of general price stability coincided with the end
  of the bear market in equities**
- Early evidence: rising demand for commodities at lower prices → spreading demand → general
  price stabilization
- **Low inventory levels** confirmed price recovery could be sustained (not just a bounce)

> "In 1949, as in 1921 and 1932, a return of general price stability coincided with the end
> of the bear market in equities. Spreading demand for and price stability of selected
> commodities augured well for general price stabilisation."

- Inventory liquidation had depressed prices; with stocks at rock bottom, deflation abated
- **Wholesale price index** peaked August 1948, fell 7.5% by June 1949 DJIA bottom —
  only marginal further decline followed (Figure 85)
- CPI behaved similarly; equity bottom occurred as the period of sharp price *decline* ended,
  not necessarily at the absolute price bottom

### Price Data as Leading Indicator

- April 1949: rents and food rising within retail price index
- June: wheat and oil prices improved
- July: price rises in lead, rayon, poultry, zinc, copper — WSJ: 'the public is willing to
  spend if it considers the price is "right"'
- **Key confirming feature**: rising demand at lower prices + low inventories together
  suggested deflation ending

### Scale of Deflation: 1949 vs. Prior Episodes

- Post-WWI deflation: **45% decline** in wholesale prices
- Post-WWII deflation: only **7.9%** decline (Aug 1948–June 1950) — dramatically muted
- 1946–49 bear market occurred even as **corporate earnings doubled** — proves market
  feared a 1920-style deflation that never arrived
- Those who recognized the "built-in inflationary bias" of the postwar institutional
  architecture (Keynesian policy, escalator wage clauses, parity prices, deficit spending,
  full employment mandate, disinclination to restore gold standard) could foresee muted
  deflation
- But investors didn't need macro foresight: could simply observe price stabilization
  signals in summer 1949 and act on them

### Strategic Implication

- **Extreme equity undervaluation in 1921, 1932, and 1949 all followed major disturbances
  to the general price level** — uncertainty about where prices would settle crushed
  equity values
- Safest time to buy equities is **following a major price disturbance**, when prices begin
  to stabilise at a new level
- Without such a price disturbance, a bear market may not produce "buy of a generation"
  valuations
- **"General price level"** = prices of all goods and services; a "material disturbance"
  is one large enough to have major impact on equity markets

---

## Liquidity and the Bear (1949)

### Fed Policy Complexity in 1949

- By 1949, Fed had operated 35 years but was **no easier to read** — inconsistency and
  error throughout that period
- Critical distortion: Fed's wartime obligation to **support government bond prices at
  predetermined levels** made it a provider of unlimited high-powered money on autopilot
- Treasury bill/certificate support ended 1947, but longer-maturity bond support remained
- When market forces pushed bond prices below support levels, the Fed had to buy → **elastic
  currency expanded automatically**, regardless of Fed's preferred stance
- When reserve requirements raised (Feb 1948) to slow inflation, banks sold government
  securities → Fed forced to buy to support prices → Fed accidentally **expanded credit**
  while trying to tighten it; policy tool self-defeating

### Reading Fed Intentions in 1949

- With main tool on autopilot, investors had to watch other signals:
  - **Margin requirements**: reduced from 100% to 75% (Feb 1947); no further reductions
    despite prolonged bear → Fed not unhappy with price adjustment
  - **Consumer credit controls**: regained by Fed Aug 1948; used to restrict credit Sept 1948
    → clear tightening signal
- Prices peaked Aug 1948, economic activity peaked Nov 1948

### The January 1949 Signal

- In Q4 1948, bond prices rose above support level → Fed freed from autopilot, could
  show its true intentions
- Fed responded by **selling** government bonds → 5% contraction in elastic currency in
  January 1949 alone → confirmed Fed preferred tight money to squeeze out wartime inflation
- Historical precedents investors feared:
  - Post-WWI: Fed credit outstanding fell **69%** (bottomed July 1922)
  - 1928–31: **50% decline** in Fed credit outstanding before easing
  - Post-WWII: Fed credit rose from $2.3B (Pearl Harbor) to $24.7B peak (Dec 1946) —
    if 50–85% contraction repeated, equity market had far further to fall

### The Surprise: Contraction Stopped Early

- Dec 1948–Oct 1949: only a **25% contraction** in Fed credit outstanding — then stopped
- Elastic currency stretched back to Dec 1948 level by September 1951
- No force majeure — government bonds trading well above support level throughout
- **Fed balance sheet gave NO good buying signal**: contraction appeared only half done
  when market bottomed in June 1949

### What Actually Worked: Policy Signals, Not Balance Sheet

> "Though the balance sheet of the Fed did not give a good indication of when to buy
> equities, changes in its policy stance did provide timely signals. The first easing of
> credit controls imposed in September 1948 came as early as March 1949, providing clear
> evidence the Fed believed the pace of economic contraction was too rapid."

- **Timeline of easing signals**:
  - March 1949: first easing of consumer credit controls (imposed Sept 1948)
  - May 1949: series of reserve requirement reductions began
  - 29 June 1949: Fed officials confirm they would stop intervening to prevent bond price rise
- Investors buying on first easing signal (March 1949) saw DJIA fall further 10% before
  bottoming 13 June — still far better than waiting for Fed balance sheet confirmation
- **Commercial bank loans** bottomed June 1949 (coinciding with DJIA bottom); grew 3.2%
  by November — commercial bank behaviour was a **better real-time indicator** than Fed
  balance sheet; WSJ reported NYC bank loans broke out of record 27-week decline by end
  of July 1949
- **Broad money (M2)**: first improvement only Q2 1950 — useless as timing signal
- **Inflation-adjusted M2**: noticeable improvement Aug–Sept 1949 — some value, but lagging

### Cross-Episode Comparison: Policy Signals vs. Balance Sheet

| Episode | First policy easing signal | DJIA bottom | Balance sheet bottom |
|---------|---------------------------|-------------|----------------------|
| 1921 | Discount rate cut (May) | Aug 22 | Jul 1922 |
| 1949 | Consumer credit easing (Mar) | Jun 13 | Oct 1949 |
| 1932 | Rate cuts from Nov 1929 | Jul 1932 | — |

- 1921: buying on discount rate cut → 20% further decline before bottom
- 1949: buying on credit control easing → 10% further decline before bottom
- 1932 counterexample: rate cuts began Nov 1929 when market had very long way to fall —
  underscores that policy signals are useful but not infallible

---

## The Bulls and the Bear (1949 Sentiment)

### Myth of Universal Pessimism at Bear Bottoms

- Contrary to popular mythology, **plenty of bullish voices existed at the 1949 bottom**
  (as in 1921 and 1932) — waiting for universal pessimism means missing the turn
- **13 April**: Broad Street Investing Corp. — diversified fund yield above 5% only in
  1932, 1911, 1942 (all 'highly auspicious buying occasions'); current yield 5.25%
- **18 April** — Sam Smith, Bache & Co.: 'Noteworthy that while the bulk of recent news
  has not been cheerful, the market has failed to break down' — market's failure to respond
  to bad news as key signal

<!-- pp. 321-340 -->

## 1949 Bear Bottom: WSJ Sentiment Chronology (continued)

### April–May 1949: Stretched Valuations, Growing Short Interest

- **19 Apr** — Harry D Comer (**Paine, Webber, Jackson & Curtis**): 20 common stocks
  yielding 8–12%, each earning 50%+ more than dividend payments, with
  20+ years uninterrupted dividends — extreme value on display
- **19 Apr** — W. Maynard (**Shearson, Hammill & Co.**): "fairly persuasive evidence
  that adversity… has already been thoroughly taken into consideration
  by both buyers and sellers" — bad news already priced
- **25 Apr** — L.O. Hooper (**W.E. Hutton**): Bear since summer 1946, nearly 3 years;
  PE ratios should *rise* as earnings decline; "more than half of the
  time in recent years stock prices have moved inversely to the business
  index and profits" — market decoupling from fundamentals
- **25 Apr** — **Arthur Weisenberger & Co.**: stocks never lower relative to
  dividends "except at the critical points of WWI and II and in the
  depths of our worst depressions, in 1932 and 1873"
- **2 May** — Wall Street's largest houses lending "more stock than at any time
  since 1929" — massive **short interest** seen as a cushion against
  further decline
- **2 May** — **Coffin, Betz & Co.**: "Once again, as at the bottom in late
  November there are a lot of little bears hoping to make a profit.
  They rarely do."
- **10 May** — **Hugh W Long & Co.**: "For almost a decade there has been little
  or no relationship between the level of business activity and the
  level of security prices" — warns against assuming business decline
  = stock decline
- **10 May** — A.J. Messing (**Hertzfeld & Stern**): "I am now ready to express
  the definite opinion that the lows of the year have been made" —
  premature bottom call
- **12 May** — **Kenneth Ward**: when high-grade stocks sell at prices
  "all out of proportion to even a substantial decline in earnings,
  then it is usually close to buying time"
- **14 May** — **Edmund W. Tabell** (Walston, Hoffman & Goodwin): market
  "very rapidly reaching a sold-out condition… near the start of an
  important upside move"
- **14 May** — DJIA had been in a **7% trading range** for 6 months despite
  relentlessly bad business news
- **19 May** — **Short interest** reaches 1,628,551 shares — largest in 16 years
  (since Feb 27, 1933); ratio to daily average volume = 213 days of
  trading; largest positions in **Pepsi Cola, Hudson Motors, GM**

### June 1949: Testing the Triple Bottom

- **25 May** — **Vance, Sanders & Co.**: "With the exception of 1932-33 common
  stocks are selling at about as low a level in relation to dividend
  payments as they have for 50 years"
- **1 June** — Consensus: 1949 testing the **163-165 triple bottom** defined
  by the lows of 1946, 1947, and 1948
- **4 June** — Stocks sink further into the rut above 163-165; volume at
  only 700,000 shares — not alarming but not bullish
- **6 June** — L.O. Hooper compiles list of **225 stocks selling below working
  capital** — deep value by any measure
- **10 June** — Hooper (W.E. Hutton): "We would prefer to buy than sell…
  we are approaching a 'saturation point' in pessimism regarding
  business… a mid-summer rally is traditional, even in bear markets"

> "Stock prices have never been lower in relation to dividends, except
> at the critical points of WWI and II and in the depths of our worst
> depressions, in 1932 and 1873." — Arthur Weisenberger & Co., 25 April 1949

### 13 June 1949: The Bottom

- **13 June** — **DJIA bottoms at 161.6**
- **14 June** — All resistance swept aside; industrials drop 3.01 to lowest
  since Aug 7, 1945; railroads slip through all bottoms since Oct 1944;
  volume fails to reach "climactic proportions" — **final decline on
  low volume**, consistent with 1921 and 1932
- **15 June** — The bear market since May 29, 1946 has lasted **3 years** —
  "longer than any other, exceeding even that from September 1929 to
  July 1932"

### June–August: The Rebound Begins

- **17 June** — L.O. Hooper: "The bear market has some of the features of
  being in its final stages. Volume of trading falls on each succeeding
  attack on prices" — declining volume on sell-offs = key bottoming signal
- **21 June** — Short interest *decreases* slightly — surprise, as Street
  had expected further crowding of the bear side
- **29 June** — **Keystone Co. of Boston**: DJIA 30 stocks historically sell at
  ~15x earnings; bull market peaks ~25x; bear market troughs ~10x;
  currently selling at **6–7x** trailing 12-month earnings
- **7 July** — Final-hour volume surges to highest since June 15; 810,000
  shares after 2pm — most active 60-minute period since May 17, 1948;
  volume on upside exceeds any downside session — technically significant
- **14 July** — Market rises on disquieting labor news and tension abroad;
  volume surpasses 1 million shares; **1,016 stocks** on tape vs. 941
  Tuesday — breadth expanding on advances
- **16 July** — Market advances despite "seemingly certain strike in the
  steel industry" — bad news no longer drives prices down
- **21 July** — Short interest = **1,644,313** shares, matching January 1933
  figure; ratio to daily turnover = **2.40 to 1** — highest since May 1938;
  "on both those prior occasions the bears were wrong"

> "Traders should not overlook that the market is resting on a potential
> keg of dynamite. Stocks have been going into very strong hands for
> some time and the latent power of the extremely large short interest
> is tremendous. Very few of the amateur shorts will succeed in making
> money out of their short positions." — Herbert G. King, 25 July 1949

- **5 Aug** — **Ralph Rotnem** (Harris, Upham & Co.): In 1929 bond yields
  *exceeded* stock yields by 1¾%; in 1932 nearly equal; 1937 gap 1½%
  in favor of stocks; 1942 (war) gap over 3%; now stocks yield **4%,
  more than bonds** — widest spread in 20 years — extreme relative value
- **14 Aug** — L.O. Hooper: "One of the confusing things about this market
  is that so many people still 'do not believe in it'… This investor
  scepticism makes for technical health rather than technical weakness"

---

## Analytical Summary: What the 1949 Bottom Reveals

### Value Was Early — But Not Wrong

- **Value investors started beating the drum in early 1947** when the
  **S&P Composite PE** fell below its 1871–1947 average — yet the DJIA
  still fell a further 10% over the next 18 months before bottoming
- By June 1949, the S&P Composite PE was **~60% below** the long-term
  average PE — driven not by large price declines but by an explosion
  in earnings
- **Q ratio** had been below its geometric mean since **1939** — the market
  traded below fair value on an asset basis for a full decade before
  the bottom
- Key insight: **cheap can become very cheap**; value is necessary but
  not sufficient to time the bottom

> **"As early as 1939, the q ratio of the market was below its geometric
> mean, indicating that the market was trading below fair value from
> 1939 to 1949. In seeking the bottom of the bear market it is important
> to determine that equities are below fair value but it is also
> important to look at other factors if one is to avoid investing too
> early and watching cheap equities become very cheap."**

### Sentiment Signal: Market Apathy to Bad News

- Many commentators in May–June 1949 noted the failure of bad news to
  push prices lower — a **key leading indicator** that future declines
  are limited
- **General apathy** to both good and bad news signals bears are no
  longer able to drive the market lower, even as they refuse to cover
- When the market shows apathy to news *in conjunction with* a large
  **short interest**, supply/demand outlook is improving markedly

> **"The combination of a large short position in conjunction with a
> market that does not decline on bad news was a positive indicator of
> a rebound in 1921, 1932 and 1949."**

### Volume Pattern at the Bottom

- **Bear market ends on low volume** — the final decline is *not*
  accompanied by a surge in volume; no climactic selling
- The rebound begins on low volume; **short interest does not capitulate
  immediately** — there is a lag of several weeks
- Rising prices *with* rising volumes on the upside confirms the move;
  this was evident in the 1949 summer rebound
- Late-session volume spikes in 1949 rebound suggest bears were
  reluctantly covering as each day passed without a setback — "throwing
  in the towel"
- "Little bears" (small retail shorts) mirror the "little bulls" of
  bull market manias — both groups arrive late and lose

### Diffusion of Holdings

- Bottom associated with **widespread small-holder ownership, limited
  trading**: AT&T annual meeting had 19 million of 23 million shares
  voted; 94% of AT&T shareholders held ≤100 shares; at GM, 59% held
  fewer than 26 shares each
- In 1921 and 1932, **diffusion of holdings** reaching historically high
  levels was a well-noted sign that big constructive interests were about
  to consolidate — this indicator was cited less in 1949 as it had given
  false signals since the 1930s
- **Merrill Lynch, Pierce, Fenner & Beane** launched retail investor
  education drives including a "For Women Only" class (May 1949) —
  cultivating the next generation of buyers

### Dow Theory Success in 1949

- **E. George Schaefer** issued bullish newsletter 18 June 1949 citing
  intra-day lows at 160.62 (industrials) and 40.88 (rails) — neither
  was breached on the final decline
- **Kenneth Ward** (WSJ, 16 June): Dow Theory signals selective buying
- Dow Theory correctly identified the bottom to within a few days in
  **1921, 1932, and 1949** — three for three

---

## Bonds and the Bear (1946–1949)

### Fed's Yield Peg Distorts the Sequence

- Fed's **de facto commitment** to buy government securities at set
  yields distorted the normal order of market recovery
- US long government bonds reached a **yield low of 2.03%** in April 1946;
  bond prices declined thereafter requiring massive Fed support operations
- Fed's government bond holdings rose **129%** in 1948 alone to defend
  the yield peg; rally in govts didn't begin until November 1948, ending
  with yields at **2.18%** in November 1949

### Corporate Bond Sequence — Different from 1921/1932

- **Moody's AAA corporate bonds**: yield low 2.46% in April 1946;
  rose to 2.90% by January 1948; then rallied to 2.57% by end of 1949
- **Moody's Baa corporates**: yield low 2.94% April 1946; rose to 3.56%
  January 1948; rally continued to 3.16% by February 1951
- Corporate bond prices bottomed **January 1948** — 10 months before the
  government bond rally and **16 months before the equity market bottom**
- In 1921 and 1932, the sequence was: government bonds → corporate
  bonds → equities; in 1949, corporates rallied *before* government
  bonds due to the yield peg distortion
- Probable explanation: investors switched from pegged govt rates to
  higher-yielding corporate paper; the "early" corporate rally was
  an artifact of Fed suppression of govt yields

> **"While recognising the different sequence for the commencement of
> bull markets in financial assets in 1949, the abnormality of the
> postwar situation must be remembered. It seems more likely the 1921
> and 1932 sequence of stabilisation of government bonds followed by
> corporate bonds followed by equities is more likely to be the normal
> sequence of events."**

### Q Ratio and Replacement Value — Consistent Signal

- As in 1921 and 1932, equity prices stopped falling in 1949 when they
  reached a **~70% discount to the replacement value of corporate assets**
- All key signals from 1921 positive in 1949 *except*: Fed interest rate
  policy constrained → it was a **reduction in credit controls** (not
  rate cuts) that signaled the bear was in its final phase
- All three episodes (1921, 1932, 1949) occurred under a **fixed-exchange-
  rate regime** of varying strictness — Napier raises the question of
  whether these signals would work in a **free-float currency** environment
  (i.e., 1982 test still pending at chapter's end)

<!-- pp. 341-360 -->

## Part IV: August 1982

> *The old textile plants given over to discount clothing outlets… acres of dead railroad track and car shops and stockpiled wheels and empty boxcars stick in the heart of the city like a great rusting dagger.*
> — John Updike, *Rabbit is Rich*

- By August 1982, the **S&P Composite Index** in real terms was back where it had first been in **August 1906** — a 76-year round trip
- The 1949–1982 period forced investors to cope with something unprecedented: **systemic inflation** (not the war-driven, cyclical inflation of before)
- Key question: did this "new era" of persistent inflation alter the nature of bear markets and their ultimate denouement?

---

### The Road to August 1982

### Why 1974 Ranks Fifth (Not Fourth) Among Great Bear Bottoms

- The four great bear market bottoms studied: **August 1921, July 1932, June 1949, August 1982**
- **December 1974** ranks only fifth — a great trading opportunity but not a great buy-and-hold opportunity

**Q Ratio at Five Bear Market Bottoms** (Smithers & Co.):
| Year | Q Ratio Year-End | Q Ratio at Market Bottom |
|------|-----------------|--------------------------|
| 1921 | .35 | .28 |
| 1932 | .43 | .30 |
| 1949 | .36 | .29 |
| 1974 | .36 | .35 |
| 1982 | .38 | .27 |

- 1974 year-end data looks cheap because the DJIA bottomed in December; adjusting for the rebound already underway in 1921/1932/1949, those earlier bottoms were cheaper
- **Cyclically adjusted PE** in December 1974: 11.2x — well above 7.4x (August 1921) and 4.7x (July 1932); marginally below 11.7x (June 1949) but above 9.9x (August 1982)

**Real S&P Returns from Market Bottoms** (Shiller data):
| Year | 5 Years | 10 Years | 15 Years |
|------|---------|----------|----------|
| 1921 | +106% | +152% | +211% |
| 1932 | +209% | +46% | +92% |
| 1949 | +84% | +237% | +343% |
| 1974 | +9% | +21% | +114% |
| 1982 | +143% | +163% | +414% |

- 1974's good 15-year return was largely earned *after* the 1982 bottom, not from 1974 itself
- Inflation further penalised 1974 buyers: the real S&P price index in 1982 was **13% below** the December 1974 level (per **Robert Shiller**, Yale)
- Contrarian insight: despite gold standard → Bretton Woods → free float improving the Fed's capacity to respond, **gross undervaluation is just as likely today as a century ago** — the q ratio oscillation shows no diminishing tendency

---

### The Course of the Dow: 1949–68

- **Bull market**: June 1949 to December 1968 (S&P Composite peak; DJIA peaked February 1966 but broader index ran to Dec 1968)
- Within the bull: 8 corrections >10% by DJIA definition (the "**Kennedy break**" of 1962 the biggest at 27%)
- **Kennedy break**: JFK branded anti-business for blocking steel price hikes → panic about profit margins; Cuban Missile Crisis (Oct 22-28, 1962) barely moved the market by comparison
- 1966 decline (25%): crisis of confidence — **Adam Smith** (*The Money Game*):

> *They don't believe Johnson, they don't believe anything in Washington, they believe taxes are going to go up but not enough, they don't believe we'll ever get out of Vietnam, and… nobody will believe any earnings.*

- Overall 1949–68: S&P Composite +662% nominal, +413% real

**Key drivers of the 1949–68 bull market:**

- **Defense industry rise**: Sputnik (Oct 1957) → permanent US armaments industry → strong profits; **Eisenhower** warned of 'unwarranted influence' by the **'military-industrial complex'** in his Jan 1961 farewell address
- Equities trading at discounts to replacement value → conglomerate/takeover boom; **Litton Industries** launched aggressive acquisitions as early as 1958
- Counterintuitive: bull market ran against a backdrop of **regular fiscal deficits** (surplus in only 4 of 19 years, 1949–68)

**Trading volumes — institutionalisation:**
- Annual NYSE turnover in 1949–68: only 17% — never approached 1900–1937 highs (>100%)
- Peak turnover in 1949–68 was 24% — surpassed every year from 1900–1937
- NYSE seat prices lagged DJIA: not until 1968 did seat prices surpass the $450,000 paid in 1929 (even though DJIA exceeded 1929 highs by November 1954)
- Not until 1963 did annual NYSE volume exceed the 1929 high; by then seat prices were still two-thirds below 1929 highs
- Explanation: **institutionalisation** brought longer holding periods, block trading off-market; retail share of trading fell from ~50% (1961) to one-third (1969)

**Pension fund revolution:**
- 1949: total US pension assets = $14.3bn vs GNP of $258.1bn; invested primarily in government bonds
- **National Labor Relations Board** 1948 ruling (*Inland Steel* case) forced pension negotiations into collective bargaining → explosive asset growth
- Private pension fund assets grew 11-fold 1952–68; mutual fund assets 13-fold
- Institutional equity holdings: 9.5% of NYSE market cap (1952) → 21.3% (1968)
- Institutional share of NYSE dollar trading: one-third (1960) → 60% (1968)

**The yield gap reversal — the structural driver:**
- Since the NYSE's founding in 1792, **dividend yields on equities always exceeded bond yields** (the "yield gap")
- Institutional shift out of bonds into equities pushed S&P dividend yield *below* long-term government bond yields in **July 1957** — a permanent "reverse yield gap"
- By December 1968 peak: S&P yield = 2.88%, long-term government bonds = 5.65%
- The bond bear market began January 1950, just 6 months after the equity bear market ended; bond yields doubled as equity dividend yields fell ~60%
- Root cause: acceptance that the postwar financial/social infrastructure had made **inflation structurally permanent**, eliminating the advantage of bonds' fixed payments

**Valuation expansion drove the bull, not earnings:**
- Earnings from Dec 1949 to Dec 1968: +150% — vs nominal GDP +240% and S&P Composite +662%
- Equity valuations 1949→1968 (Smithers & Co. / Shiller):
  - q ratio: 0.49x → 1.06x
  - PE trailing: 5.8x → 18.5x
  - Cyclically adjusted PE: 11.7x → 25.1x
- The bull was a **re-rating story**, not a profits story

**The "Go-Go Years" and new era thinking:**
- By mid-1960s, a new generation emerged who believed only the young understood the "new economy" — **John Brooks** (*The Go-Go Years*): belief only someone under 40 could foresee growth of fast-moving companies
- **LBJ's "Great Society"** (January 1965): fiscal largesse rivalling FDR's New Deal; combined with Vietnam spending, spooked the bond market
- Fed held rates steady (discount rate 4.0% in October 1967 = same as September 1959) even as inflation rose from 1.23% to 3.56% — monetary tools in abeyance
- **William McChesney Martin** (Fed chair) tasked to 'lean against the wind' but fiscal restraint politically impossible
- First Fed move: 50bp hike November 1967; rate eventually exceeded 9% within two years
- Market ignored rising rates in 1968: buoyed by LBJ's decision not to run, Paris peace talks, Nixon's 'peace with honour' promise
- Market peaked soon after Nixon's November 1968 election victory → 14-year bear market began

---

### The Course of the Dow: 1968–82

- Key forces: **demise of Bretton Woods** + **acceleration of inflation**
- **Robert Triffin** (Yale) had warned in 1960 (*Gold and the Dollar Crisis*): US must run current account deficits to supply world liquidity → this would eventually undermine faith in the dollar as reserve currency
- Nixon suspended dollar-gold redemption **15 August 1971**; dollar devalued Dec 1971 ($35→$38/oz gold), then again 1973 ($42); by March 1973 free float confirmed
- Gold link severed → key discipline on inflation removed
- **Arthur Burns** became Fed chairman January 1970; Nixon on swearing him in:

> *I respect his independence. However, I hope that independently he will conclude that my views are the ones that should be followed.*

- Burns and Nixon views "regularly coincided" — Fed reputation as guardian of price stability suffered; roller-coaster through the 1970s on interest rates
- **Inflation, and the fight against it, drove the 1968–82 bear market**

<!-- pp. 361-380 -->

## The 1968-82 Bear Market: Inflation, Stagflation, and the Road to the Bottom

### Burns, Nixon, and the Inflation Spiral

- **Arthur Burns** at the Fed: within his first year, short-term rates fell back below 4.0%
- By mid-1971, rates rising again; Nixon imposed first **price controls** since 1949
- Inflation back below 3% by mid-1972 — then Nixon dismantled controls in 1973
- **OPEC oil shock**: oil price tripled from $3.12/barrel (Oct 1973) to $11.63 (Dec 1973)
- Annual inflation surged from 2.9% (Aug 1972) to **12.5% by December 1974**

> *There were actually two oil shocks in the 1970s. The first began in October 1973, when Arab OPEC members announced they would no longer ship oil to countries supporting Israel in its war with Egypt... The second was caused by a decline in oil exports from Iran following the revolution of January 1979. By year-end, the oil price had risen 150%. Within 12 months of both oil shocks, G7 GDP contracted.*

- The sharp recession (Nov 1973–Mar 1975) **failed** to bring inflation under control
- April 1973: the term **"stagflation"** first appears in the *Wall Street Journal*
- Fed's response remained mild: Fed Funds rate only 75bp higher in Jan 1977 than in Jan 1960,
  despite inflation going from 1.1% to 6.1%
- **Stagflation** coined November 17, 1965 by Conservative MP **Ian Macleod** in the House of Commons;
  he was appointed Chancellor of the Exchequer five years later — died after one month in office

### The Secular Bear in Real Terms

- **S&P Composite Index declined 63% in real terms** from December 1968 to July 1982
- Inflation threshold: bear market really began in 1969 as inflation moved above **3%**
- 1970s inflation averaged **7.1%** — beyond this threshold, equities could not produce positive real returns
- DJIA dropped 33% from Dec 1968 high to 1970 lows (first phase), then rallied to new high Jan 1973,
  then dropped **45%** — bottoming Dec 1974 down 37% nominal, 57% real from 1968
- By Dec 1974, S&P Composite (real) was back to levels first seen in **November 1928**
- In real terms the Index hit its low in **July 1982**, 13% below the Dec 1974 low —
  back to levels first surpassed in **June 1905**
- Investors were **entirely reliant on dividends** to provide any positive real returns

### The Nifty Fifty Disaster

- By 1972, investor portfolios concentrated in "one-decision" growth stocks called the **"Nifty Fifty"**
- Belief: these 50 stocks would produce earnings/dividend growth making the purchase price irrelevant
- Nifty Fifty drove DJIA to new highs in early 1973 while the broader **Value Line Index** failed to surpass prior highs
- Investors paid an average **PE of 42x** in 1972; these stocks suffered an average **62% price decline** in 1973-74
- By Dec 1974, nominal market levels were back to **1958**

> *The Nifty Fifty was a group of 50 stocks. In December 1972, the average PE ratio for the group was 42x earnings. Although all 50 were part of the S&P Composite Index, the PE of the broader index was just 18x at that time... Professor Jeremy Siegel points out in his Stocks for the Long Run that the annual return on the Nifty Fifty from December 1972 to November 2001 was 11.62%, just below the 12.14% of the S&P Composite Index over the same period.*

- Counterintuitive: for long-term holders the Nifty Fifty did eventually deliver near-market returns

### Earnings Failure and Inflation's Equity Swindle

- Losses in 1968-82 came from **both poor earnings growth AND valuation compression**
- Nominal EPS increased just **143%** vs. nominal GDP up **246%** — a 12% **real decline** in earnings
- Investors assumed management could adapt with higher margins in inflation; **Warren Buffett** pointed out the fallacy

> *Recent statistical evidence does not inspire confidence in the proposition that margins will widen in a period of inflation. In the decade ending in 1965... manufacturing companies had an average annual pre-tax margin on sales of 8.6%. In the decade ending in 1975, the average margin was 8%. Margins were down despite a very considerable increase in the inflation rate.* — Buffett, Fortune, May 1977

- **Sydney Homer** (Salomon Brothers, "father of modern bond market research") warned in November 1976:
  "The complete blind confidence of the 1950s in the dollar, and hence in our status in the world, can never return."
- Homer compared rising bond yields to the crash of 1929-32, warned it would hold up yields for generations

### Valuation Collapse: 1968-1982

- Dec 1968: S&P historic PE of **18.5x**, q ratio of **1.06** (previously surpassed only in 1929 and 1905)
- July 1982: historic PE fell to **7.8x**; cyclically-adjusted PE fell from **25.1x to 9.9x**
- Q ratio collapsed from **1.68x to 0.38x** (Dec 1968 to Dec 1982)
- Historic PE had been below **10x since March 1977** — market looked cheap for years before the bottom
- Q ratio below geometric mean for **almost nine years** before the 1982 bottom

### Market Activity: Rising Turnover Despite Bear

- NYSE turnover low point: **1974 at 16%** — still above the 1949-68 average
- Turnover rose steadily to **42% by 1982** — nearly double the 1968 bull-market peak; highest since 1933
- NYSE seat prices: fell **93% in nominal terms** from 1968-1977, then rose ~10x from 1977-1982
- Average holding period: 6+ years in 1974 → **less than two years by 1982**
- Rising turnover reflected **adaptation to volatility**, not the birth of a new bull market

### Institutionalization of the Market (Figure 101)

- Key US savings institutions grew from $448bn (1968) to $1,600bn (1982) — roughly GDP pace
- Despite declining equity weightings, **total funds committed to equities increased ~300%**
  even as the DJIA declined 20%+
- Private pension funds: $111bn (1968) → $577bn (1982); equity % fell from 55% to 42%
- Mutual funds remained highly equity-weighted (~58-90% in equities throughout)

### Miller, Volcker, and the Policy Climax

- 1978: President Carter appointed **G. William Miller** (CEO/lawyer) as Fed chairman
- Extreme measures: US borrowed from the IMF, borrowed foreign currency to support the dollar
- Gold exceeded **$300/oz** by August 1979 (vs. $35 under Bretton Woods)
- Miller moved to Treasury; **Paul Volcker** appointed Fed chairman **6 August 1979**
- Volcker immediately raised rates (4-3 FOMC vote), then convened a **secret FOMC meeting October 6**
- New policy: target **M-1 monetary aggregate** growth rather than interest rates
- Fed funds rate range set at **11.5-15.5%** — creating massive interest rate uncertainty

> *Before there was a Greenspan there was a Volcker. Paul Volcker was Chairman of the Federal Reserve System from August 1979 to August 1987 and is credited with bringing runaway inflation under control. When Volcker took office, inflation was almost 12%. When he left, it was just 4%.*

- In 1995, Volcker asked Greenspan: "Whatever became of M-1?" Greenspan: "It was once the name of a pretty good rifle."

### The 1980 Credit Shock and Its Aftermath

- Inflation kept rising; Carter imposed **credit controls** in March 1980; on TV told Americans to stop spending
- Result: Q2 1980 GDP declined at the **fastest rate ever recorded**; Fed Funds fell from **20% to 8% in three months**
- Volcker later: "It is all recorded in the books as a recession, but in retrospect it was an odd, almost accidental occurrence..."
- By end of 1980, Fed funds pushed to new high again; **May 1981** fight resumed — Fed funds back above **20% by July**
- Bond market did not believe inflation was beaten until **September 1981** — the start of a 20+ year bond rally
- **Donald Regan** (Treasury Secretary) recalled Volcker saying he'd ease if Congress moved on deficits — a standoff that kept real rates high

### Financial Crisis Catalyzes the Bottom (1982)

- May 1982: **Drysdale Government Securities** went bust
- Early July 1982: **Penn Square Bank** (Oklahoma) failed — had originated $1bn+ in loans sold to Continental Illinois
- August 1982: **Mexico** publicly bust; US commercial banks faced massive write-downs on Mexican debt
- **Walter Wriston** (Citibank head) at the IMF annual meeting in Toronto, August 1982:
  > *We had 150-odd finance ministers, 50-odd central bankers, 1,000 journalists, 1,000 commercial bankers, a large supply of whiskey… [which] produced an enormous head of steam driving the engine called 'the end of the world is coming'. It was the Titanic. We were just rearranging the deck chairs.*

- FOMC on June 30 — aware Mexico would default — changed direction despite M-1 growth
- Fed funds rate: above **14% early July → below 9% by early September**
- This was a **de facto abandonment** of money-supply-growth targeting
- Bond market rallied — not spooked by the policy change
- The equity market finally bottomed in **August 1982** with the public announcement of the Mexican crisis
  and the Fed's pivot

---

## Structure of the Market in 1982

### The Stock Market in 1982

- By 1982, equities were no longer a "financial sideshow": NYSE market cap reached **$1,143bn (36% of GDP)**
  vs. $64bn (23% of GDP) in 1949 and $693bn (76% of GDP) in 1968
- Public ownership of equities (via intermediaries): **4% of adults (1952) → 28% (1985)**
- Average holding period just over **two years** vs. five-year average from 1949-1981
- NYSE remained dominant: share of registered exchange trading up from 74% to **85%** by 1982
  (ASE declined from ~18% to <4%)
- Listed companies grew modestly: 1,043 (1949) → 1,273 (1968) → 1,526 (1982);
  average market cap grew from $58m (1949) to **$639m (1982)**

### Sector Shifts: Oil Permanent, Finance Rising

- **Oil** remained the #1 sector at every bear-market bottom (1932, 1949, 1982); #3 at the 1929 bull top
- Finance rose from **16th largest sector (1949) to 2nd largest (1982)**
- Business Equipment and Health also surged (from <3% to ~11% each)
- Heavy industry (steel, autos, chemicals) declined sharply
- Six sectors consistently appeared in the 10 largest across all periods: oil, utilities, retail,
  communications, chemicals, autos — accounting for ~74-77% of market cap throughout

**Sector total returns (1949-1982) — Best performers:**
- Business Equipment: **80.2x**
- Health: 62.7x
- Meals: 55.1x
- Electric Equipment: 53.2x

**Worst performers (1949-1982):**
- Coal: 6.1x
- Chemicals: 16.9x
- Steel: 17.9x

**Sectors producing positive real total returns in the 1968-82 bear market:**
- Tobacco: **+420%** (also best in deflationary 1929-32 bear)
- Telecoms: +194%
- Oil: +185%
- Health: +180%
- Coal: +180%

- Tobacco's ability to adjust prices to maintain margins in differing inflationary climates "seems almost unique"
- Only **5 of 30** industrial sectors produced positive real returns in 1968-82 (including dividends)
- S&P Composite up 82% nominally but CPI up **174%** over same period — a real loss

### The Bond Market in 1982

- NYSE no longer accurately reflected the bond market by 1982
- NYSE corporate/foreign bond listings = just **28% of total market value** outstanding (down from 33% in 1958)
- Total US fixed interest market grew from **$303bn (end 1952) to $2,246bn (2Q 1982)**
  - Treasury securities: $221bn → $858bn
  - Municipal securities: $30bn → $474bn
  - Corporate & foreign bonds: $50bn → $563bn

### Referenced Works
- **Robert Shiller**, *Market Volatility*
- **Adam Smith**, *The Money Game*
- **John Brooks**, *The Go-Go Years*
- **William Greider**, *Secrets of the Temple*
- **Robert Triffin**, *Gold and the Dollar Crisis: The Future of Convertability*
- **Marc Faber**, *The Great Money Illusion*
- **Warren Buffett**, "How Inflation Swindles the Equity Investor," *Fortune*, May 1977
- **Paul Volcker** and Toyoo Gyohten, *Changing Fortunes: The World's Money and the Threat to American Leadership*
- **Donald T Regan**, *From Wall Street to Washington*
- **Phillip L Zweig**, *Citibank and the Rise and Fall of American Financial Supremacy*
- **Kenneth R. French**, "Industry Portfolio Data"
- **Jeremy Siegel**, *Stocks for the Long Run*
- John Updike, *Rabbit is Rich* (epigraph for this section)

<!-- pp. 381-400 -->

## At the Bottom with the Bear — Summer 1982

> *Oil going up takes everything up with it… It's just like the Weimar thing, people's savings are being washed right down the tube, everybody agrees there's a recession coming to curl your hair.*
> — John Updike, *Rabbit is Rich*

### Bond Market Context (1952–1982)

- In 1952, US **fixed-interest securities** were 1.8x larger than the equity market; ratio
  basically unchanged through 1982
- Despite massive **bond bear market**, bond issuance grew; private sector share of
  bond market rose from 16% to 25% (1952–1982)
- **Quasi-government securities** (New Deal agencies) grew from <1% to ~16% of
  all fixed securities by 1982
- **Sidney Homer** and **Richard Sylla** (*A History of Interest Rates*): a constant-maturity
  30-year 2½% bond would have declined from 101 in 1946 to 17 in 1981 — an 83% loss

> *If a constant maturity thirty-year 2½% bond had been available throughout this second bear market of the century, its price would have declined from 101 in 1946 to 17 in 1981, or 83%.*
> — Homer & Sylla, *A History of Interest Rates*

- **Moody's Baa** corporate bond yield reached 17% by February 1982 — vs. peaks of
  8.6% (1921) and 11.6% (1932) in prior deflationary bear markets
- In 1949, equity investors faced Baa yields just below 3.5%; by 1982, yields >17% meant
  bond investors were in "uncharted territory"

### Valuations at the 1982 Bottom

- By August 1982, DJIA had returned to April 1964 levels; in real terms, back to April 1928
- **q ratio**: year-end 1982 = 0.38x; mid-year low probably ~**0.27x**
- **Cyclically adjusted PE**: 9.9x (ten-year rolling earnings) vs. 1881–1982 average of 15.8x
- Peak bull market valuations (1968): q ratio 1.06x, CAPE 25.1x
- Took **14 years** to move from overvalued to undervalued — consistent with 1921 and 1949
  bottoms (both ~13–16 years); 1932 was the outlier at 3 years (required 89% DJIA decline)

**Figure 109 — Duration of swing from overvaluation to undervaluation:**
| Bottom | q ratio (years) | CAPE (years) |
|--------|----------------|--------------|
| 1921   | 16             | 20           |
| 1932   | 3              | 3            |
| 1949   | 13             | 13           |
| 1982   | 14             | 17           |

- Key lesson: **barring a crash of 1929–32 magnitude, expect ~14 years** for equities to
  travel from extreme overvaluation to extreme undervaluation

### Good News and the Bear

- In 15 months from April 1981, DJIA fell another **30%** to bottom in August 1982
- Meanwhile: commodities contained, dollar rallied, govt bond market firmed (Sept 1981)
  — evidence Fed was winning inflation battle; but equity investors focused on economic damage
- **NBER bottom**: November 1982 — equity market bottom preceded it (August)
- **GDP bottom**: Q1 1982 — meaning equity rebound *lagged* GDP improvement by one measure
- Key insight: **the popular myth that stocks lead the economy by 6–9 months is not correct**
  at great bear market bottoms; the economy and equity market bottom nearly simultaneously,
  and the economy may even lead

### WSJ Economic Recovery Headlines (June–October 1982)

Napier documents the flood of improving economic news *at* the market bottom — consistent
with the 1921, 1932, and 1949 pattern of good news being ignored:

- **14 June**: Business inventories cut at fastest real rate since WWII; consumer expectations
  improving; new car sales +5.9% YoY; employment +777,000 jobs; real disposable income
  growing unusually fast despite recession; 10% tax cut expected to boost spending
- **15 June**: Wharton's **Donald Straszheim** says "second quarter still expected to mark end
  of recession"
- **16 June**: Auto sales pace ~8.3M units annually; **Paul Volcker** says consumer spending
  and inventory data "tend to accompany a levelling out of a recession and the beginning of
  a recovery" — "I don't see any place for those interest rates to go but down"
- **17 June**: Housing starts up 22% in May, above 1M-unit annual rate for first time in 10 months
- **22 June**: Economy expanding at 0.6% annual rate — first growth since Q3 1981; **David
  Stockman** says "We are past the trough of the recession"; **Donald Regan** says "we can
  begin to see the vistas of recovery"
- **1 July**: Tax cut to enrich consumers $32B annually; Social Security COLA adds $11B;
  **Alan Greenspan** says recovery signs visible "in a matter of weeks"; leading indicators
  index rising for third consecutive month
- **6 July**: **Robert Wilson** (prominent NY short-seller) intrigued by notion of economic
  recovery amid high rates "just because everyone says it can't happen"
- **12 July**: Consensus shifting to sustained (if weak) recovery; market observed to have
  "begun to rise at or just before a recessionary trough" in every prior cycle — but noted
  this would be the first recovery where the market fell rather than climbed at the outset
- **2 August**: Q2 price deflator 5% — half the 1981 level of 9.4%
- **5 August**: Corporate cash flow in Q1 higher than for all of 1981
- **6 August**: **Blue Chip Economic Indicators** (Robert Eggert) consensus: 3.3% real GNP
  growth in next 12 months — all 40+ forecasters expected at least some growth
- **22 September**: Economy growing at 1.5% annual rate; Q2 revised to 2.1%
- **27 September**: Business start-ups near record high; capital gains tax cut (max 20% vs
  49% in 1978) encouraging small-company investment
- **5 October**: Business confidence improved for third consecutive quarter (Conference Board)

**Actual outcome**: Q2 1982 real GDP did post 2.2% annual growth rate; economy grew 3.2% in
following 12 months — consensus forecast of 3.3% was almost exactly right.

> **Once again, as in 1921, 1932 and 1949, the bottom of a bear market is not marked by the
> absence of good news, but rather by an increasing supply of good news ignored by the market.**

### Auto Sector as Lead Indicator

- Across all four bear market bottoms, **auto sector recovery preceded** the broader economy
  and equity market bottom
- 1982: monthly low for new car registrations was January 1982; by June, down only 4% YoY
  (vs. much steeper earlier declines)
- Mechanism: pent-up demand for consumer durables triggered by **declining effective cost**
  of purchase — in 1982, car prices rose 1.9% but US prime lending rate fell from >20% to
  <16%, making cars cheaper to finance; de facto price decline triggered demand recovery
- Same dynamic (literal price declines) visible in 1921, 1932, 1949
- **New England recovery** preceded all four equity bottoms by just weeks — WSJ (19 July 1982)
  reported Northeast's perennially depressed states coming through with "flying colors" driven
  by tech/telecom boom

### Price Stability and the Bear

- In prior bottoms (1921, 1932, 1949), **end of deflation** marked end of equity bear market
- 1982 was structurally different: no gold standard, no external monetary constraint; CPI
  did not decline until November 1982 — *after* the new bull market had begun
- Yet the key turning point was again **stabilisation of commodity prices**
- **CRB index** fell >30% from November 1980 peak to October 1982 low
- Metals component (CRB Spot Metals) bottomed in **June 1982** — two months *before* the
  equity bottom in August
- **Copper** as leading indicator: copper bottomed in August 1921, June 1949, July 1932,
  and led the equity bottom in 1982 as well

> **In all four of the great bear market bottoms analysed in this book, the end of the decline
> in commodity prices marks the end of the great bear market in equities.**

> **On every occasion, the rebound in copper prices preceded or coincided with the rebound in
> the equity market.**

- Paradox: in 1982, rising commodity prices could have been read as signalling resumed
  inflation and tighter Fed policy — yet the pattern held anyway
- Interpretation: with bond market already pricing in Fed victory over inflation, commodity
  stabilisation was read as evidence of improving final demand rather than inflation threat
- CRB index rose **24%** in ten months after October 1982; DJIA rose >50% in under a year

**Actionable framework**: look for (1) cheap valuations, (2) rising copper prices, (3) low
inventory positions, (4) evidence of actual (not forecast) rising auto demand — when all
present, "history suggests one is very close to the bottom of the equity market"

- Monetary system change (gold standard → flexible rates) did not invalidate the
  commodity price signal — lessons from 1921/1932/1949 held even in 1982

### Liquidity and the Bear

- **"Fed watching" is more art than science** — Napier focuses on non-borrowed reserves as
  the objective indicator of Fed policy
- By summer 1982, Fed had set course for growth of **non-borrowed reserves** consistent with
  monetary aggregate targets; if M grew too fast → banks borrowed reserves → upward pressure
  on Fed funds rate → demand dampened
- Non-borrowed reserves grew only **1.8%** in 21 months from July 1980 to April 1982
- **May 1982 turning point**: seasonally-adjusted non-borrowed reserves grew 2.4% month-on-month;
  in next eight months they expanded **10.6%**
- Signal was hard to read in real time — trend change not visible until August
- **NOW accounts** (interest-bearing checking accounts) distorted M-1 data, making Fed
  watchers confused: mid-June M-1 annual growth was 6.7% vs. Fed target of 3.5%, but
  growth reflected financial innovation not actual spending intentions
- Further confusion: BIS report (16 June) noted Fed had **exceeded money supply targets
  for three consecutive years** — so market couldn't reliably forecast Fed reaction to M-1 data
- M-1 plunged $3.7B week of June 30; by September M-1 growing at 16% annual rate — any
  investor who read the September M-1 data as a signal of tightening was "completely wrong-footed"
- **Volcker** told Congress (14 June) that budget action was "pre-requisite for easier credit
  conditions"; fiscal impasse led many — including the BIS — to predict rising world interest
  rates in H2 1982; **Alan Greenspan** admitted: "I had expected a compromise would be struck
  on the budget during the first half, and I was wrong"

<!-- pp. 401-420 -->

## The 1982 Bottom: Liquidity, Policy Signals, and Market Sentiment

### Volcker's Covert Pivot — Summer 1982

- **Alan Greenspan** (then private forecaster, Reagan adviser) predicted prime rate
  of 11¾% by June 30, T-bill at 8.8%, 30-yr bond at 12.9% —
  all proved too high; consensus was rates could NOT fall
- **Volcker** broke from consensus: told Senate Banking Committee (21 July)
  that record deficits were "not an insuperable obstacle to lower interest
  rates" and he was "hopeful" rates could decline
- As bond market rallied, WSJ commentators were uniformly skeptical:
  - "bulk of the Fed's easing is probably behind us" (2 Aug)
  - "most economists don't think that the drop has much further to go" (19 Aug)
  - "any recovery would set a floor under rates" (13 Sep)
- Fears about fiscal impasse proved misplaced because a **financial crisis**
  was developing that created demand for government bonds surpassing new supply

### The Fed's Hidden Policy Shift

- Evidence the Fed was permitting accelerated growth in **non-borrowed reserves**
  as early as May 1982 — but most commentators were conditioned to read
  everything through the money-supply-growth lens
- Key change: **FOMC on 1 July** effectively abandoned money-supply targets
  (no announcement made)
- Volcker's 21 July Senate testimony was the first coded signal:

> 'Growth somewhat above the targeted ranges would be tolerated for a time
> in circumstances in which it appeared that precautionary liquidity motivations,
> during a period of economic turbulence, were leading to a stronger-than-
> anticipated demand for money.' — Volcker, Senate Banking Committee, 21 July 1982

- "Economic turbulence" caveat: Volcker admitted that **Drysdale Government
  Securities** and **Penn Square Bank** bankruptcies didn't yet qualify —
  what he knew and the public didn't: **Mexico's bankruptcy was imminent**,
  and bond dealer **Lombard Wall** was in trouble
- Real catalyst for the policy change: potential impact on US banking system
  of sovereign debt defaults

### The Sovereign Debt Crisis — Scale of the Threat

- WSJ (30 July): bank balance sheets in worse shape than admitted;
  **Continental Illinois** nonperforming loans up 54% to $1.3B;
  **Chase** up 47% to $1.05B
- ~2/3 of **Citibank**'s loans and 50% of **Manufacturer's Hanover** were overseas
- Analyst quote: "Not one dime is classified as bad debt even though there
  is no way Poland can pay it back" — banks defended by saying "nations
  don't go bankrupt"
- By 15 September, WSJ listed the full nightmare: Poland, Mexico, Argentina,
  East Germany, Brazil, Nigeria, Chile, Zaire, Yugoslavia, Bolivia,
  Venezuela, Peru, Tanzania, Sudan, Indonesia, Romania, and others
- Developing-country debt had soared from **$100B in 1973** to ~$540B and
  was expected to reach **$640B** — $327B owed to Western commercial banks
- **Walter Seipp** (Commerzbank chairman): it was "inconceivable that a
  sovereign country would allow itself to go into default" — any bank that
  avoided international lending in the 1970s "would not have stayed a large bank"
- Fear of **domino effect**: Argentina + Brazil default → push major banks
  over the brink → global financial panic → 1930s-style depression

### The Real Signal: Dual Targeting

- The FOMC meeting agreed to "cap" the Fed funds rate while tolerating
  money-supply growth above targets — a **subtle dual-targeting shift**
- This was the best signal easier money was coming, readable only by those
  who parsed Volcker's guarded language
- From 19 July, discount rate was reduced **350bp** over six months
- Policy change formally acknowledged in October 1982 (Fed announced it
  would also target the Fed funds rate)
- Long-term govt bond yields fell from ~14% to 10.5% (Aug–Dec 1982)
- The rally in equities occurred against a backdrop of DECLINING both
  short- and long-term rates simultaneously

### Lessons on Liquidity as a Bear Market Signal

- Fed balance sheet analysis as a bear-market timing tool: **wrong in 1921
  and 1932**, extreme difficulty in 1949, but **accurate in 1982**
- Broad money / credit growth signals were also unreliable:
  - Broad money rebound from April 1981 led equities by 16 months —
    but DJIA still fell 24% in that period
  - Credit growth rebounded in Q4 1980 — long before the 1982 bottom
- **Discount rate cuts** proved more reliable across most bottoms:
  - May 1921 first cut → August 1921 bottom (20% intervening loss)
  - March 1949 credit controls eased → July 1949 bottom (~10% loss)
  - October 1981 first discount rate cut → August 1982 bottom (<10% loss)
  - Exception: November 1929 first cut led to catastrophic losses

> **The rule:** Reductions in Fed interest rates in Fed-induced recessions
> (1921, 1949, 1982) are a good time to buy cheap equities. 1929 was NOT
> a Fed-induced recession — it was the consequence of German reparations,
> Allied debt repayments, and inept gold-standard reconstruction.

- Practical rule-of-thumb: await a further **10% market decline** after
  the first discount rate cut before buying — history shows minimal
  further downside and very significant upside thereafter
- Caveat: May 1980 rate cut was reversed mid-implementation (money-supply
  targeting regime), causing a zig-zag. **With 1929 and 1980 in mind,
  be prepared to buy when a discount rate cut signals the end of a
  Fed war on inflation — but tread warily**

---

## The Bulls and the Bears (Section)

*Epigraph: John Updike, Rabbit is Rich*

### Bulls Were Plentiful at the 1982 Bottom

- **Myth: bulls are extinct at bear market bottoms.** The 1982 bottom
  was surrounded by active bullish commentary — yet the market kept falling
- Timeline of WSJ analyst commentary (June–September 1982):
  - **14 June**: Daniel Ahern (Wellington/TDP&L) — consumer atmosphere
    improving, auto sales upturn, stimulus from 10% income-tax cut
  - **15 June**: Eric Miller (Donaldson Lufkin & Jenrette) — "most stocks
    have seen their lows"
  - **18 June**: **James Dines**, the "ultimate gold bug," reversed 20 years
    of bullion advocacy, told subscribers to sell gold — "end of the gold
    bug era"
  - **23 June**: Alan Poole (Laidlaw Adams) — "bear markets end in selling
    climax or flat dead period — we appear to be in such a dead period"
  - **28 June**: James McCall (Keystone Custodian) — "more bullish than in
    a long time, walking along a market bottom"
  - **2 July**: Howard Stein, Dreyfus Fund ($1.6B) — trimming utility
    stocks, moving cash back into equities, sees "50% gain" potential
  - **14 July**: Merrill Lynch, Goldman Sachs, Bear Stearns, E.F. Hutton
    all had lengthy buy lists — yet their top strategists all thought
    investors would be **better off in bonds**
  - **28 July**: John Brush (Columbine Capital) — "crystal clear that
    inflation will be cooling for next few years"
  - **30 July**: Leon Cooperman (Goldman Sachs) — "entry into a classical
    bull market must be validated by further and sustained decline in
    interest rates"
  - **2 August**: Robert Kirby (Capital Guardian Trust) — doubts market
    has ever sold lower relative to book value over the past 50-60 years
  - **6 August**: Alan Shaw (Smith Barney) — "spirit of the bear is still
    with us — fear of financial collapses, banking and corporate,
    high rates, rekindled inflation"
  - **12 August: DJIA bottoms**
  - **13 August**: Minshall (Capital Advisors Tulsa) — no ability to mount
    sustained rally means "a selling climax will be required to end the
    bear market" [day AFTER the bottom]
  - **18 August**: **Henry Kaufman** (Salomon Brothers) reverses long-standing
    pessimism — expects "substantial drops in interest rates," long-term
    Treasuries could fall to 9% from 12.5%; Goldman Sachs tells clients
    to raise equity allocation to 55% from 35%
  - **18 August**: One-day DJIA record rally — largely attributed to
    Kaufman's reversal
  - **18 August**: Alfred Goldman (A.G. Edwards) — "classic ingredient of
    a real bottom is capitulation by institutions, high disgust…
    they've been complacent, confident. It's unusual to get a bull
    market with so little pain"
  - **19 August**: Heavy institutional buying → NYSE one-day volume record;
    small investors mainly on the sidelines, sceptical
  - **23 August**: Richard McCabe (Merrill Lynch technical) — "institutions
    didn't reach desperate selling prior to the rally" — doubts sustainability
  - **29 September**: Cooperman (Goldman) — "early stages of a bull market;
    average postwar bull market lasts 30 months, trough-to-peak advance of 66%"

### No Capitulation — A Cross-Bottom Pattern

- **The 1982 bottom, like 1921, 1932, and 1949, lacked a final high-volume
  sell-off ("capitulation")**
- Alfred Goldman and Richard McCabe both cited absent capitulation as
  evidence the bottom wasn't real — they were wrong
- Capitulation occurs at some turning points but did NOT occur at any of
  the four great secular bottoms examined in this book
- Capitulation may be more a feature of **trading-range markets** (1968-82)
  than true secular bottoms

> **The signature of a true bear market bottom when equities are cheap:**
> market trading sideways or drifting downward on low volume, subdued
> reaction to both good and bad news, then initial recovery on either
> limited or (as in 1982) large volume — confirmed by **higher volume
> at higher price levels** thereafter.

- Turnover rates at bottoms: 42% (1982), 13% (1949), 32% (1932), 59% (1921)
  — no meaningful pattern in absolute levels
- 1982 unique: initial rebound on **very high volumes** (opposite to other
  episodes where rebound came on low volume)

### Short Interest as Confirmation Signal

- At previous bottoms, initial refusal of shorts to cover confirmed
  the rally's durability
- 1982: peak short positions of 103.6M shares (14 May) declined to
  96.4M by mid-August — then when market rallied, **short positions
  spiked to a NEW RECORD of 120.5M on 15 September**
- Shorts adding aggressively into the new rally confirmed the move
  had characteristics of a **permanent, durable reversal**

### Earnings Lag vs. Rate Focus

- In 1982, WSJ coverage showed far LESS focus on corporate earnings
  than at other bear bottoms — investors focused almost entirely on
  interest rates
- This was correct: the equity market bottomed when the bond market rally
  began; earnings nadir came roughly **4-7 months AFTER** equity bottoms
  (average ~6 months lag across all four bottoms)
- Waiting for earnings recovery would have kept investors out until Q2 1983

### Henry Kaufman and the Bond Market Inflection

- **Kaufman ("Dr. Doom")** — Salomon Brothers credit analyst, pre-eminent
  interest-rate forecaster, renowned for pessimism
- Returned from European vacation 17 August, reviewed data, concluded
  a "significant interest rate decline lay ahead":
  - Economy stalling → moderating inflation
  - Financial blockages + international competition → balance sheet repair
  - Financial institutions no longer in aggressive lending mode
  - Huge burden of international debt restricting lending

> 'I concluded that a significant interest rate decline lay ahead.'
> — Henry Kaufman, autobiography

- His bullish forecast triggered the biggest one-day DJIA rally ever recorded
- The **fiscal deficit consensus** proved wrong again: 1982 deficit was
  3.9% of GDP (highest since WWII); by 1985 it reached 5.9% of GDP
  (surpassing Roosevelt's peacetime peaks) — yet rates fell and economy recovered
- Senate budget resolution (June 1982) projected $103.9B deficit for FY1983;
  actual deficit was **$208 billion** — fiscal deterioration continued and
  yet the bond rally did not reverse
- Parallel to 1932: gross fiscal deterioration didn't prevent strongest
  economic growth in US history or a bull market in equities

### Bonds and the Bear (Section)

- **Bond bear market in its fifth decade ended October 1981**
- Long-term Treasury yield: 2.03% (April 1946) → **15.1%** (first week
  of October 1981) — a 35-year bear market in bonds
- Bond market was unmoved by falling inflation or declining commodity prices:
  - CPI peaked March 1980 at 14.6%, fell to 11.0% by September
  - CRB futures index peaked November 1980, declined 20% by September 1981
- Key bond market fears: very high short-term rates under money-supply
  targeting (Fed funds hit 20% in early summer 1981) and fiscal concerns
  under supply-side White House + Democrat Congress
- From early October 1981 to end of July 1982: long-term govt bond yield
  declined **~200bp to 13.1%**
- Real yield on govt bonds rose from 4.4% (September 1981) to **7.4%**
  (July 1982) — bond investors still sceptical despite nominal yield decline
- **Dow Theory** again provided useful (if lagging) signal: "buy" signal
  seen in October 1982 — by that point DJIA had already risen ~30%,
  but still a small portion of the full 1982-2000 bull market return

<!-- pp. 421-439 -->

## End of Chapter 8 (1982 Bear Bottom) — Closing Arguments

### Bond Market Rally: Fear, Not Fed Policy

- The *WSJ* cited corporate bankruptcy epidemic, US Treasury borrowing needs,
  and Drysdale Government Securities default as factors keeping real yields high
- **William H. Gross** (pension fund manager, **Pacific Investment Management**),
  June 15: "The system has been undergoing an extensive period of pressure,
  and that can lead to accidents. It's better to be safe at times like this."
- **Henry Kaufman**'s bullish bond call (Aug 17) had impact — but primarily
  because it was predicated on *further* economic deterioration, not recovery
- Global capital fled to US bonds and gold due to Mexico crisis fears and
  rumors of Argentine problems — a **flight-to-safety** dynamic
- The real bond rally required **clear signs of financial distress** — only then
  did the market accept that short-term rates would not surge again
- Fiscal deficits did NOT prevent interest rate declines once fear took hold

### The Ironic Timing of 1982

- **Government bond market technically bottomed September 1981**, but the major
  rally in government bond prices did not begin until **July 1982** — when the
  Fed abandoned **money supply growth targeting**
- Irony: FOMC feared bond markets would punish them for abandoning monetary
  targets; instead, bond investors ignored the Fed shift entirely and were
  driven into government bonds by fear of financial collapse
- **Fear factor** swamped anti-inflation credibility concerns and fiscal
  profligacy fears — a crucial lesson about what actually drives bond markets

### Corporate Bond Sequence (1982)

- Pattern confirmed again: **government bonds → corporate bonds → equities**
  (same as 1921 and 1932; 1949 was distorted by Fed yield-cap policy)
- Long-term US Treasury bottomed **first week of October 1981**
- **Moody's Baa corporate bond index** yield did not peak until **mid-February 1982**
  (17.3%); by mid-July had only fallen to 16.8%
- **Baa yield premium over Treasuries** peaked November 1982 — *after* the
  major bull market in both corporate and government bonds had begun
- Investors waiting to buy equities until Baa yield premium peaked were already
  well past the equity bottom — a costly tactical error
- Commodity price stabilization → corporate bond premium decline (same
  relationship as 1921 and 1932, even in an inflationary rather than
  deflationary context)

> "Suffice to say, the indicators that signalled the bottom of the bear market
> in 1921, 1932 and 1949 worked again in 1982. This is particularly encouraging
> for investors seeking patterns." — Napier

---

## Conclusions

> *Exit, pursued by a bear.*
> — William Shakespeare, *The Winter's Tale*

> *Perhaps surprisingly, the same indicators that helped identify the end of
> the bear market in 1921, 1932 and 1949 worked again in 1982. The similarities
> between all four bear-market bottoms are particularly intriguing when one
> considers the huge changes to the institutional framework over the period.*
> — Napier

- Napier calls the indicator set **"Einstein's questions"** — the right
  questions to ask, requiring better-than-average answers to profit

---

## Conclusions: Strategic

### Valuation at Bear-Market Bottoms

- **q ratio** fell below **0.3x** at all four bear-market bottoms — the most
  reliable single valuation indicator
- **Cyclically adjusted PE** range at bottoms: 4.7x (1932) to 11.7x (1949);
  wide enough to be less useful as a precise signal
- Using inflation-adjusted earnings still gives a wide range: 5.2x to 9.1x
- **Equities become cheap slowly** — average nine years from peak q to trough
  (14 years excluding the 1929-32 outlier)
- US equity market reached highest-ever valuations in **March 2000**; history
  suggests slow multi-year grind to undervaluation follows
- Real GDP expanded ~52% and nominal GDP ~285% on average across the three
  long bear markets (ex-1929-32) — bear markets occur during expansion, not
  depression (except 1929-32)
- Inflation-adjusted earnings growth ranged from **-67% to +28%** across the
  four bottoms; nominal earnings -67% to +119% — enormous variance

### Price Disturbance as Catalyst

- A **material disturbance to the general price level** is required to push
  equities to cheap levels in all four cases:
  - 1921, 1949, 1982: high inflation followed by deflation (commodity-only
    in 1982)
  - 1932: no initial inflation, but severe deflation
- Price disturbance creates uncertainty about both future earnings and the
  opportunity cost of holding bonds — compresses equity valuations

### Commodity Prices as Leading Signal

- All four bear-market bottoms occurred during **economic recession**
- **Return of price stability** (especially commodity prices) signals the
  bottom — stabilizing commodities augur more general price stability ahead
- **Copper** specifically has been the most accurate commodity signal for
  improving equity prices
- To assess whether price stability is sustainable: look for low inventories,
  rising demand at lower prices, producers selling below cost

### Government Bond Behavior

- Government bond sell-off accompanies at least part of every bear market
- Exception nuance: 1929-32 saw bonds *rally* September 1929 to June 1931,
  before the sell-off began (lasting until January 1932)
- Even in the two deflationary bears (1921, 1932) there was some government
  bond sell-off

---

## Conclusions: Tactical

### Lead Times from Bond Bottom to Equity Bottom

| Year | Govt Bond Lead | DJIA Decline During Lag |
|------|----------------|------------------------|
| 1921 | 14 months      | 23%                    |
| 1932 | 7 months       | 46%                    |
| 1949 | 9 months       | 14%                    |
| 1982 | 11 months      | 6%                     |

- **A recovery in government bond prices precedes equity recovery** in all cases
- Corporate bond recovery leads equities by: 2 months (1921), 1 month (1932),
  5 months (1982); 15-17 months (1949, distorted by post-war controls)

### Fed Rate Cuts

- In the three long bear markets (ex-1929-32), **Fed rate cuts preceded equity
  bottoms** by ~3 months (1921, 1949) and 11 months (1982)
- DJIA decline during each lag was less than 20% in all three cases
- 1929-32 exception: Fed cut November 1929 while bear was still in infancy —
  rate cuts alone don't signal a bottom

### Additional Tactical Signals

- **Auto sector recovery** precedes equity market recovery
- **Bear-market bottoms characterized by good economic news being ignored** —
  bulls bang the drum but prices fall anyway
- **Worsening fiscal position** will be blamed for preventing recovery; these
  warnings will be wrong
- **Corporate earnings declines continue well past the equity bottom** — do not
  wait for earnings recovery to buy
- Bottom preceded by **market declining on high volume, rising on low volume**;
  final slump on very low volume; confirmation of new bull = rising volume at
  higher prices after first rebound
- **Short interest reaches peak at the bottom** and rises further in the first
  weeks of the new bull market
- **Dow Theory** works to signal a buy for equities

> "Just as the possession of fur does not, of itself, permit the identification
> of an animal as a bear, the possession of any one of the features above should
> not be considered as constituting positive identification of its financial
> equivalent. Our list is the financial equivalent of Einstein's questions."
> — Napier

---

## Conclusions: Then and Now (2005 Assessment)

- Written in 2005; Napier applies the framework to the then-current bear market
  (begun 2000)
- **q ratio** at end of 1999: all-time high of 2.9x (geometric mean);
  cyclically adjusted PE was **170% above** its 1881-2005 average — extreme by
  any historical standard
- **From June 2005 levels**: cyclically adjusted PE would need to fall 40% to
  reach long-term average; 60-84% to reach prior bear-bottom levels
- **q ratio** in June 2005 was still **44% above fair value**; to match prior
  bear bottoms, would need to fall another 67% from there
- No general price disturbance had yet occurred (as of 2005)
- No meaningful bond market sell-off; no recession; no Fed rate cuts
- Napier's conclusion: **DJIA likely to decline at least 60%, possibly 80%+**
  before the bear ends
- Predicted bear market end: "sometime after 2009, though probably nearer
  to 2014" — written in 2005, remarkably prescient about the GFC arc

> "If, as Milton Friedman asserts, inflation 'is everywhere and at all times a
> monetary phenomenon', the next general price disturbance is likely to be
> inflationary, given the current institutional framework." — Napier

